<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rochester's pro soccer team aiming to build 20,000-seat stadium  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The minor-league darlings of U.S. soccer are
gearing up to build a 20,000-seat stadium.
<P>
	   The Rochester Raging Rhinos, winners of the nation's top soccer cup last
fall, promised Tuesday to contribute $25.7 million in private funds toward
building a $44.1 million, soccer-specific stadium by 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   The project's success hinges on the ability of the A-League team's three
co-owners to persuade state, county and city governments to come up with the
balance - $18.4 million.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're willing to risk all of our money to make this a done deal," said
Rhinos president Frank DuRoss. "We need to convince the government officials
that this project has legs, that it's a good investment in the community."
</P>
<P>
	   The Rhinos are by far the biggest draw in professional soccer's second
division A-League with an average attendance of 11,551 last season. They are
campaigning to gain a slot in Major League Soccer, which is aiming to expand
from 12 to 14 teams by next year.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, the stumbling block has been the Rhinos' home ground. Since their
inaugural year in 1996, they have played at 12,052-seat Frontier Field, a
seashell-shaped stadium built that year for minor league baseball's Rochester
Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
	   For the MLS to invite them aboard, the Rhinos first need to build a
soccer-specific stadium with a capacity of at least 20,000 that would triple
their market to about 3 million by drawing fans from Syracuse, 75 miles east of
here, and Buffalo, 60 miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
	   Team officials unveiled architectural designs for a rectangular stadium they
expect to start building this summer to open for the 2001 season. They said they
have honed in on four possible sites - one near Frontier Field and the others in
the Rochester suburbs.
</P>
<P>
	   The stadium would be designed to play host to other sports, such as
lacrosse, field hockey, football and rugby, and also be used to stage music
concerts and various community events.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed stadium would be used for A-League competition if the Rhinos
don't win a place in the MLS, but DuRoss said the team's survival is at stake.
</P>
<P>
	   Without government help, he said, "we'd have to reevaluate where we're at
and how we could survive in this marketplace without our own stadium."
</P>
<P>
	   By contrast, success on the field has seemed easy to come by. The 1998
A-League champion Rhinos toppled the Colorado Rapids 2-0 in September to become
the first A-League team to win the U.S. Open Cup since MLS teams entered the
premier cup competition in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
