<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki calls for a $77 billion state budget for fiscal 2000-01  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Almost everyone who matters politically in Albany
said they liked something they heard in Gov. George Pataki's 2000-01 state
budget proposal.
<P>
	   In fact, Democrats and Republicans alike said Tuesday they either thought of
the ideas first or have been promoting them for years.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican leader in the state Assembly, John Faso, said Pataki's
proposed elimination of the gross receipts tax on utility bills, the governor's
debt reform ideas and his economic development plans "closely mirror" those of
his GOP Assembly members.
</P>
<P>
	   Ditto, said the leader of the Democrats in the state Senate, Martin Connor.
He said the gross receipts tax rescinder and economic development proposals
targeted to upstate New York are things Senate Democrats have been talking about
for years.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, praised the Republican governor
for no longer talking about cuts in areas the Democrats have defended in
Pataki's past budgets - tuition at state colleges, for instance, and Medicaid
programs that aid hospitals and poor families. Silver also said the Pataki
proposals to rein in state debt, including a provision to no longer allow
borrowing not approved beforehand by voters, are things his chamber has also
advocated.
</P>
<P>
	   And the Republican leader of the state Senate, Joseph Bruno, said debt
reform, the gross receipts tax rescinder and upstate economic development
programs have all been talked about for years in his house.
</P>
<P>
	   A nearly $77 billion budget would be 5.5 percent larger than the current
fiscal-year spending plan. Pataki conceded that would be more than the projected
inflation rate for the next year, but he said the numbers are skewed by the
inclusion of $2 billion in rebates due property taxpayers in fiscal 2000-01
under the "STAR" program.
</P>
<P>
	   Those rebates are classified as state spending when they really are not,
Pataki argued.
</P>
<P>
	   A better gauge, the governor said, is the proposed size of the state's
general fund - $37.9 billion. That fund is comprised of money generated through
state taxes and fees. Pataki said it would grow by only 2.3 percent in fiscal
2000-01, or by less than the expected inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have a budget this year which I think is just a great budget," Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The anti-tax group Change-New York wasn't so sure. It said by starting
budget negotiations with the Legislature at a "disturbingly high" platform of a
5.5 percent budget increase, lawmakers are essentially being invited to go
significantly higher in the budget they finally adopt.
</P>
<P>
	   "Overall, this proposed budget is a major disappointment," Change-New York
President Tom Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic state Comptroller H. Carl McCall quibbled with Pataki's numbers.
He said the governor was putting "off budget" some funds which will probably be
spent, meaning that the governor's reckoning that general fund spending would be
below the inflation rate is an illusion.
</P>
<P>
	   "I awaited this budget with high expectation," said McCall, who may end up
challenging Pataki for the governorship in 2002. "In his State of the State
address, the governor made encouraging statements on his plans to focus on
improving education in our state. But I'm disappointed that his budget actions
don't live up to his State of the State words."
</P>
<P>
	   Silver argued that by not rolling over unspent school dollars into the next
state budget from the current fiscal year, Pataki would actually spend nearly
$900 million less on education in fiscal 2000-01, not $355 million more as the
governor said he was proposing.
</P>
<P>
	   "The governor has chosen to break faith with local school districts by
cutting funding and reneging on commitments he's already made," the chairman of
the Assembly's education committee, Manhattan Democrat Steven Sanders, said.
</P>
<P>
	   State School Boards Association Executive Director Timothy Kremer called a
$355 million funding increase a "drop in the bucket" compared to the commitments
districts must meet.
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Pataki received mostly praise from what was a critical
quarter during his previous five budgets as governor - higher education.
</P>
<P>
	   He proposed spending $75 million more on the State University of New York
and $19 million on the City University of New York systems and did not advocate
any tuition increases in the 2000-01 academic year.
</P>
<P>
	   "A huge boost for the State University," said SUNY Chancellor Robert King,
who was Pataki's budget director until late last month. CUNY Chancellor Matthew
Goldstein said he was "encouraged and pleased" by Pataki's proposal. Goldstein
was nominated by Pataki to the SUNY chancellorship last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the next several weeks, legislators and their analysts will pore over
Pataki's proposal and hold budget hearings before each chamber will formulate
changes. It has been 16 years since lawmakers and the governor completed passage
on a new state budget prior to the April 1 deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
