<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The chances suddenly aren't so bad for an on-time budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's 15-year-old streak of failing to pass the
state budget on time might end this year, politicians predicted after seeing
Gov. George Pataki's latest budget proposal.
<P>
	   "All the pieces of the puzzle are in the right place to pass an on-time
budget this year," said Republican state Sen. Nicholas Spano of Westchester
County.
</P>
<P>
	   The main culprits behind the most recent five overdue budgets - Pataki,
Republican Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and Democratic Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver - all insist that this is the year for a change.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, the budget wasn't finished until Aug. 4, only hours before it
would have become the latest budget in state history. State budget are supposed
to be enacted by April 1, the beginning of the state's fiscal year, but there
are no penalties for the Legislature and governor for failing to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Some people don't think the leaders will succeed in being on time in 2000,
either.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I had a ranch, I wouldn't bet it," said Blair Horner of the New York
Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
	   But the politicians all said Tuesday there's reason for real hope this year.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you look at this budget, I think it's a very sound budget and I would
hope the Legislature would not feel the need to make any dramatic changes,"
Pataki said. "And if that's the case, there's no reason why the changes that
they produce shouldn't and can't be made in an open and prompt manner and I
would hope that will be the case."
</P>
<P>
	   When reminded by a reporter that he says that every year, Pataki added: "I
feel more so this year."
</P>
<P>
	   Silver and Bruno did agree that Pataki has given them a better place to
start from with his budget proposal Tuesday. They say it will allow them to come
to an end product faster.
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe it should," Silver said. "It certainly has a better foundation."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki proposed Tuesday that New York spend nearly $78 billion in its next
fiscal year, 5.5 percent more than the current fiscal-year spending plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno agreed with Silver's assessment of an on-time budget's chances.
</P>
<P>
	   "The governor has established a pretty good base," Bruno said. "I think this
year will be better than other years."
</P>
<P>
	   Of course, this is also an election year for the Senate and the Assembly.
The quicker they finish the budget, the quicker they get home and start raising
money full-time and campaigning for re-election.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, the budget was finished on April 14 in 1998, the last time the
Legislature was up for re-election. Legislators have never gone past July 13
without a budget in an election year.
</P>
<P>
	   "And this is a uniquely important election," Horner pointed out.
</P>
<P>
	   The 2002 Legislature will decide how to redistrict the state after the 2000
Census and the advantage in redistricting goes to the party that controls the
Assembly and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Legislature that's in power in 2002 will be the Legislature who will be
in power for the next 10 years," Horner said. "They'll want to get out of Dodge
and get home as soon as they can."
</P>
<P>
	   The budget process has not changed. Bruno last week suggested ending the
"three men in a room" approach under which Pataki, Silver and Bruno meet
privately and agree to key aspects of budgets. Pataki and Silver would not
immediately commit to it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of going home for good for the rest of the year after finishing the
budget last August, the Legislature returned to Albany several times to hash out
the Health Care Reform Act, New York's one-of-a-kind subsidy system to fund
cash-shy aspects of the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the HCRA deal, Pataki and the Legislature agreed to a three-year
continuation of Medicaid cost containment programs worth about $1 billion a
year. Cost containment has been at the center of budget battles for years.
</P>
<P>
	   "It think that was a very, very important part of HCRA," Pataki said. "It
doesn't just make this year's budget process easier, it makes the budget process
easier for the next three years because that, last year, was probably the most
difficult issue, whether or not to continue the cost containment and that is now
resolved."
</P>
<P>
	   However, it won't be completely smooth sailing this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno and Silver both criticized Pataki's education proposal. Pataki called
for $12.9 billion for education, a record amount. But Silver and Bruno both want
more, pointing out that the governor is not seeking to continue funding certain
programs.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the things that were left out included class-size reductions,
pre-kindergarten programs and increased teacher salaries, Silver said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think the members of the conference will take those education cuts
lightly," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno was more charitable. "Now is not the time to cut back on our support
for secondary education," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
