<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugger makes high wire escape in pizza deliverer's outfit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In a chase straight out of the movies, a quick-thinking
mugger being pursued by police ran into an office building and leaped from a
19th-floor window to the building next door, where he stole a pizza deliverer's
hat and apron and calmly vanished out the front door.
<P>
	   It all started when police responded to a call about a street robbery at
59th Street and Park Avenue around 11:45 a.m. Tuesday. Officers chased the
suspect to East 53rd Street, where he ran into the Banco Santander office
building.
</P>
<P>
	   As if following a scriptwriter's cue, the elevator doors opened; the suspect
jumped in; the doors closed. He arrived at the 19th floor a step ahead of
police, who had to take another elevator.
</P>
<P>
	   Before police could catch up with him, he had darted through an office and
jumped out the window.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses thought he had plummeted to his death. But instead he landed on a
window air conditioner at the office building next door.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear how many floors the man fell before grabbing the air
conditioner, but the space between the buildings is about 10 feet wide, and a
few floors below where he jumped, the two structures join.
</P>
<P>
	   Police didn't know right away that he had landed unscathed and crawled
through the window into the neighboring building.
</P>
<P>
	   There, he encountered a delivery man from the Checkerboard Gourmet deli. The
thief took the delivery man's hat and apron and put them on in the elevator; he
emerged in the lobby disguised as the delivery man and sauntered out of the
building.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't think anything of it. He just looked like your ordinary delivery
guy," said a security guard at the second building. "We thought all the action
was next door."
</P>
<P>
	   Afterward, the scene at Checkerboard was business as usual as the workers
coped with the lunch rush.
</P>
<P>
	   "The guy grabbed my delivery man's hat and apron. He scared the hell out of
him," said Checkerboard manager Seth Novak.
</P>
<P>
	   The delivery man, who would only give his name as Salvador, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Deputy Inspector Donald Feser admitted: "This was not your usual
occurrence."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
