<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal's birthday dinner raises $4 million for charity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Cardinal John O'Connor's birthday party is turning into
a major fund-raiser for the New York Archdiocese.
<P>
	   The dinner, scheduled for Saturday, when the cardinal turns 80, has raised
$4 million for education and other Catholic charities.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's been one of his top priorities, to help preserve Catholic education
in the archdiocese, so part of the money from this will go to that," said
O'Connor's spokesman Joe Zwilling.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 1,400 and 1,500 people are expected to attend the event at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel honoring the cardinal's legacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Tickets were $1,000 a head but many of the guests made additional
contributions, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
	   Proceeds from the dinner will also be used to fund a seminary position named
for the cardinal. The John Cardinal O'Connor Distinguished Chair in Hebrew
Studies at St. Joseph's Seminary in Yonkers, is designed to educate future
priests about the shared scriptural heritage of Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
	   Tributes to the cardinal and a video about his legacy are planned for the
dinner.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the clergy expected to attend are seven cardinals, six archbishops and
a number of bishops from around the country. The guest list includes some of the
men who have been mentioned as possible successors to O'Connor, including
Archbishop Justin Rigali of St. Louis; Archbishop Edwin O'Brien, who heads the
archdiocese for the U.S. military; and Bishop Henry Mansell of Buffalo, a former
top aide to O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the clergy are expected to be present when O'Connor presides over
Mass the next day at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
	   The cardinal had a brain tumor removed in September and has missed a number
of public appearances, including Masses, since then.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor has hinted that he expects to be replaced soon by the pope. He
offered his resignation on his 75th birthday as the church requires but it was
not accepted then. Cardinals lose their power to vote for a new pope when they
turn 80, which has led to speculation that his resignation could be accepted
soon.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor is the oldest active bishop in the United States and as leader of
the New York Archdiocese's flock of 2.4 million, he is regarded as one of the
most powerful Catholics in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
