<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court balks at city lawyer's 'Sensation' claims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - An appeals judge showed skepticism toward the city's
plans to kick the Brooklyn Museum out of its building because it refused to
withdraw the controversial "Sensation" art exhibit the city found inappropriate
for children.
<P>
	   "Is every book in the New York Public Library appropriate for school
children?" Justice Jon Newman asked city lawyer Leonard Koerner. "Is the library
next?"
</P>
<P>
	   Koerner said the city would not attack the library for the content of its
books but would consider action if it housed an exhibit celebrating the Klu Klux
Klan or homophobia.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchange occurred during arguments Tuesday before the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals stemming from the holiday controversy that featured Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani in another clash with advocates of the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   Repeatedly in recent years, the mayor has fought in federal court over the
issue of how strictly the city can regulate demonstrations and other speech
governed by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   This time, Koerner sought to distance the city from the First Amendment
issues at stake.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not a First Amendment case, your honor," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It isn't?" snapped Justice John Walker.
</P>
<P>
	   Newman called the statement possibly "the most extraordinary thing" he had
heard from the city.
</P>
<P>
	   The judges reserved decision. They must consider whether to uphold a federal
judge's ruling in Brooklyn that found the city's decision to freeze its $7.2
million annual contribution to the museum violated the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   They also must determine whether the case belongs in state court rather than
federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani vowed to cut off the funding after a controversy erupted over the
exhibit, titled "Sensation: Young British Artists From the Saatchi Collection."
</P>
<P>
	   Various groups had protested to the mayor about a Chris Ofili painting, "The
Holy Virgin Mary," which depicts Mary with African features and includes a
shellacked clump of elephant dung and magazine cutouts of female genitalia.
</P>
<P>
	   The show opened on Oct. 2 and closed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Koerner had barely begun delivering his argument before the appeals court
panel when he faced a barrage of fast questions from Newman.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge asked why the city had begun what amounted to eviction
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   "Is it really the city's position that the Brooklyn Museum should take its
entire collection out of that building now?" Newman asked. "Your words and your
complaint say so, but I'm not sure you mean it."
</P>
<P>
	   Koerner conceded that the city would like to negotiate a solution with the
museum but only after a judge had found in its favor. At the very least, he
said, the city would like to stop funding the museum.
</P>
<P>
	   Museum attorney Floyd Abrams said the city wanted only to punish the museum
for its exhibit, ruining a 100-year relationship that included numerous
accolades from the city heralding the museum as one of the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Abrams said even the notion that an eviction would force the museum to move
to California or to New Jersey was "so bizarre that it is a basis for
considering that this whole thing is nothing more than an effort to punish."
</P>
<P>
	   "We funded this museum," Koerner said. "Let's assume that it celebrated the
Klu Klux Klan or the Holocaust or homophobia. I don't think the court would be
saying we'd be required to fund it."
</P>
<P>
	   "Don't be so sure," Newman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
