<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 44.98; Nasdaq Down 67.87  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as investors
worried that reports due for release later this week will indicate that the
economy is growing fast enough to warrant more interest-rate increases by the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 44.98 at 11,556.06
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 7.82 at 1,430.74, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 67.87 at
3,853.32.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks struggled as the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.69
percent, the highest level since Sept. 11, 1997. Bond investors have been highly
sensitive to growing fears that the Fed will raise interest rates at its next
meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, and may impose further hikes later in the year to keep
inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as
it becomes more expensive to borrow money. Also, rising bond yields can attract
investors away from stocks by offering lucrative, stable returns.
</P>
<P>
	   The next barometers of economic growth will come on Thursday, when the
government reports on producer prices for December, as well as retail sales. On
Friday, the Labor Department will release its Consumer Price Index, a widely
watched gauge of inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks were mostly lower today. Yahoo! fell 24 5/8 to 372 3/4 a
day after posting a better-than-expected profit report. Yahoo! said late Tuesday
it earned 19 cents per share in the fourth quarter, above Wall Street's
prediction of 15 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   But company officials warned in a conference call that Yahoo!'s strong
revenue growth is not sustainable, and that prompted investors to sell shares
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Microsoft fell 2 7/8 to 106 1/2 and Oracle fell 3 9/16 to 108 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 126.63 million shares, behind Monday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.53 to 490.08.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.0 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 0.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down .01 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
