<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 70.73; Nasdaq Down 27.71  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as investors continued moving money
away from pricey technology shares and toward blue-chip industrials that perform
well when the economy is growing.
</P>
<P>
	   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
70.73 at 11,581.81, above its closing record of 11,572.20 set on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 1.10 at 1,437.46, and the Nasdaq composite index was off 27.71 at 3,893.48.
</P>
<P>
	   Yahoo! led a decline in technology stocks. Shares of the Internet service
provider fell 18 49/64 to 378 39/64 a day after the company posted a
better-than-expected profit report. Yahoo! said late Tuesday it earned 19 cents
per share in the fourth quarter, above Wall Street's prediction of 15 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
	   But company officials warned in a conference call that Yahoo!'s strong
revenue growth is not sustainable, and that prompted investors to sell shares
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Microsoft fell 2 13/16 to 106 9/16 and Oracle fell 2 3/8 to 110.
</P>
<P>
	   With technology stocks slipping, investors once again sought out relative
bargains in the industrial and consumer goods sectors. After lagging behind the
high-flying Nasdaq in the second half of 1999, the Dow Jones industrials have
outstripped other market measures so far this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, 3M rose 2 1/8 to 102 5/8, and Merck rose 1 11/16 to 74 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   The broadening of the market has created a healthier environment for
investors, many analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
	   "Breadth has improved dramatically this year," said Gregory Nie, technical
analyst at First Union Securities in Chicago. "This market has a good enough,
healthy enough underpinning to support a real rally."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, stocks may struggle in the next two sessions as investors await the
next round of economic indicators. On Thursday, the government will report on
producer prices for December, as well as retail sales. On Friday, the Labor
Department will release its Consumer Price Index, a widely watched gauge of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports should offer some indication of the Federal Reserve's next move
on interest rates. Many analysts believe the Fed will raise rates at its next
meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, and may impose further hikes later in the year to keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as
it becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond investors, highly sensitive to inflation and short-term rate changes,
today sent the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.68 percent from 6.67
percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 303.61 million shares, behind Monday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.52 to 489.09.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
