<DOCNO> APW20000112.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Mrs. Pickle  </HEADLINE>
    By STEVE BRISENDINE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MISSION, Kan. (AP) -- Mrs. Pickle is crazy for cornichons, ga-ga for
gherkins, daft for dills.
</P>
<P>
	   The title character in "Picky Mrs. Pickle," illustrator Christine
Schneider's first foray into children's writing, is a woman who knows what she
likes.
</P>
<P>
	   She'll only eat pickles and pickle-flavored foods -- like pickle parfait ice
cream and pickle soup.
</P>
<P>
	   Clothing? It's got to be green. Ditto her furnishings and even the sweaters
her poodle, Dill, wears. And when she goes out, it's with a spritz of "Eau de
Pickle No. 19" behind her ears.
</P>
<P>
	   The inspiration for parts of that character is as close as the nearest
mirror, Schneider said -- although she doesn't own any green shoes.
</P>
<P>
	   "Pickles are definitely a love of mine," she said. "And I have a tendency
sometimes to be a bit picky. So some of that does come from me. But otherwise
she was a character that just kind of sprung from the story."
</P>
<P>
	   As anyone knows, an object in a rut remains in a rut unless acted upon by an
outside force. In this case, it's Mrs. Pickle's youngest niece, Sophie Claire.
</P>
<P>
	   All the other relatives are resigned to Mrs. Pickle's carved-in-cucumber
ways, but not Sophie Claire. Each week, when the two stop by Igor's Ice Cream
Stand, she urges her aunt to try something new -- tomato, perhaps, or eggplant.
</P>
<P>
	   If that produces a nose-wrinkling reaction from a young audience hearing the
book, Schneider said, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I'm doing a reading for kids, I try to provoke that as much as I can,"
she said. "I'll even throw in an extra 'ewwwwwwwwww."'
</P>
<P>
	   The book, while written for children, contains a few in-jokes that older
readers will recognize. For example, Mrs. Pickle's favorite brand is "Pete's" --
from the tongue twister about Peter Piper.
</P>
<P>
	   There are a few puns that are a little bit older humor," Schneider said.
"That gives the parents something to enjoy when they're reading the book. But
you'd be surprised -- some of the kids get that, too."
</P>
<P>
	   And often, people see their friends or family members in either Mrs. Pickle
or Sophie Claire.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's always somebody in the crowd who's extremely picky," Schneider
said. "Or people will say, 'This is perfect for my niece or my mother."'
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider, 28, graduated from the University of Kansas, where she studied
under children's illustrator Thomas B. Allen. In her first foray into children's
books, she did the illustrations for "Jeremy's Muffler," by Laura F. Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
	   But, she said, doing "Picky Mrs. Pickle" was "much more rewarding at the
end. I felt like it was one package. I could get in everything I had intended
for the book, because I could work back and forth between the story and the
pictures."
</P>
<P>
	   Even though it was her first experience writing a book, Schneider said she
still concentrated most on the illustrations.
</P>
<P>
	   "In a picture book, it's very important what the pictures do for the story,
because there aren't a lot of words," she said. "Depending on what age you're
talking about, some kids are going to rely on pictures more than words."
</P>
<P>
	   The whole process, start to finish, took about 18 months -- seemingly a long
time, until you take a look at the illustrations.
</P>
<P>
	   They're not the simple, primary-color drawings of the children's books you
read growing up. Instead, each page is saturated with rich greens (of course),
golds and purples.
</P>
<P>
	   "It takes me about 40 hours to do one illustration," Schneider said. "I was
working a job at the same time, and was doing that pretty much at night. So
that's why it took me so long."
</P>
<P>
	   Now, writing and illustrating are a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sometimes it's a little nerve-wracking, but I can't think of anything else
I'd rather be doing," she said. "It's a pretty wonderful job to have, because I
get to tell stories and draw pictures at the same time."
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider's next book is due out in fall 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm working on the revisions to the story right now," she said. "It doesn't
have a title yet, but it's basically about a magician. I think that's probably
enough to tell you right now."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1221 </TRAILER>
