<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Orders More Northwest Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ST. PAUL. Minn. (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered Northwest Airlines and
its flight attendants union to resume private negotiations, even though the
National Mediation Board has scheduled no talks.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Donovan Frank ordered the two sides to pick a private
mediator by Friday or provide him with a list of acceptable mediators.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge said he wanted to see either a tentative agreement by Feb. 4 or a
"detailed" list of issues between the two sides and ordered both sides back to
his courtroom Feb. 15-16 to present evidence.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest spokesman Jon Austin said late Tuesday that the company is aware
of the ruling, but couldn't comment further.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials with the Teamsters Local 2000 did not return phone calls seeking
comment. A spokesman for the National Mediation Board did not immediately return
a phone call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Frank said in his ruling that both the Eagan-based airline and the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters Local 2000 have "represented to the court
that they are presently more than willing to engage in good faith negotiations
in an effort to end a three-year deadlock."
</P>
<P>
	   Mediated talks between Northwest and its flight attendants have been
recessed since Dec. 7 and no talks are scheduled, but the National Mediation
Board has not declared an impasse to trigger a 30-day countdown to a strike.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest has said repeatedly since talks were recessed that it would return
to the bargaining table when summoned by the mediation board. Local 2000 had
pushed for private talks until mediated negotiations were resumed.
</P>
<P>
	   Frank granted Northwest a temporary restraining order last week to prevent
flight attendants from engaging in job actions that would harm the carrier.
</P>
<P>
	   The union of 11,000 Northwest flight attendants has been seeking a new
contract since September 1996. In late August, Local 2000 members overwhelmingly
rejected a tentative agreement that had been endorsed by union
negotiators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1252 </TRAILER>
