<DOCNO> APW20000112.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Millionaire' Back on ABC  </HEADLINE>
    By FRAZIER MOORE AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- "Nobody thought it could possibly work," Regis Philbin
began Sunday night as his ABC game show, "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire," made
its breathless return for "a brand-new century."
</P>
<P>
	   Having proved itself in August then November as more than a fly-by-night
success, "Millionaire" was now back for an eight-night marathon (continuing
tonight at 8 p.m. EST and on through Sunday) before settling into an open-ended
run of three airings per week.
</P>
<P>
	   "The eagle has landed!" crowed host Philbin, presumably departing from the
script ...
</P>
<P>
	   One day last week, "Millionaire" executive producer Michael Davies was
plotting that opening sequence. He wanted to come back with a bang. Maybe kick
off with a visual pastiche of past big winners, spiced with a bit of
we-told-you-so for the show's naysayers.
</P>
<P>
	   Plus, some purple prose to capture the phenomenon when, "night after night,
31 memorable nights, a nation sat transfixed as real Americans rode a roller
coaster of raw emotions."
</P>
<P>
	   Davies would soon sit down to write those opening lines for his host to
bring to life.
</P>
<P>
	   But he, Philbin and the entire "Millionaire" staff are also strapping
themselves in for another ride on the game-show roller coaster, this time
sharing it with Fox's copycat, "Greed," as well as Johnny-come-latelies "Winning
Lines" (CBS) and "Twenty-One" (NBC).
</P>
<P>
	   Until last Aug. 16, game shows hadn't clicked in network prime-time since
the 1950s. Then came the premiere of "Millionaire," a British-bred quiz show
that Davies, a 33-year-old former ABC exec who himself is British-born, had
talked the network into letting him import.
</P>
<P>
	   "'Millionaire' now seems like such a big, obvious, 'duh!' sort of television
program," Davies notes. "But before it went on the air, this was the most
alternative, the most pie-in-the-sky, the most unlikely-to-work idea."
</P>
<P>
	   He doesn't begrudge other producers now riding the quiz-show wave and makes
no forecasts for what effect, if any, their clones will have on "Millionaire."
</P>
<P>
	   But Davies can claim two advantages with final-answer certainty: His show
was first, and it has something that no one else's has -- talk-show veteran
Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can't say enough about how great he's been," Davies declares.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, for ratings-anemic ABC, "Millionaire" has proven to be Dr. Regis'
Audience Pick-Me-Up (recommended dosage: schedule as needed).
</P>
<P>
	   But simple Nielsen glory hardly conveys the show's impact on the national
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's been amazing to watch the show just penetrate the pop culture," Davies
says.
</P>
<P>
	   He caught his first glimpse in September on a drive through Pennsylvania.
Along the way, he happened to pick up a local newspaper, whereupon his eye fell
on a sports story that referred to a team's uncertain prospects as "the $1
million question."
</P>
<P>
	   As Davies realized, "before August, it would have read 'the $64,000
question"' -- a turn of phrase born of a game show nearly 50 years ago, updated
only now, thanks to "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire."
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Davies doesn't really consider "Millionaire" a game show.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it works in spite of being a game show," he says. "You don't ever
actually worry about the game. You just watch the drama unfold."
</P>
<P>
	   He means the drama of each contestant facing 15 successive multiple-choice
questions that, when answered correctly, mean a million-dollar payday. "I don't
think you follow the game elements," he says. "I think you follow the human
nature of it."
</P>
<P>
	   In Davies' large yet sparsely appointed office, one conspicuous element is a
bulletin board posted with different colored index cards bearing titles like
"Mastermind," "Smush" and "TFI Friday." These are project ideas to which Davies,
as an independent producer, would like to turn his attention.
</P>
<P>
	   But for the moment, "Millionaire" is too big a hit and too much work.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think any of us had any idea how tough it would be to do," he
concedes. According to the unforgiving cycle, each episode is taped just one day
before air. Then time-consuming post-production starts. "We came alarmingly
close to not delivering the show on several occasions."
</P>
<P>
	   He sighs, a little weary but clearly fired up. Then, before returning to a
staff meeting to thrash out that opening, he grapples with a million-dollar
question: What have the past few months meant to him?
</P>
<P>
	   "I've had what you might think would be the greatest feeling anyone could
have as a television producer," he replies. "But I've never had one time when I
thought, 'This is great, we've changed television.' Because we're all working
like a mother to get the next show out!"
</P>
<P>
	   That's it? Final answer? Davies reconsiders and smiles. "This is about as
good as it gets."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   SEINFELD ON 'DILBERT': You haven't seen him much in anything new since
"Seinfeld" folded a couple of seasons ago -- and you won't see him now. But
Jerry Seinfeld will be heard as the voice of an arrogant supercomputer named
Comp-U-Comp in an episode of UPN's animated-cartoon office comedy "Dilbert,"
airing next month. The program reunites Seinfeld with "Dilbert" executive
producer Larry Charles, who was supervising producer and writer on "Seinfeld."
The episode is scheduled for Feb. 22 at 9:30 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore "at" ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
