<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Higher; Gold Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major currencies in
European trading today. Gold was mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro was quoted at $1.0271 in late European trading, down from $1.0285
Tuesday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at $1.0286.
</P>
<P>
	   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday, included 105.86
Japanese yen, up from 105.66; 1.5655 Swiss francs, up from 1.5636; 1.4552
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4562.
</P>
<P>
	   The British pound was quoted at $1.6458, down from $1.6468.
</P>
<P>
	   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 105.93 yen, and the pound
was worth $1.6455.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro rates, the dollar is
worth 1.9035 German marks, up from 1.9005; 6.3853 French francs, up from 6.3741;
2.1451 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1416; 1,884.81 Italian lire, up from 1,881.70.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold closed in London at $281.20 bid per troy ounce, down from $282.90 on
Tuesday. In Zurich the bid price was $282.15, up from $282.00. Gold rose $0.60
in Hong Kong to close at $282.85.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver closed in London at $5.12 bid per troy ounce, down from $5.16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
