<DOCNO> APW20000112.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   The financially troubled drug store company said Tuesday it will delay
filing any further quarterly financial statements until July 11 and pushed back
the date for the sale of its PCS Health Systems unit. Today, Lehman Brothers
said the New York Stock Exchange may delist the stock, but exchange officials
later said they had made no decision to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong expects to report fourth-quarter earnings of 90 cents to 95 cents
a share, below analysts' consensus estimate of $1.21 a share. Armstrong cited
weakness in European sales and rising lumber prices in its hardwood flooring
division.
</P>
<P>
	   Merrill Lynch raised its rating on Avista stock to "buy" from "accumulate,"
labeling the small-cap utility company "2000's hidden gem." Merrill cited the
perceived potential in three of Avista's units, including an Internet-based
utility aggregation business.
</P>
<P>
	   Roche Holdings AG, which owns a majority stake in Genentech, has renewed
plans to raise $1 billion by selling bonds that are exchangeable into Genentech
stock. Genentech said it expects about 2.5 percent of its stock to be involved
in the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The company earned 19 cents per share in the fourth quarter, easily beating
analysts' estimates of 15 cents per share. Yahoo! also announced a 2-for-1 stock
split. But company officials warned investors that Yahoo!'s revenue growth is
not sustainable.
</P>
<P>
	   The sneaker maker expects to report fourth-quarter earnings in the range of
40 cents to 50 cents per share. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 55 cents
per share. KSwiss said several footwear and sporting goods retailers delayed
orders during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said its results for the quarter ended Dec. 31 are likely to
fall below analysts' expectations due in part to concerns about the Year 2000
computer bug. Santa Cruz said many customers delayed purchases of its server
operating systems and network computing software.
</P>
<P>
	   The company has entered discussions with Red Hat Inc. to sell Red Hat's
Linux operating system to the federal government. Government Technology said it
plans to add Linux products and services to at least two of its government-wide
acquisition contracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
