<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Jan. 16-22:
</P>
<P>
	   65 years ago: Gary Cooper and Franchot Tone starred in "The Lives of a
Bengal Lancer," a film made from the novel by Major Francis Yeats-Brown.
</P>
<P>
	   And Freddie Bartholomew, W.C. Fields, Lionel Barrymore and Maureen
O'Sullivan starred in "David Copperfield," directed by George Cukor.
</P>
<P>
	   45 years ago: "The Bridges at Toko-Ri," starring William Holden and Grace
Kelly, opened at Radio City Music Hall in New York and the Hollywood Paramount.
</P>
<P>
	   40 years ago: Singer Sam Cooke signed with RCA Records.
</P>
<P>
	   And some 20 million viewers in Britain saw singer Cliff Richard's television
performance on "Sunday Night at the London Palladium."
</P>
<P>
	   30 years ago: The Doors recorded their "Absolutely Live" double album at the
Felt Forum in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   25 years ago: "Baretta" premiered on ABC-TV. Robert Blake starred as
Detective Tony Baretta. The show ran until June 1978.
</P>
<P>
	   15 years ago: Actor Leonard Nimoy, who roamed the galaxies as the
emotionless Mr. Spock of the "Star Trek" television series and movies, was
honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
	   And the Statlers' love song "Elizabeth" was selected by music fans as the
top country tune of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   10 years ago: The Kinks, Simon and Garfunkel and The Who were among the
artists inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. After the ceremony, about
60 musicians, including Bruce Springsteen, Roger Daltry and Peter Townshend of
The Who, hopped up on stage for a jam session.
</P>
<P>
	   Quincy Jones was awarded the French Legion of Honor for his musical
contribution as a trumpeter, composer, arranger and record producer. Jones was
praised as "a man who reconciles the rhythms of rock, jazz and bop."
</P>
<P>
	   And the first MTV "Unplugged" special was aired. The show featured British
rockers Squeeze.
</P>
<P>
	   One year ago: Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson made their debut as co-hosts
of "Good Morning America" on ABC-TV. "We want to in effect take this program
back to the future," said Gibson, who had recently ended an 11-year "GMA"
stretch. He also spoke of his surprise at the unexpected assignment: "A few
weeks ago, you'd have knocked me over with a feather if you'd told me we were
going to be here."
</P>
<P>
	   Spoken 10 years ago:
</P>
<P>
	   "Seeing everybody makes me realize rock 'n' roll has become respectable.
What a bummer." -- Singer Ray Davies, at induction ceremonies for the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
	   Spoken five years ago:
</P>
<P>
	   "My age is the best time there is to be a woman. It used to be middle-aged
women just seemed to vanish. Look at me." -- Cybill Shepherd, 44, whose new CBS
sitcom "Cybill" was loosely modeled on her real life.
</P>
<P>
	   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
	   "Scully is a change of pace, I guess. There's something about her
intelligence that mixes with the male fantasy of 'What does she really look like
underneath those tailored suits?"' -- Gillian Anderson, on her character in "The
X-Files."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
