<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bach Rocks but Without Skid Row  </HEADLINE>
    By GERARD O'LEARY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP)-- Sebastian Bach, former lead singer for the dismantled heavy
metal band Skid Row, leans back in his chair and reflects on what led to the
breakup.
</P>
<P>
	   "They basically kicked me out," Bach said. "We started with the same idea of
what we wanted in a band, but they started looking to other bands for
inspiration and that's like the enemy to me."
</P>
<P>
	   Skid Row was synonymous with '80s heavy metal and was considered the cream
of the crop. The band's self-titled, metal-blasting debut album, released in
1989, eventually sold more than five million copies in the United States. That
same year, Skid Row opened for Bon Jovi and Motley Crue, touring across the
country and also taking part in the historic Moscow Music Peace Festival at
Lenin Stadium.
</P>
<P>
	   The band's 1991 album "Slave to the Grind" debuted at the No. 1 spot on the
U.S. chart, avoiding the dreaded "sophomore jinx."
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought we were going to be like AC/DC, Aerosmith and Kiss; I never
wanted to break up that band," Bach, 31, said. "We only had three studio albums
and an EP; I wanted 20."
</P>
<P>
	   When grunge came on the scene in the '90s, Skid Row and other metal bands
were considered uncool. The band broke up after the release of its "Subhuman
Race" album in 1995. Other band members slid into oblivion, but Bach continued
on, contributing a song to the soundtrack of Wes Craven's 1996 movie "Scream"
and singing on tribute albums to Rush and Iron Maiden.
</P>
<P>
	   When he decided to go back on the road, Bach put together a band consisting
of guitarists Jimmy Flemion and Richie Scarlet, best known for his work with Ace
Frehley; drummer Mark McConnell; and a bassist known only as Larry. Two weeks of
dates became more than 100 gigs, with stops in Japan, Korea and Canada, plus two
weeks of touring U.S. arenas as the opening act for Pantera.
</P>
<P>
	   "The first time we hit the stage in Japan," Bach recalled, "the lights went
down and the sound of the crowd was the loudest, most vociferous reception I've
ever experienced in my life -- and I've played every big arena you could name."
</P>
<P>
	   His new album "Bring 'Em Bach Alive!" (Spitfire Records) captures some of
the intensity of his live performances and demonstrates the chemistry he has
with his new band.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the live cuts, Bach recorded five new songs with legendary
session drummer Anton Fig.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every time I ask him to jam with me, he says 'yes' and I never expect him
to say 'yes,"' Bach said with a laugh. "I had him at my house last week jammin'
and I'm saying to myself, 'I'm the luckiest guy."'
</P>
<P>
	   "Bring 'Em Bach Alive!" was co-produced by Bach and producer Michael
Wagener, who has worked with Metallica, Ozzy Osbourne and Janet Jackson. "I
figured if it's going to have my name on the cover, I'd better take
responsibility for everything," Bach said. "I'm proud of how the guitars sound
and the overall production."
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Bach is working on a new album to be released later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
