<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Kate Betts  </HEADLINE>
    By CAROL DEEGAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an interview, Katherine Betts talked about her career in
fashion journalism and her new job as editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar
magazine.
</P>
<P>
	   1. What were your dreams growing up?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: I always wanted to be a reporter, actually. Actually, that's not
true (laughs). Um, I always wanted to be a reporter, but I actually really
wanted to be a ballet dancer. I grew up in New York and I danced and thank God
my parents cut that dream short (laughs).
</P>
<P>
	   2. Did you go to journalism school?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: No, I actually majored in European history. ... In high school, I
worked on the paper, and I went to Princeton and I worked on The Daily
Princetonian, although not to any great success because it was very much a boys'
club, which I resented deeply when I was there. But I did want to work for a
newspaper when I graduated.
</P>
<P>
	   3. How did you get your start?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: I'm a big Francophile and I love Paris. I really wanted to live
there. So I kind of decided, OK, for a year I'll go and just see what I can do.
... And I went to Paris, everybody else was going to Wall Street, I thought, 'My
God, I'm crazy, I'm throwing away this education, I don't know what I'm going to
do there, I'll never get working papers.' But I was really lucky. I got a job at
The (International) Herald-Tribune on the support staff. ... I didn't write
anything for them, but it was great to be in Paris and to be the only person in
that office who spoke fluent French, so I was useful (laughs).
</P>
<P>
	   3 1/2. Do you read every word of Bazaar 10 times before publication?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: Not 10 times (laughs), but I read all the manuscripts and revised
manuscripts, finals. I read all of the titles and blurbs and I reread them again
when we do something called release, which is where we lay out the whole
magazine. And cover lines, captions. We're always working on three issues at one
time. Right now, we're closing March, and we've assigned April and May, and
we're starting to think about June, and now April, we have to really think about
April visuals. We're sort of finishing those up because that will all be shot in
January. You just have to always be thinking on like four different planes
basically.
</P>
<P>
	   4. Do you have a 40-hour day?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: There aren't enough hours in the day, I have to say (laughs).
It's really hard. You can't do it all, that's why you have to have great talent
working for you; people that you trust their judgment.
</P>
<P>
	   4 1/2. Is this job everything you dreamed it would be?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: Yeah. It's amazing. It's overwhelming, I have to be honest. There
is so much to do, but that's the exciting part, too, because it really is like
starting over, you know, and we can do anything. And I have to say that Hearst
has been incredibly supportive of all of our ideas, and even when I told them
that we wanted to change the logo, I was kind of scared that they would freak
out because it is a logo that has been redrawn a lot, but the typeface hasn't
really been radically changed. And I remember I went into a meeting with (Hearst
Magazines president) Cathie Black, and I thought I'd just sort of slip it in to
test the waters and see what her reaction would be, and she was very casual
about it, she was like 'Fine, you know, whatever you think is the right thing to
do,' and that's great, that is really, really unusual.
</P>
<P>
	   5. Are you excited about the completely redesigned February issue?
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts: Yeah. I am. I'm kind of nervous (laughs). I go back and forth. I
mean, I feel very excited about it because I feel like we hit a lot of the notes
we wanted to hit that I didn't think would necessarily be possible to hit in one
issue the first time out. But then I still have sleepless nights thinking, 'Oh,
my God, maybe this is the wrong thing to put into this issue!' I don't know, I
think risk is important.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kate Betts Launches a New Bazaar  </HEADLINE>
    By CAROL DEEGAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Katherine Betts accepted an offer to become editor in chief
of Harper's Bazaar three days before her first child was born.
</P>
<P>
	   Harper's Bazaar is a Hearst Magazines publication. Ms. Betts, 35, had worked
for eight years at competitor Vogue, published by Conde Nast, and was closely
identified with editor in chief Anna Wintour. ("... She gave me her blessing,"
Ms. Betts wrote in her December editor's letter.)
</P>
<P>
	   "I actually accepted the job on my due date, which was really insane when I
think back on it," she said in an interview in her sun-filled office. "People
are now saying to me, 'How did you do it? How did you take the job on the same
day?' Well, I had the baby three days later."
</P>
<P>
	   Oliver Betts Brown was born in June. "I officially started Sept. 1. In
August, I was coming in a few days a week. I was working from home right away."
</P>
<P>
	   She replaced Liz Tilberis, the celebrated Bazaar editor who died of ovarian
cancer last April.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past four months, Ms. Betts has redesigned Bazaar from head to toe,
including the magazine's logo. She has added new sections, new writers and new
photographers. The layouts and typefaces are new, and the cover is glossy. The
February issue, which is completely redesigned, goes on sale at newsstands on
Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
	   Ultimately, the success of the new Bazaar will be measured in fashion buzz,
readership and advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts, a Princeton graduate who prefers to be called Kate, is known for
her strong writing style and fashion knowledge with an eye toward new trends.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of people have said I'm going to make Bazaar like In Style, which I
don't know where they get that information, or (they ask) 'Are you going to put
celebrities on every cover?' They're focusing on the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
	   "To me, the success of In Style ... it's not the fact that there are
celebrities on the cover; it's not the fact that they do product endorsement. To
me, what's great about In Style is the tone. They've created this uniform,
all-inclusive, friendly not pretentious (magazine). They've brought that to the
fashion world and to Hollywood where it didn't exist before and that's what
makes that magazine successful. It's like what made Martha Stewart successful."
</P>
<P>
	   Gwyneth Paltrow, star of "The Talented Mr. Ripley," is on the February
cover. The January issue featured a full-page photo and an interview with
co-star Jude Law, nominated for a Golden Globe for his performance, who was
relatively unknown before "Ripley."
</P>
<P>
	   "We can't lose sight of the idea of supporting new talent and spotlighting
new talent and being a home for those kind of personalities," Ms. Betts said.
"Because I feel like that's the thing that drives magazines now, that's what
people are interested in. They are interested in stories and personalities and
what those people have to say for themselves. ... We have to think about
celebrities and the stories they can bring to the magazine in a new way."
</P>
<P>
	   Readers should not expect celebrity covers to become standard issue because
it would take away "from the surprise and the occasion" of having a celebrity on
the cover, Ms. Betts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't want to commit to like, you know, we'll do six celebrities and six
models. Who knows? We will do what we feel is right for the moment."
</P>
<P>
	   One goal is to attract a slightly younger readership, down from about age 38
to 35, she said, adding that fashion age is not necessarily something that is
measured in years.
</P>
<P>
	   "Twenty-five-year-olds are wearing designer labels more than ever and
65-year-olds are wearing Old Navy and the Gap more than ever," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   She also wants Bazaar to take a more journalistic stance, not follow the
fashion pack and "give fashion that extra layer, that extra story, that extra
bit of information that I always think tends to get lost in the shuffle because
the emphasis has been so much on glamour and celebrity, and certainly those two
things are important ingredients of fashion, but I don't think they are the only
interesting part of fashion."
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts also believes that it is important to show fashion in a bigger
cultural context.
</P>
<P>
	   "In order to sort of illuminate fashion, you have to give the reader an idea
of what's going on around the frock or the runway or the new hemline," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "And I have to say that that's something that I really, really learned about
from John Fairchild, because he was a genius at always looking at the guest list
or the menu at a dinner party instead of only what people were wearing."
</P>
<P>
	   From 1988 to 1991, Ms. Betts was a reporter and later bureau chief in the
Paris office of Fairchild Publications. She managed the office of the daily
trade paper Women's Wear Daily, W and M magazines, and helped launch W Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   "I loved it," she said. "It is really an amazing school for fashion, but it
teaches you a lot about reporting and covering a beat, because the fashion beat
is so specific, and also you have to cover the business side, so you really
learn the whole business from the inside out."
</P>
<P>
	   A friend introduced her to Ms. Wintour, who offered her an editing job at
Vogue. Ms. Betts turned it down because she wanted to continue writing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I remember thinking, 'Oh, my God, she's never going to call me again, what
have I done?' But she called me a few months later and offered me a writing job
and that's when I moved back.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anna gave me a lot of freedom right from the beginning. I was writing a lot
of stories, fashion features. But I was also writing a lot of copy for the
magazine, which I actually love doing that kind of stuff, like titles and blurbs
and cover lines. And I started off right away working a lot on the tone and
changing the tone and making it snappier and smarter and funnier, and it was
great, I mean, she really, really is a great boss in that way; if you want to do
something, she lets you do it."
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Betts is crafting a new Bazaar while acknowledging the magazine's
traditions. Bazaar started charting fashion in 1867.
</P>
<P>
	   "One of the things I love about the tradition of Bazaar as a mainstream
magazine is that sort of quirkiness that it's always had, and that was something
(art director Alexey) Brodovitch started in the '50s, and he kind of introduced
this idea of surprising the reader and doing something a little bit offbeat
every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
	   "The famous quote that he always used to say was 'astonish me,' and I think
that that's something that Bazaar has that very few mainstream magazines have in
their tradition, and I think that it's also something that's missing from a lot
of magazines because it has become very same and formulaic."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1311 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
