<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Studio Boss Expected To Quit  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Walt Disney studio boss Joe Roth, under whom the company
released two of its top three films ever, is expected to resign today, sources
told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney would not confirm the move, but sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the company and Roth were expected to issue a news release today
announcing his departure.
</P>
<P>
	   The resignation would follow another record year at the box office for
Disney, which was the top film distributor worldwide with $2.6 billion in ticket
sales and No. 1 domestically with $1.24 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The studio's 1999 releases included "The Sixth Sense," which has taken in
$276 million domestically, and "Toy Story 2," which has grossed $220 million.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first time two films from the same distributor topped the $200
million mark in one year. The movies are second and third on Disney's all-time
list, behind "The Lion King" with $312 million.
</P>
<P>
	   As head of studio operations, Roth oversaw film, TV, video and animation
production. Studio chairman since 1994, Roth also was responsible for such
movies as "Armageddon," "The Waterboy" and "Enemy of the State."
</P>
<P>
	   Sources would not disclose Roth's plans, but the Los Angeles Times reported
today that he intends to form his own independent movie company.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth's resignation would be the latest in a string of high-profile
departures of top Disney brass in the last few years, including two former chief
financial officers, Steve Bollenbach and Richard Nanula, ABC TV and radio
station chief Steve Burke and cable programming boss Geraldine Laybourne.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney also suffered through costly severance settlements with former top
executives Jeffrey Katzenberg and Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth took over Disney studio operations after Katzenberg quit. Previously,
Roth had been movie chairman at 20th Century Fox and also ran two independent
film companies, Morgan Creek Productions and Caravan Productions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1313 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union Chief Trumpets Worker Rights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    JERUSALEM (AP) -- Leading a delegation of American labor leaders in Israel,
AFL-CIO president John Sweeney said Wednesday that only a stronger labor
movement can protect workers' rights in a global economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney and his host, Israeli labor leader and legislator Amir Peretz, led a
one-day conference in Tel Aviv on globalization. They said the process tends to
deprive workers in industrialized countries of pension rights, insurance and
other aspects of social security.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we have these problems in all the industrialized countries and we
have to address them in the most effective way possible, and the way to do it is
to build a stronger labor union," Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday was the seventh day of Sweeney's trip to Israel and the
Palestinian areas. His six-member delegation of union leaders met Israeli
President Ezer Weizman and planned to have talks with Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Cabinet ministers and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney and his delegation also were to visit the West Bank to meet
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and other Palestinian officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1340 </TRAILER>
