<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yields Up on Inflation-Index Notes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yields on 10-year, inflation-indexed notes rose in
Wednesday's auction.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield was 4.338 percent, up from 4.040 percent at the last auction on
July 7. A total of $6 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling $18.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The government began selling inflation-indexed securities in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the yield, owners of inflation-indexed notes receive an
adjustment to principal twice a year. For instance, if inflation were 2 percent
in a year, the principal of a $1,000 note would increase to $1,020.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
