<HEADLINE> Ernest Hemingway letter stolen from home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) - A letter penned by author Ernest Hemingway was
reported stolen from the home of a friend and biographer.
<P>
	   A.E. Hotchner said he noticed the letter missing from his collection last
summer, shortly before he received a phone call from John Resnikoff, a local
antiques dealer. Resnikoff said he had just purchased a letter written to
Hotchner from Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
	   "Before I got back to him, he had sold it to an art collector in New York,"
Hotchner told The Associated Press on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   When the collector failed to respond to letters from Resnikoff, Hotchner or
his attorney, Hotchner decided to call police.
</P>
<P>
	   Hotchner would not identify the collector.
</P>
<P>
	   Hotchner said Resnikoff bought the letter from another dealer, who had
acquired it from another dealer, who claimed he got it from a man "whose name he
couldn't remember, who had moved to Peru," Hotchner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hotchner said the one-page, handwritten letter was penned during the filming
of the movie version of "Old Man and the Sea." He said it had been appraised at
about $6,000.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was writing me about how about they were preparing to shoot and they
were tied up by waiting for Spencer Tracy to show up; and he was grousing about
the whole thing," Hotchner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hotchner, who wrote the biography "Papa Hemingway, a Personal Memoir," in
December donated his entire collection of letters, photos and recordings of
Hemingway to the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   He said they will be given the missing letter if it is returned.
</P>
<P>
	   Hotchner and actor Paul Newman are the cofounders of the Newman's Own food
company and the Hole-in-the-Wall Gang Camp for seriously ill children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
