<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid To Delay Financial Reports  </HEADLINE>
    By HOPE YEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. says it plans to delay release of
several scheduled financial reports until July, a decision that sent its stock
plummeting 24 percent after a halt in trading earlier today.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York Stock Exchange halted trading for about an hour this morning
amid reports that it may delist Rite Aid. But in a statement, NYSE later said it
would not delist "at this time," though it was closely monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
	   A NYSE representative did not immediately return phone calls this afternoon.
Rite Aid shares were trading at $8.06 1/4, down $2.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's third-largest pharmacy chain announced late Tuesday it had
reached agreement with its lenders on the delay and planned to seek extensions
on Securities and Exchange Commission filings for the remaining quarterly and
annual reports for fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Rite Aid's third quarter report for the period ending Nov. 27 was due
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe it's a responsible action to take," said vice president Karen
Rugen. "We've had a new management team for a month, we've had new auditors for
just a few weeks, and with all the delays with the reaudit of '97, '98 and '99,
we realized we didn't have enough time."
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement didn't assuage analysts' concerns, however.
</P>
<P>
	   "The move tells me that the problems run pretty deep and that there is no
easy solution to remedying the problems with Rite Aid's former internal
accounting methodologies," said Steven Valiquette of Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
	   The Camp Hill-based chain has been trying to recover after financial woes
sent the company's stock tumbling by more than 80 percent in a year. Former top
executive Martin L. Grass was ousted in October, and a new team led by CEO
Robert Miller has pledged to improve profitability with stricter financial
controls and strategic marketing.
</P>
<P>
	   Rite Aid also has switched auditing firms and a restatement of its earnings
for the past three years was expected to result in a $500 million reduction.
</P>
<P>
	   Valiquette said Rite Aid's move is a possible setback for the company.
</P>
<P>
	   "It takes the wind out of their sails in the short term, to the extent the
company had some momentum after announcement of its new management team," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   John Ransom of Raymond James &AMP; Associates agreed, citing figures on Rite
Aid's same-store sales released Tuesday showing a 5.9 percent increase. That was
a poor performance compared to the double-digit growth of Walgreen's and CVS, he
said. Same-store comparisons measure sales growth excluding the impact of newly
opened stores.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the double whammy of weak December sales and a likely black hole of
information doesn't help," Ransom said. "I doubt any investors are betting on a
quick and easy turnaround."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
