<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Hughes Stock Climb on Rumor  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL WHITE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Reports that Boeing Co., the world's biggest airplane
maker, will buy Hughes Electronics Corp.'s satellite manufacturing operations
pushed up the stock of both companies today.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shares jumped $4.18 3/4 to $107.37 1/2 in early afternoon trading,
while Boeing stock was nudged up 43 3/4 cents to $43.31 1/4 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   The long-rumored deal would make Boeing a dominant player in the commercial
satellite industry, now led by Hughes. Hughes, which is owned by General Motors
Corp., would be allowed to focus on its fast-growing DirecTV satellite-to-home
entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shares trade separately from regular GM shares.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing plans to buy the satellite-making operations for $4 billion,
according to a Dow Jones Newswires report citing unidentified sources familiar
with the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesman for Boeing and Hughes declined to comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing wants to position itself broadly in the aerospace market, said Jon
Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, an investment bank
specializing in aerospace acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
	   The move would reduce its dependency on jet airliner sales, and put the
company in position to capitalize on the growing demand for commercial
satellites. The purchase also would reflect some uncertainty on Boeing's part as
to which areas of aerospace will become the most lucrative in the next century,
Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
	   "For Boeing, it's hard to sit here and decide which way things are going to
go, and they want to be represented across the board," Kutler said. "They're
trying to have their arms in most of the major areas of the space market in
order to be well-positioned regardless of how the market goes."
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shares have more than doubled during the past year, driven by the
growth of DirecTV. The service, with more than 8 million subscribers, had
revenue of $1.05 billion in the third quarter, up from $408 million in the third
quarter of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
