<DOCNO> APW20000112.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economy Embraces Change  </HEADLINE>
    By JOJI SAKURAI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Banks crossing over traditional loyalty lines to merge with
rivals. An automaker renowned for its old-school ways seeking a savior from
France. An Internet entrepreneur outshining the industrial old guard.
</P>
<P>
	   In many ways, 1999 was truly the end of an era for Japan -- and after a
decadelong economic downturn, many economists wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
	   But the question now facing the world's second-richest nation is whether it
can keep up the momentum.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the year that decides whether we create a new Japan or slip back,"
said Yotaro Kobayashi, head of the Japan Association of Corporate Executives.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say this year that the economy will finally return to growth thanks
to generous public spending. Other bright signs include a recovery in the stock
market, where the benchmark index rose 36.8 percent in 1999, and a bottoming-out
of corporate bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
	   But the broader question -- whether dynamic change will give birth to
self-sustained expansion or a return to inertia leads to steady decline -- is
the one that is being watched most avidly.
</P>
<P>
	   Following London's example, Japan is in the process of a broad-ranging "Big
Bang" reform program aimed at pepping up the economy by easing or abolishing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reforms have been particularly noteworthy in the financial sector, where
struggling brokerages and banks saddled with bad debt had become a major draw on
the economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, regulations in currency exchange were lifted. Fixed commissions
charged by brokerages were scrapped last year and by 2001 banks, insurance
companies and brokerages will be allowed to enter one another's businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Experts say the official goal of a more dynamic marketplace is already
reflected in new thinking among the private sector.
</P>
<P>
	   "Japanese industry is transforming itself drastically," said Kanji Ishii, a
professor of economic history at the Tokyo Keizai University.
</P>
<P>
	   Some examples of that transformation from the past year are, by Japanese
standards, breathtaking:
</P>
<P>
	   --Several top banks announced mergers with rivals, signaling the decline of
the "keiretsu" business groupings that built up the postwar economy. The mergers
demonstrate a shift in emphasis toward profitability and away from the
traditional ethic of group loyalty.
</P>
<P>
	   --Ailing Nissan Motor Co., one of the bastions of Japanese-style enterprise,
accepted a massive cash infusion from France's Renault and invited "cost-killer"
Carlos Ghosn to run its operations. The result is a plan to cut 21,000 jobs,
close five factories and break ties with inefficient suppliers.
</P>
<P>
	   --The success story of the year wasn't a mainstream mogul but entrepreneur
Masayoshi Son, whose Internet colossus Softbank Co. inspired scores of new
info-tech companies and is persuading investors to look into risky, but
potentially lucrative, ideas in relatively untested territory.
</P>
<P>
	   Professor Ishii and others acknowledge Japan still has many areas in which
it lags behind the United States. And, they note, drastically reworking the
economy carries considerable cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, the culture that made a cherished axiom out of "a nail that
sticks out will get bashed back in" is now asked to cast laurels at the
enterpreneurial infotech pioneers.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, businesses whose loftiest management principal was loyalty to
employees and business ties are being urged to ruthlessly close factories and
dump cost inefficient partners.
</P>
<P>
	   As such, larger concerns have been raised about the potential downside the
economic bottom line will have for society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan's treasured cultural homogeneity has largely been supported by a
homogeneity of wealth. Now, as innovative startup firms sprout up and
restructuring creates record-high unemployment, the possibility of a chasm
between the rich and poor is becoming a real threat.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Japanese feel scuttling time-honed values is too high a cost for
economic prosperity. Even the government waffles between economic shock-therapy
and shielding businesses and workers from the consequences of structural reform.
</P>
<P>
	   And there are, of course, near-term dangers that could stall recovery.
</P>
<P>
	   Private spending in the second quarter of fiscal 1999 dipped 0.3 percent,
showing consumer confidence remains fragile. A strong yen continues to threaten
export-oriented firms, and with a general election due this year the ruling
party might back-peddle on reform.
</P>
<P>
	   But experts generally believe Japan is too far along in its metamorphosis to
go back now.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are seeing a complete rethinking of the postwar Japanese model," said
Peter Morgan, an economist at HSBC Securities. "There will be no return back to
that."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
