<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Chooses Moderates for Response  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two of the Senate's newest, youngest and least partisan
Republicans have the high-profile task of giving their party's response
following President Clinton's State of the Union address later this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Sens. Bill Frist of Tennessee and Susan Collins of Maine, both 47-year-old
freshmen known for their non-confrontational styles, will get a unique
opportunity to portray the policies and image of the Republican Party following
Clinton's Jan. 27 speech to Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., in selecting the two, emphasized
their expertise in education and health care issues, two major legislative
battlegrounds in this year's session.
</P>
<P>
	   But Lott also is following the example set by House Republican leaders last
year, when they chose a personably pleasing pair of lawmakers, former NFL
football star Steve Largent of Oklahoma and Jennifer Dunn of Washington, to be
the face of the party responding to Clinton's annual speech.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a real effort on the part of the Republican leadership to put
forward the people in the party who are attractive, who are not threatening
characters,'' said Rutgers University professor Ross Baker, who studies
Congress. ``They want to put the lie to the argument that the party is made up
of flinty-eyed ideologues.''
</P>
<P>
	   John Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman, stressed that ``resume really drove this
decision'' -- Frist, as the Senate's only physician, is one of the party's most
authoritative experts on health care issues and Collins has focused on education
policies since she came to Washington in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   But Czwartacki added that the pair, ``like many senators, many members of
our caucus, look like America ... The two of them both by experience and
appearance come across as effective spokespeople.''
</P>
<P>
	   Frist, a heart-lung transplant surgeon in Nashville before his election to
the Senate in 1994, is the more conservative of the two. He wants private
savings accounts to be a part of Social Security system reform and has
championed the GOP version of a patient's bill of rights bill that, unlike
Democratic-backed bills, would limit a patient's rights to sue a managed care
provider.
</P>
<P>
	   But Frist, who gained a moment of fame in July 1998 when he treated the
wounded gunman who killed two Capitol Hill police officers, has also worked
closely with Democrats on education and health issues, and leads a bipartisan
group working toward Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He'd rather reach out than waste valuable time bickering,'' said his press
secretary, Margaret Camp.
</P>
<P>
	   Frist's State of the Union response will give him national exposure at a
time when he is gearing up for his re-election campaign, but Frist, who defeated
three-term Democratic Sen. James Sasser in 1994, does not appear to face a
serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
	   Collins is in the moderate tradition of her old Senate boss, former Maine
senator and current Defense Secretary William Cohen. She has led her party's
efforts to loosen federal controls over education money, but has also differed
with most Republicans by supporting abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Collins attracted national attention twice this year -- first during
Clinton's impeachment trial when she unsuccessfully pushed a plan to find
Clinton guilty without removing him from office and second when she sponsored
popular legislation to stop sweepstakes company deceptions. She was one of five
Republican senators to vote not guilty on both articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
	   Her role models are people who ``knew that you have to cooperate and have
consensus to get anything done,'' said her spokeswoman, Felicia Knight.
``Reasonable is the perfect word for her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1531 </TRAILER>
