<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki budget pushes for control of state Education Dept.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki, with a couple of provisions
tucked away in a corner of his executive budget, is mounting a full-scale
assault against the state Education Department again after a disappointing year
for state schools.
<P>
	   Pataki not only wants to take away the department's control over the state
Library, Archives and Museum, he also wants to slash some of the Education
Department's staff; personally choose the department's commissioner, as well as
its controlling board, the Board of Regents, and the Regents' chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   He even wants to strip the department of $250,000 in charter school money.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Pataki never specifically mentioned his plans during his State of
the State address last week or in his executive budget address on Tuesday to
legislators. Instead, Pataki focused on the record amount of public school aid
he wants to spend in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   "By the way, we haven't seen the results from the schools that we should
have expected when you pour this amount of money into them," Pataki told
reporters after his executive budget address Tuesday. That "is why we don't need
just the additional dollars that we're proposing but we need structural reform.
We need accountability."
</P>
<P>
	   State officials got the first test results from the Board of Regents' push
to increase the educational standards in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half of the fourth grade students did not pass the Regents' new
English test, a third failed the fourth-grade Math test and a fourth of those
who took the senior English exam needed to graduate have to take it again.
</P>
<P>
	   But Education Commissioner Richard Mills, who was hired by the
Assembly-controlled Board of Regents, didn't like Pataki's education plan.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think this is personal. We have a very good working relationship
with the governor's staff but I certainly don't agree with this proposal," Mills
said. "The Board of Regents has mustered the forces at their command to raise
standards. The Regents have been very persistent about this. I don't see the
logic of that change at all."
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers, especially in the Democrat-controlled Assembly, are unlikely to
go along with Pataki's plan. Pataki has suggested that the Legislature give him
greater control of the state's schools every year since the first year of his
term, Assembly Education Chairman Steven Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Legislature has rejected this autocratic approach to education every
year since," Sanders said. "We will certainly reject it again this year."
</P>
<P>
	   While Pataki has suggested abolishing the Board of Regents before, this is
the first time he has suggested taking away the state Museum, Archives and
Library away from the Education Department, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Joe Conway, a spokesman for Pataki's Budget Division, said all of Pataki's
suggestions were "common-sense" initiatives. The State University of New York
gets more charter school applications than the Education Department and
streamlining the command structure will provide a greater level of
accountability, Pataki's plan says.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10 percent reduction Pataki wants would only be 18 employees from the
department's Office of Management Services and Elementary, Middle, Secondary and
Continuing Education divisions, which would be accomplished through attrition,
Conway said. "We would rather spend general fund dollars on the classrooms, not
on the bureaucracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The point behind the initiatives is "producing the best possible result for
the students," Conway said. "This plan would allow the Education Department to
focus its attention where it belongs, on the classrooms."
</P>
<P>
	   But Carole Huxley, the deputy education commissioner for cultural education,
worried about the separation between politics and education. Putting political
appointees in charge of information distribution and education might not be a
good idea, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "A buffer between politics and libraries, public broadcasting, archives and
museums is an important thing," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1602 </TRAILER>
