<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jail guards plead guilty to fatal beating of Nassau Jail inmate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) - Two Nassau County correction officers pleaded
guilty Wednesday to federal civil rights charges for fatally beating a
recovering heroin addict in his cell at the county jail.
<P>
	   The guards, Patrick Regnier and Edward Velazquez, changed their pleas to
guilty before U.S. District Court Judge Jacob Mishler. They opted to plead after
a third guard cut a deal last week to admit that he served as the lookout on
Jan. 8, 1999, and to testify against his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Velazquez, under questioning from Mishler, admitted that he went to Thomas
Pizzuto's cell "to quiet him down and use unreasonable force if necessary."
</P>
<P>
	   The recovering heroin addict was crying out for his methadone treatment.
Pizzuto, 38, of Hicksville, was serving a 90-day sentence for traffic
violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Three days after the beating, he suffered a seizure and died. The Nassau
County medical examiner found that Pizzuto had suffered a ruptured spleen and
ruled the death a homicide.
</P>
<P>
	   The courtroom was packed for the guilty pleas, with Pizzuto's
wheelchair-bound mother weeping quietly during the 70-minute session.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount of prison time the pair faces at their April 7 sentencing will be
determined by Mishler after conducting a hearing on whether their conduct
amounted to murder or manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
	   A ruling that the death was the result of murder could bring each guard up
to 30 years in prison, while a manslaughter ruling would yield a sentence of
between 3 1/2 and 12 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Their defense case suffered a major setback last week when a third guard
charged in the case, Ivano Bavaro, pleaded guilty to federal conspiracy and
witness tampering charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Bavaro admitted that he acted as a lookout while Velazquez and Regnier went
into Pizzuto's cell and pounded the inmate into silence.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial against a fourth guard, Joseph Bergen, accused of filing a false
report indicating that Pizzuto had slipped in the shower, will proceed later
this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The East Meadow jail, which houses about 1,800 inmates and is patrolled by
approximately 1,100 guards, has been the subject of numerous allegations of
guard misconduct. Following Pizzuto's death and other allegations of abuse, the
U.S. Department of Justice began an investigation of how inmates there are
treated.
</P>
<P>
	   Last March, a Nassau County correction officer was found liable in the
beating of a mentally retarded jail inmate with a frying pan in 1993. County
officials agreed to a $500,000 settlement in the inmate's civil rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   Sheriff Joseph Jablonsky, whose jurisdiction included the jail, retired late
last year. A replacement has yet to be hired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1603 </TRAILER>
