<HEADLINE> Corn Leads Grains Sharply Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures soared Wednesday on the Chicago
Board of Trade after the U.S. Department of Agriculture reported a surprise cut
in its estimate of U.S. corn production.
</P>
<P>
	   The USDA lowered its forecast for the 1999 corn crop by 100 million bushels
to 9.4 billion bushels at a time of year when estimates traditionally rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn rocketed to a four-month high, settling up 4 percent for the day, and
other grains and soybeans followed.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans also were bolstered by the USDA's projected cut in soybean
production figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices were buoyed by lower-than-expected quarterly grain stocks and a
slight reduction in winter wheat acreage that pushed U.S. wheat acreage to its
lowest level since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery rose 5 cents to $2.58 3/4 a bushel; March corn rose
8 1/4 cents to $2.15 1/2 a bushel; March oats rose 1 3/4 cents to $1.10 1/4 a
bushel; March soybeans rose 5 3/4 cents to $4.80 1/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle fell .45 cent to 70.42 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle fell .68 cent to 85.97 cents a pound; February lean hogs fell 1.22 cents
to 54.80 cents a pound; February pork bellies rose .80 cent to 83.15 cents a
pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
