<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEP begins deer hunt at Bluff Point Coastal Reserve  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   GROTON, Conn. (AP) - The state began its hunt of 78 deer at Bluff Point
Coastal Reserve on Wednesday, a day after a judge ruled the state could go ahead
with its plans to kill three-quarters of the deer there.
<P>
	   The hunt began shortly after daybreak Wednesday and was scheduled to
continue on weekdays through Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not clear how many deer were killed Wednesday. Department of
Environmental Protection officials did not return telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Bill Mannetti of the New Haven-based Animal Rights Front, had sought to
delay the hunt until a trial is held on the issue next month, said some members
of his group might attempt to disrupt the hunt, as they have previously.
</P>
<P>
	   "Some people feel passionately about this and want to express their feelings
in a dramatic fashion by sabotaging the hunt," he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday morning several protesters were in front of barricades that
blocked the access road into the preserve. They were holding signs, including
one that read "Stop the Slaughter."
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile Derek Oatis, the group's attorney, said he was considering filing
a direct appeal to the state Supreme Court. The rare move is an option on issues
of public interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The group sought to use a 1963 state law to prevent the DEP from conducting
the special hunt. The activists argued unsuccessfully that the agency had
violated the law in the past by killing fawns and was likely to do so again.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue in the hearing was when a fawn becomes an adult. The activists
claimed a fawn becomes a deer when it is 1 year old, while the state said deer
are no longer fawns after they lose their spots at about five months.
</P>
<P>
	   After hearing two days of testimony, Berger said the DEP definition is
easier to enforce because hunters cannot easily distinguish between fawns whose
spots have faded and more mature deer.
</P>
<P>
	   The hunt originally was scheduled to begin on Monday but was put on hold
while the judge heard the case.
</P>
<P>
	   The state contends that 78 of the 103 deer at Bluff Point must be killed in
order to protect the fragile flora at the 800-acre preserve.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want a balance," said Ed Parker, chief of the DEP's natural resources
bureau.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bluff Point Reserve and adjacent Bluff Point State Park have been closed
since Monday and are scheduled to remain closed to the public while the hunt is
conducted through Jan. 28. However, the park will be open on weekends and the
Martin Luther King Jr. Holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1626 </TRAILER>
