<DOCNO> APW20000112.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Studio Boss Resigns  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Walt Disney studio boss Joe Roth, under whom the company
scored two of its three top films ever last year, said today he is resigning to
form his own independent film outfit.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth will be replaced as Disney studio chairman by Peter Schneider, who has
been the studio president for the last year.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have loved working at Disney, both as an executive and a producer, for
the past seven years, but feel that it is time for me to pursue a more
entrepreneurial, independent life," Roth said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
	   The resignation follows another record year at the box office for Disney,
which was the top film distributor worldwide with $2.6 billion in ticket sales
and No. 1 domestically with $1.24 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The studio's 1999 releases included "The Sixth Sense," which has taken in
$276 million domestically, and "Toy Story 2," which has grossed $220 million.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first time two films from the same distributor topped the $200
million mark in one year. The movies are second and third on Disney's all-time
list, behind "The Lion King" with $312 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney Chairman Michael Eisner said Roth helped maintain the company's
leadership in live-action films. Eisner said he hoped Roth would hook up with
Disney on future films.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have little doubt that Joe and Disney will be working together on
projects in the years to come," Eisner said in the news release.
</P>
<P>
	   As head of studio operations, Roth oversaw film, TV, video and animation
production. Studio chief since 1994, Roth also was responsible for such movies
as "Armageddon," "The Waterboy" and "Enemy of the State."
</P>
<P>
	   Roth's resignation is the latest in a string of high-profile departures of
top Disney brass in the last few years, including two former chief financial
officers, Steve Bollenbach and Richard Nanula, ABC TV and radio station chief
Steve Burke and cable programming boss Geraldine Laybourne.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney also suffered through costly severance settlements with former top
executives Jeffrey Katzenberg and Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth took over Disney studio operations after Katzenberg quit. Previously,
Roth had been movie chairman at 20th Century Fox and also ran two independent
film companies, Morgan Creek Productions and Caravan Productions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
