<HEADLINE> Astronaut Makes Rommel Remark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The commander of NASA's next space shuttle
mission jokingly told German astronaut Gerhard Thiele that ``Rommel would have
been proud of you'' after Thiele drove an armored personnel carrier during
training Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Kregel made the remark about the Nazi general on a vacant launch pad
at Kennedy Space Center where crew members were practicing shuttle escape
maneuvers. Part of their training includes driving a M-113 armored personnel
carrier away from the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
	   Thiele, who is part of Kregel's six-member crew on space shuttle Endeavour,
laughed when he heard the remark.
</P>
<P>
	   Endeavour is scheduled to launch Jan. 31 for an Earth-mapping mission.
</P>
<P>
	   Erwin Rommel was known as ``The Desert Fox'' during World War II and led
Germany's Afrika Korps against Allied forces in Libya in 1941.
</P>
<P>
	   He repeatedly outmaneuvered his opponents but was overcome by British forces
at El Alamein, Egypt, in 1942. In 1944, Rommel was implicated in a plot to kill
Adolf Hitler and chose to ingest a fatal dose of poison rather than face trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
