<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Offers SUV Rollover Air Bags  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    AP Photos DTC105-106
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will offer a new safety option in its sport
utility vehicles -- air bags that cover the side windows like curtains to
prevent passengers from being thrown out in rollover crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   The new ai-rbag curtains are Ford's answer to figures showing passengers in
SUVs are four times more likely to be involved in a rollover during a serious
accident than passengers in cars. Most often, rollover deaths involve passengers
being thrown from the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
	   The curtains, unveiled Wednesday during the preview of the North American
International Auto Show, will be phased in on Ford's SUVs.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said an unspecified model will get the curtains as an option late this
year, and the devices should be available as optional equipment on all of the
automaker's SUVs in about three years.
</P>
<P>
	   No price has been set. Nor would Ford executives talk about putting the
system in pickups, minivans or cars.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 47 percent
of all deaths in light trucks -- which include SUVs -- result from rollovers. In
comparison, 22 percent of car deaths involve rollovers.
</P>
<P>
	   The system has a sensor that can measure the amount of vehicle tilt and
trigger the air-bag curtain. The curtain would deploy downward in milliseconds
from the edge of the roof, covering the side windows along the front and back
rows of seats.
</P>
<P>
	   The curtains, attached to the vehicle with tethers, remain inflated for six
seconds, the amount of time Ford says it takes the average vehicle to roll over
up to three times. The sensor will modulate the force of the airbags depending
on the speed of the vehicle, inflating the curtains faster at higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said the curtains are also intended to reduce head injuries in
side-impact crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   Several automakers, including Mercedes and Volvo, also have air bag curtains
that inflate across the windows. BMW has an air bag that inflates in the shape
of a tube that hangs near the top of the window.
</P>
<P>
	   Those systems are primarily advertised as a means of protecting people's
heads, though the automakers say they could help keep passengers from being
thrown out in a rollover.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ford system is designed specifically for rollover protection.
</P>
<P>
	   Many automakers, including Ford, already have side air-bag systems that
deploy from the seat or door and are designed to protect the head or chest in
side-impact crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford's announcement came as the NHTSA develops a vehicle rollover rating
system expected to be proposed in the next few months. Last year, the agency
started requiring most new SUVs to carry illustrated warning labels declaring
they have a "higher rollover risk" than standard automobiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1642 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Protects Drivers' Privacy  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE ASSEO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress can protect motorists' privacy by barring states
from selling the personal information on drivers' licenses, the Supreme Court
ruled Wednesday in rejecting a states' right challenge.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices' unanimous decision ran counter to their recent trend of
reining in Congress' power over the states.
</P>
<P>
	   The case involves South Carolina's challenge to the 1994 Driver's Privacy
Protection Act, enacted in response to the 1989 killing of actress Rebecca
Schaeffer by a stalker who used a private investigator to get her address from
driver's license records.
</P>
<P>
	   The act ``does not require the states in their sovereign capacity to
regulate their own citizens,'' Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the
court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It does not require the South Carolina Legislature to enact any laws or
regulations, and it does not require state officials to assist in the
enforcement of federal statutes regulating private individuals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The law bars states and their employees from releasing personal information
from motor vehicle records -- including names, addresses, telephone and Social
Security numbers and photographs -- unless someone consents to such release.
</P>
<P>
	   The law's sponsor, Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said the ruling means
``Congress has the right to protect the privacy of personal information that
could be used to harm our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Feminist Majority Foundation called the decision ``a decisive victory''
for protecting women against violence. The law is ``crucial to protecting
workers at abortion clinics,'' where people have used drivers' license numbers
to get workers' home addresses, the group said.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision was criticized by Gregg Leslie, acting executive director of
the Reporters' Committee for Freedom of the Press.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For perhaps 100 years, state legislators have always made these decisions
by balancing privacy with the public need to know,'' Leslie said. ``Then without
research, Congress, reacting to some scares, made a sweeping decision to deny
access to all this information.''
</P>
<P>
	   States routinely have sold drivers' license information to businesses and
political candidates, earning millions of dollars in revenue each year. When
Congress enacted the law, 34 states made drivers' license records public in some
form.
</P>
<P>
	   The law includes exceptions, allowing such information to be disclosed to
law enforcement officials, courts, government agencies and private
investigators. No exemption is included for the news media.
</P>
<P>
	   South Carolina argued that Congress' power to regulate interstate commerce
did not give it the authority to govern the release of such state records. The
4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Department lawyers argued to the Supreme Court that releasing
drivers' license records means people are forced to provide the key to their
personal information on their license plates.
</P>
<P>
	   Rehnquist's opinion distinguished the case from a 1997 dispute in which the
justices decided Congress could not force the states to conduct background
checks on prospective gun buyers.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Wednesday's case was more like a 1988 ruling in which the Supreme
Court upheld a law that barred states from issuing unregistered bonds. The law
regulated state activities but did not try to control how states regulate
private parties, the court said at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1643 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver pushes new campaign finance limits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Assembly's Democratic majority called
Wednesday for banning fund-raising events for state office candidates held
within 40 miles of the state Capitol during annual legislative sessions.
<P>
	   In wide-ranging campaign finance reform legislation, the Assembly Democrats
also proposed limits on the amount of money political party committees could
transfer to such state office candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, party committees could only give $700,000 to candidates for
governor; $50,000 to state Senate candidates; and $25,000 to Assembly candidates
under the Assembly majority's proposal. There are currently no such limits.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure, which stands almost no chance of becoming law in its current
form, also renews the Assembly Democratic majority's past calls for partial
public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   "As we enter the 21st century, it is incumbent upon elected officials to
face directly the challenge of campaign finance reform and come up with a system
that is equitable and fair to the public," Stephen Kaufman, a Bronx Democrat who
is chairman of the Assembly's Election Law Committee, said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Assembly leadership indicated the proposal to ban fund-raising events in
the Albany area during legislative sessions was aimed at the practice of
politicians hitting up lobbyists and their clients for money at a time when they
want want to influence legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   In June, Gov. George Pataki unveiled his own sweeping campaign finance
proposal that would have barred fund-raising events from even being held within
25 miles of the state Capitol during the annual legislative session that
normally runs from early January through June or July.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki plan would also eliminate the unlimited "soft-money" donations
special interests can give to political parties and impose lower campaign
contribution limits for all state office races. The Republican governor did not
call for public campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither the Democratic-led Assembly or the Republican-controlled Senate has
acted on the governor's proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing its campaign finance proposal, the Assembly Democrats called
on the Senate GOP majority to approve the governor's plan and then allow a joint
Assembly-Senate conference committee to work out compromise legislation
acceptable to both chambers.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican, said
Wednesday that his GOP Senate colleagues would be unveiling their own campaign
finance proposal. He gave no timetable for when that plan might be made public.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno did take a jab at the Assembly Democrats, noting that they have
refused to go along with legislation approved by the Senate to bar all gifts
over $25 from lobbyists. The Senate leader noted that the senators have agreed
to abide by that ban voluntarily even without Assembly approval of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno said Wednesday that in that same spirit, the Assembly Democrats should
pass their campaign finance plan and then voluntarily abide by its restrictions,
even without agreement from the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1644 </TRAILER>
