<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Tax Break for Poor  </HEADLINE>
   By TERENCE HUNT AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reassuring himself that he's not a lame duck, President
Clinton began laying out the agenda of his final year in office Wednesday with a
$21 billion expansion in tax credits for the working poor and more help for the
nation's neediest communities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The great challenge for us today is to make up our minds: what are we
going to do with this magic moment of promise,'' Clinton said, boasting about
low unemployment, declining crime rates and the strongest economy in America's
history.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans reacted warily to Clinton's proposal. ``I think the Clinton
administration spends money every day, it seems like,'' Republican presidential
front-runner George W. Bush said. ``If you look at the newspapers, and look at
the programs, there is always another program, another initiative.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president spoke before the Democratic Leadership Council, the centrist
political group he helped found. Introducing Clinton, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., said the booming economy was ``a great legacy'' for the president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I always get nervous when people start talking about legacies,'' the
president joked moments later. ``You know, alliteration having the appeal that
it does, it's just one small step from legacy to lame duck.'' But Clinton
hastened to add that he would not be a lame duck until he gave a speech and the
audience was empty.
</P>
<P>
	   Previewing the State of the Union address he will deliver before Congress on
Jan. 27, Clinton said a primary theme would be ``a new opportunity agenda'' of
advancement opportunities for families ``still at the margins of society who are
willing to work and ought to be rewarded for it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will put forth my last but still a new agenda, rooted in responsibility,
designed to create a wider, stronger, more inclusive American community and to
create new opportunities.'' He said he would offer education and training
proposals and measures to make health care and child care more affordable.
</P>
<P>
	   The major ingredient of Wednesday's speech was a proposed $21 billion
expansion over 10 years of the earned income tax credit program, which provides
an annual payment for nearly 20 million families living around the national
poverty line. In 1998, the average claim was $1,459 for 19.4 million taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said his initiative would provide up to $1,200 more in tax relief
for eligible families. It would expand the credit for parents with three or more
children, allow married couples to earn an additional $1,450 before the start of
a phase out of their credit, lower the phase out rate and allow families to
contribute to a 401 (k) retirement plan without risking their credit.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, taxpayers earning between $10,000 and $31,000 were eligible,
depending on the number of children they have. Clinton said his program would
increase aid for 6.4 million families.
</P>
<P>
	   On Capitol Hill, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, reacted skeptically to the president's proposal. ``Taxpayers
might question spending billions more on a program that the IRS says already
wastes close to $6.5 billion each year -- or about one dollar out of every five
-- because of fraud and mistakes,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond expanding the earned income tax credit, Clinton will propose
significant spending increases for programs designed to steer investment to the
nation's neediest urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton will seek $5 billion over 10 years for his New Markets tax-credit
program to encourage businesses to invest in neglected communities, said Gene
Sperling, the president's top economic adviser. The program, offering investors
a 25 percent tax credit, had been budgeted at $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the president will expand his empowerment zone tax initiative
by $4 billion over the next 10 years, Sperling said. The program offers tax
relief to attract businesses to economically disadvantaged areas. It also
provides housing redevelopment and enhanced local services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
