<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Unveils Education Money  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will propose $367 million to
create smaller and safer schools around the country, Vice President Al Gore said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The funding request, part of the fiscal 2001 budget President Clinton will
submit to Congress, will include $247 million for the Safe Schools/Healthy
Students Initiative, which awards grants to help develop community-wide
responses to school and youth violence.
</P>
<P>
	   The president also will propose spending $120 million for the Small, Safe
and Successful High Schools Initiative, which encourages school districts to
create smaller schools.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the aftermath of tragic violence in our schools, there can be no doubt
that this investment in our children's safety is essential,'' Gore said. The
goal, he said, is to offer ``young people the safe and healthy environments they
need to thrive.''
</P>
<P>
	   As for smaller schools, Gore said it would mean ``more personal attention to
the varied needs of all our children.''
</P>
<P>
	   In September, Clinton announced over $100 million in Safe Schools/Healthy
Students grants for 54 school districts. The amount being proposed in the new
budget is an increase of more than $100 million and will allow grants for 40
more communities.
</P>
<P>
	   The second program allows schools to break up larger schools using
innovative strategies such as autonomous schools-within-schools, restructured
school days and career academies.
</P>
<P>
	   The program is structured around research that has shown that smaller
schools are safer and more productive because students feel less alienated, more
nurtured and more connected to caring adults.
</P>
<P>
	   There are more than 12,400 three- and four-year high schools in the United
States. More than 70 percent of students in those schools attend a school with
more than 1,000 students. Enrollments of 2,000 and 3,000 are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
	   The program started last year with $45 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Mary Elizabeth Teasley, government relations director for the National
Education Association, said it is partnerships like the ones being proposed that
help school districts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The resources will make a significant difference both in funding these
programs and in highlighting these issues. ... It's an encouragement for
districts that are lagging behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
