<HEADLINE> Korea Auto Cos. Show Off New Models  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSEPH ALTMAN Jr. Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Three Korean automakers that found good times in the U.S.
market last year showed off their expansion plans during previews Wednesday for
the North American International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai, Kia and Daewoo all exhibited models going on sale in 2000, most of
which expand their lineups from the small cars that sold well in 1999 to midsize
sedans and sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai announced it will sell a full-size passenger car, currently dubbed
the XG, in the United States this fall. The four-door, five-passenger sedan is
aimed at older buyers who make more than $60,000 per year -- a step above the
automaker's typical base of customers who are looking for value-priced, compact
cars.
</P>
<P>
	   "With the success of the Sonata, we feel there is now a place in our model
lineup for a slightly larger vehicle," said Robert Cosmai, Hyundai's vice
president for sales.
</P>
<P>
	   The XG, whose name may change before it is released, will offer a 3.0-liter
V6 with 192 horsepower, and will be priced between $23,000 and $24,000, Cosmai
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai also showed off its previously introduced Santa Fe SUV, the first in
the South Korean carmaker's line. It is set to go on sale this summer at a price
between $17,000 and $21,000, Cosmai said.
</P>
<P>
	   Daewoo, attending Detroit's annual show for the first time since entering
the U.S. market 15 months ago, unveiled the first SUV in its lineup -- the 2001
Korando. The two-door Korando, poised to compete with the Jeep Cherokee and
Toyota RAV4, will have a 3.2-liter, six-cylinder engine from Mercedes that
produces 217 horsepower. Daewoo plans to sell it for about $20,000, starting in
May.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're finally joining the sport-utility segment of the market, and I don't
have to tell you that's an important segment to be a part of," said William D.
Tucker, vice president of marketing for the automaker. "It's not breaking ground
in SUVs, but it will compete with others in its segment."
</P>
<P>
	   Daewoo also announced an update for the Leganza sedan, which will sell for
between $13,000 and $18,660, and a larger sedan model called the Magnus.
</P>
<P>
	   Kia revealed its 2000 Spectra hatchback sedan, which will be in dealerships
this spring for a price only slightly higher than the Sephia sedan's $9,995
price, said Dick Macedo, executive vice president for marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
	   Kia also has plans to introduce a mid-size sedan in the fall, allowing the
Korean automaker to expand into what Macedo called "a very competitive sector."
</P>
<P>
	   Other news from the show Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
	   --The president of Toyota Motor Co. urged automakers to work together to
speed development of cars that pollute less.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can no longer afford to ignore the signs of global warming and the fact
that consumption of gasoline and other fossil fuels is on the rise," said Toyota
President Fujio Cho. "Environmentally friendly cars will soon cease to be an
option -- they will become a necessity."
</P>
<P>
	   --Honda said it would expand the hybrid engine technology it uses in its
Insight hatchback to other models in several years. The Insight pairs a
three-cylinder gas engine with an electric motor and battery pack to deliver gas
mileage of up to 70 mpg.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also said it would launch a series of cleaner gas engines this
year, and recommitted to building a car powered by fuel cells in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
