<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Despite Bond Market Slump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies on Wednesday,
despite a steep slump in the U.S. bond market.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0311, down from $1.0322.
The dollar was quoted at 105.98 Japanese yen, down slightly from 105.99 yen late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders in foreign-exchange markets are watching their moves this month amid
concerns that the Federal Reserve may boost rates at its meeting in February.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears over a rate hike sent bond prices falling Wednesday and the yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond rising to 6.71 percent, the highest level since July
1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Currency traders worry that a slump in stock and bond markets could dampen
demand for dollars as people look elsewhere around the world to invest their
money.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many people think that the Fed will take on a more aggressive rate position
and that's spooking a lot of investors," said Ricardo Gomes, head of foreign
exchange at HSBC USA.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.5627 Swiss francs, up from 1.5603, and
1.4541 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4567. The British pound was quoted at
$1.6477, unchanged from late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Wednesday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8969 German marks, up from 1.8948; 6.3614
French francs, up from 6.3549; and 1,877.78 Italian lire, up from 1,875.87.
</P>
</TEXT>
