<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton campaign asks for soft-money summit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign manager invited
his counterpart on Rudolph Giuliani's political team on Wednesday to negotiate a
mutual ban on the use of unlimited soft-money contributions in their expected
Senate race.
<P>
	   But Giuliani campaign chief Bruce Teitelbaum, in a subsequent letter to
Clinton campaign manager Bill de Blasio, said that before any such negotiations
could take place, the first lady would have to refund such money already spent
on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   "You should also determine how much soft money you have already raised and
publicly declare that none of that money will be used to benefit the Clinton
campaign in any way," the aide to the Republican mayor of New York City wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading letters, de Blasio criticized Giuliani's fund-raising activities and
said "we are disappointed that you are apparently rejecting our offer to meet."
</P>
<P>
	   Thus far, the national Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee has raised
several hundred thousand dollars in unlimited soft-money donations aimed at
helping Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign in New York. And, it spent more than
$200,000 to finance television ads across upstate New York late last year
promoting the first lady.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the DSCC, said
the committee was prepared to spend "whatever is required to win" New York's
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
	   Under fire for her use of soft money, Mrs. Clinton began pressing Giuliani
at the end of last year to agree to a ban on the use of such funding and to
disavow third-party advocacy advertising in their race. The Giuliani camp
demanded the proposal in writing before entering into such talks.
</P>
<P>
	   Howard Wolfson, spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's campaign team, said Wednesday
that de Blasio had telephoned Teitelbaum Tuesday to discuss the issue, was
unable to get through and left a message. Teitelbaum returned the call
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bruce said he would talk with his boss and get back to us," Wolfson
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Teitelbaum did so in his letter to de Blasio, and made it public.
</P>
<P>
	   "I agree this is a good opportunity to discuss the role that soft money will
play in the upcoming Senate race," the Giuliani aide wrote. "We must, however,
start the discussion on a level playing field."
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to demanding that Mrs. Clinton pay the cost of the DSCC-financed
TV ads out of her campaign account, Teitelbaum said "it would also be useful if
we could agree on an ironclad, verifiable method of accountability to ensure
that any agreement we reach will be honored throughout the campaign."
</P>
<P>
	   "Because of the soft money you have already raised, and the massive
fund-raising apparatus at your disposal, the issues of verification and trust
are of paramount concern to us," the Giuliani aide added.
</P>
<P>
	   Verification and trust was a concept promoted by President Reagan in his
dealings with the Soviets over arms control.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani has not been actively raising soft money for the Senate race,
he has not ruled out using such funds.
</P>
<P>
	   And de Blasio in his letter to Teitelbaum noted that third-party attack ads
aimed at Hillary Clinton have already appeared in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Under federal rules, Senate candidates can accept no more than $2,000 from
individual contributors to spend on their races. But those same contributors can
give unlimited money to political committees such as the DSCC that can then use
it to promote a candidate, as long as they don't directly ask you to vote for
that candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Wednesday, Mrs. Clinton appeared with the Rev. Jesse Jackson and U.S.
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers at a conference sponsored by Jackson's "Wall
Street Project."
</P>
<P>
	   At the event, the first lady proposed expanding micro-credit, small loans to
would-be entrepreneurs, and providing more small-business services to upstate
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
