<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Racial discrimination lawsuit filed against city police  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Police hunting for drug dealers turned a black actor's
professional performace into his real-life horror when they falsely arrested
him, according to a lawsuit filed Wednesday.
<P>
	   The civil rights action by Alton Fitzgerald White seeks unspecified damages
for violations of his constitutional rights to be free of false arrest, illegal
imprisonment and racial discrimination, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
	   White, 35, who has the lead in the current Broadway production of "Ragtime,"
continues to suffer severe emotional distress and damage to his reputation,
according to the lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's haunting him. As his manager, I see it every day. It was a real blow,"
said Renee Harriston.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit filed on his behalf by the New York Civil Liberties Union noted
that White's experience was not uncommon for black men. It cited a Dec. 1 state
attorney general report finding blacks are significantly more likely to be
stopped and arrested without legal justification than whites.
</P>
<P>
	   White's lawsuit stems from a July 16 encounter with police who came to his
Harlem apartment building in search of drug dealers. Instead, they found the
actor and three other black men and arrested them along with two Hispanic men.
</P>
<P>
	   The other three black men - Ronald C. Jackson, Christopher Montgomery and
Marcus McCollum - filed a separate federal lawsuit Wednesday seeking $2.22
million in damages. Jackson is the student activities coordinator at Columbia
University while Montgomery is a graduate student at Columbia and McCollum is a
clothing merchandiser for designer Donna Karan. All three were in White's
building helping a friend move.
</P>
<P>
	   "They didn't have any reason to stop me - it was because I am black," White
said in an interview with The Associated Press shortly after his arrest. "They
searched my bag and didn't find what they were looking for. There were so many
opportunities for them to let me go but they didn't."
</P>
<P>
	   But in a statement Wednesday, New York Police Department Deputy Commissioner
for Legal Matters George Grasso called the arrests "a clear-cut example of
police officers putting their lives on the line and acting well within the scope
of their duties to protect the lives of Mr. White and his neighbors. It is,
indeed, a shame that Mr. White refuses to understand this concept."
</P>
<P>
	   White has said his run-in with police has strengthened his performance as
Coalhouse Walker, the musician he plays in "Ragtime." In the musical set in
1906, Walker is harassed by white firemen as he drives through a small New York
town.
</P>
<P>
	   But the incident also left White deeply affected - he stayed in his
apartment for five days and missed five performances before he felt he had to
come to terms with the arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   "'Ragtime' is a very intense show - what my character has to go through and
what he has to say," White said. "As an actor that is a challenge, but as a
black man it's very upsetting. And that all occurs in 1906. We're in 1999 - what
happened to me is like an updated version of that."
</P>
<P>
	   White said he found it humiliating to be put "in a jail cell, strip searched
and then questioned three times."
</P>
<P>
	   At one point, realizing he would not make that night's performance, White
began weeping and repeatedly told the police he was innocent.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is standard procedure," was the answer cops gave him, White said.
</P>
<P>
	   Five hours later, White and his three black acquaintances were released.
Only the two Hispanic men - whom White contends he did not know - were charged
in connection with the drug sweep.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview last year, "Ragtime" author E.L. Doctorow said he was
saddened by White's arrest but was not surprised.
</P>
<P>
	   "Everytime a non-white person steps out of his door today he can expect his
humanity to be challenged," Doctorow said. "There's a deep fault line in
America's society, a fault line that runs through America's heart."
</P>
<P>
	   "These days the structural racism in this country finds its worst expression
in the culture of big city police departments - it seems to be the preferred
style in police work to violate rights and to debase people," said Doctorow, who
sent White a note expressing his sympathies.
</P>
<P>
	   "It didn't require any gift of prophesy on my part, in telling the story of
Coalhouse in epic terms," Doctorow said about his novel published in 1975. "In
writing about America 100 years ago, you are sadly talking about times today."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
