<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar at 8-Month Low; Grains Soar  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   The U.S. government's unexpected slashing of its estimate for the nation's
corn harvest sent prices rocketing higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade, generating hopes the market's lengthy slump may be ending.
</P>
<P>
	   Other grain futures and soybeans joined in the rally.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in commodity trading, crude oil prices forged an additional 2
percent higher and sugar sank to an eight-month low.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices rose 4 percent for the day, leaving the $2-a-bushel level far
behind and approaching the numbers of a year ago, after the Department of
Agriculture report was issued. Corn for March delivery rose 8 1/4 cents to $2.15
1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've ratcheted ourselves into a new trading level," said Dale Gustafson,
an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, reflecting an upbeat mood in the business
after months of languishing prices for not only corn but other agricultural
commodities.
</P>
<P>
	   At a time of year when crop estimates usually grow, the USDA lowered the
size of the estimated U.S. 1999 harvest by 100 million bushels to 9.4 billion
bushels. The total represents a 3 percent decline from the previous year but
still the fourth-largest on record.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn stocks were assessed at lower than expected, thanks to record usage of
corn as a livestock feed grain for the quarter. That's good news in a market
clouded by too much world supply.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a pretty positive report for everything," said Dean Nosker, an
analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Co. in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
	   "The only problem, and it's a big one, is we've got a lot of corn and
soybeans yet in farmers' hands," he said. "Those supplies are still hanging over
the market a bit. But today's report gave us a nudge in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices also were buoyed by USDA figures showing that American farmers
have planted the smallest acreage in wheat this winter since 1972 -- 8 percent
less than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans benefited from a cut, too -- the USDA said U.S. production declined
4 percent to 2.6 billion bushels, although it was still the third-biggest ever.
</P>
<P>
	   But market experts are not ready to proclaim a bull market for commodities
just yet.
</P>
<P>
	   "Before we can have a sustained bull market, we're going to have some
production problems resulting from bad weather either in the United States or in
South America," said Brenda Tucker, an analyst for AgResource Co. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   March wheat rose 5 cents to $2.58 3/4 a bushel, March oats rose 1 3/4 cents
to $1.10 1/4 a bushel and March soybeans rose 5 3/4 cents to $4.80 1/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   The week's strong rally in oil futures proceeded on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, wiping out all the price losses of a six-day decline.
</P>
<P>
	   Keeping the momentum going was news that Saudi Arabia's and Venezuela's oil
ministers will meet in Amsterdam on Thursday -- more evidence of continuing
unity among top producers who have driven prices higher.
</P>
<P>
	   February crude rose 51 cents to $26.28. In other energy commodities,
February heating oil rose 1.72 cents to 68.47 cents a gallon, February gasoline
rose 2.55 cents to 71.27 cents a gallon and February natural gas fell 2 cents to
$2.224 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, February Brent crude rose 19 cents to $24.81 on the International
Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Sugar plummeted 4 percent on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange.
March sugar lost 0.22 cent to 5.45 cents a pound after earlier reaching its
lowest level for an active contract, 5.42 cents, since last May.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices have been spiraling lower due to a world glut. No. 1 producer Brazil
has a record cane crop, and the USDA on Wednesday increased its estimate of U.S.
sugar production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
