<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jail guards plead guilty to fatal beating of Nassau Jail inmate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) - Two Nassau County corrections officers pleaded
guilty Wednesday to federal civil rights charges for fatally beating a
recovering heroin addict in his cell at the county jail.
<P>
	   The guards, Patrick Regnier and Edward Velazquez, changed their pleas to
guilty before U.S. District Court Judge Jacob Mishler. They opted to plead after
a third guard cut a deal last week, admitting that he served as the lookout on
Jan. 8, 1999. He also agreed to testify against his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Velazquez, under questioning from the judge, admitted that he went to Thomas
Pizzuto's cell "to quiet him down and use unreasonable force if necessary." When
prodded by the judge, Regnier admitted: "I did land on him with my knees. I did
punch him in the back."
</P>
<P>
	   The prisoner was crying out for his methadone treatment. Pizzuto, 38, of
Hicksville, was serving a 90-day sentence for traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Three days after the beating, he suffered a seizure and died. The Nassau
County medical examiner found that Pizzuto had suffered a ruptured spleen and
ruled the death a homicide.
</P>
<P>
	   The courtroom was packed Wednesday, with Pizzuto's mother, widow and
wheelchair-bound father weeping quietly during the 70-minute session. Outside,
dozens of corrections officers stood quietly in support of their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
	   "I cried," Carol Pizzuto said at the sight of the supporters. "I walked up
here today and I cried, because I couldn't believe this is the world that we
live in. That these people are backing up murderers ... to my face. How could
they do that?"
</P>
<P>
	   None of the corrections officers wanted to speak with reporters outside the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount of prison time the accused pair faces at their April 7 sentencing
will be determined by Mishler after a hearing on whether Pizzuto's death
amounted to murder or manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
	   A ruling that the death was the result of murder could bring each guard up
to life in prison, while a manslaughter ruling would yield a sentence of between
3 1/2 and 12 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Pizzuto said she hopes they receive the maximum.
</P>
<P>
	   "They pled for mercy, they showed my son no mercy," Mrs. Pizzuto said
outside the courthouse, tears streaming down her face.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense case suffered a major setback last week when a third guard
charged in the case, Ivano Bavaro, pleaded guilty to federal conspiracy and
witness tampering charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Bavaro admitted that he acted as a lookout while Velazquez and Regnier went
into Pizzuto's cell and pounded the inmate into silence.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial against a fourth guard, Joseph Bergen, accused of filing a false
report indicating that Pizzuto had slipped in the shower, is scheduled to start
next week.
</P>
<P>
	   The East Meadow jail, which houses about 1,800 inmates and is patrolled by
approximately 1,100 guards, has been the subject of numerous allegations of
guard misconduct. Following Pizzuto's death and other allegations of abuse, the
U.S. Department of Justice began an investigation of how inmates there are
treated.
</P>
<P>
	   Last March, a Nassau County correction officer was found liable in the
beating of a mentally retarded jail inmate with a frying pan in 1993. County
officials agreed to a $500,000 settlement in the inmate's civil rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bottom line here is they all plead guilty, really, to causing Thomas
Pizzuto's death and vindicated everything that this family has said about how it
happened," said attorney Barry Scheck, who represents the family in a civil
lawsuit against the jail.
</P>
<P>
	   "The truth of the matter is that this has been going on for a long time in
the Nassau County Jail and everybody knows it," said Scheck. "There have been
civil suits that have been successfully brought against these guards and yet
nothing is done about it. And there's a code of silence and this code of silence
has to be broken."
</P>
<P>
	   Sheriff Joseph Jablonsky, whose jurisdiction included the jail, retired late
last year. A replacement has yet to be hired.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokeswoman for County Executive Thomas Gulotta had no comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
