<DOCNO> APW20000112.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Puts Ocalan Hanging On Hold  </HEADLINE>
   By SUZAN FRASER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's government on Wednesday put on hold the
execution of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, a move aimed at enhancing the
country's prospects for joining the European Union.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision, which came after coalition leaders met for eight hours, came
in response to a request from the European Court of Human Rights to review
Ocalan's appeal. The rebel leader was sentenced to death in June by a Turkish
court.
</P>
<P>
	   Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema expressed ``great satisfaction'' with
Turkey's decision, saying ``the choice confirms the evolution of Turkish
politics towards Europe and its democratic principles.'' A Rome city official
said the colosseum would be lit up in the coming days to mark the decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit warned that the execution was only
delayed, not canceled.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the rebel organization and its supporters attempt to use this process
against the high interests of the state, then the process of delaying will be
halted and the process of execution will be started immediately,'' Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecevit's warning was an apparent attempt to appease the far-right National
Action Party, which has pressed for Ocalan's hanging, and relatives of those who
lost their lives fighting against the Kurdish rebels, who seek autonomy in
southeastern Turkey. Some 37,000 people, mostly Kurds, have died in the fighting
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The leaders made a very wrong decision,'' said Mehdi Keskin, a lawyer for
Turks who lost family in the fighting. ``They have made the martyrs' families'
consciences bleed.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Ecevit said Ocalan's death sentence cannot be overruled.
</P>
<P>
	   He also made clear that Turkey would not wait long. Review of the case in
the European court could take up to two years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This decision does not mean that we will agree for a delay under any
condition that will last forever,'' Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
	   Turkey has not executed anyone since 1984. European countries have all
abolished the death penalty and are urging Turkey to do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The execution would cause more tension in Turkey and would not be good for
Turkey's society and industry,'' Wolfgang Peukart, an official of the European
court, said at a meeting in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
	   The EU named Turkey a candidate for membership last month -- a huge step for
the country, which has been working toward joining the union since 1963.
</P>
<P>
	   Leading up to Wednesday's meeting, speculation had grown that the issue
could trigger a breakup of Ecevit's government. The nationalists came to power
on a campaign promise to execute Ocalan and are under pressure from their
electorate to immediately send the Kurdish rebel's case to parliament for
approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Wednesday, hundreds of nationalist supporters gathered in the
capital, Ankara, at the funeral of soldiers killed in clashes with rebels
Sunday. They booed President Suleyman Demirel -- who favors waiting for the
European Court's ruling -- calling him a ``traitor.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Do not bargain on the blood of our martyrs!'' they shouted before marching
in downtown Ankara. They called on the government to resign.
</P>
<P>
	   Kurds also have also voiced their concern. On Tuesday, 37 elected mayors of
Turkey's only legal political Kurdish movement, the People's Democracy Party,
urged the leaders not to hang Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecevit fears that hanging Ocalan could anger the Kurdish rebel group and
revive violence in southeastern Turkey. There has been a relative lull in
fighting in that region since Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party, known as the
PKK, announced a cease-fire and withdrawal from Turkey in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Storms Leave $3 Billion Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL-HENRI DU LIMBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- Storms last month that have left thousands of people still
without electricity or phone service will cost French public services $3
billion, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said France will give about $630 million in direct aid to those
affected both by the devastating storms and by an oil spill that hit the
country's Atlantic coast over the same period.
</P>
<P>
	   The cost of fixing the electricity service alone came to $2.7 billion,
Jospin told a news conference. There was another $79 million worth of damage
done to the road network and the same amount done to the railroads. It cost $157
million to fix the national phone company, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The prime minister also outlined a ``forest plan'' to help replace the
thousands of trees ripped down by the gale-force winds and said it would cost
nearly $1 billion over the next decade. At least 741,000 acres of forest were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ninety people died in storm-related accidents over the Christmas holidays
and on Wednesday, 26,000 homes were still without telephone service, while about
10,000 lacked electricity. Many people are still repairing roofs and hauling
away fallen trees.
</P>
<P>
	   The European Union on Wednesday denied a request from France for more storm
aid, saying some of the $5.4 billion the country gets over the next six years
could be used for reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, the European Commission, the EU's executive arm, said France
could apply for further storm aid under other programs, such as the rural or
fishery development aid programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
