<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Bond Prices Fall Again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bond prices fell for a third consecutive session
Wednesday, sending long-term yields to a 2 1/2-year high, as inflation jitters
sapped demand for U.S. Treasurys.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond fell 7/16 point, or $4.37 1/2 cents per $1,000
in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.71
percent from 6.67 percent late Tuesday. That's the highest closing yield for
long-term Treasurys since it closed at that level on July 2, 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond traders have been edgy in advance of next month's meeting of Federal
Reserve policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised rates three times last year. There are expectations of
another boost in rates to cool off the economy and keep inflation under control
now that fears of a Year 2000 computer disaster have dissipated. But analysts
are divided on how much higher rates will go.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors will get a better reading on inflation on Thursday and Friday,
when the federal government issues reports on wholesale and consumer prices. In
addition, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan speaks to economists in New York on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates hurt bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
	   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities fell 1/16
point to 3/16 point and intermediate maturities fell 5/16 point to  1/4 point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.43 percent as the discount rose
0.01 percentage point from Tuesday to 5.28 percent. Six-month yields were 5.69
percent, as the discount rose 0.05 percentage point from Tuesday to 5.45
percent. One-year yields were 6.11 percent as the discount rose 0.02 percentage
point from late Tuesday to 5.76 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was
5.50 percent, up from 5.25 percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer said the new contract for its index
of 40 actively traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 to 91 7/16. The average yield to
maturity rose to 6.29 percent from 6.28 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
