<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small college prepares for Clinton visit while mourning death of  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - As the staff of a small Brooklyn college prepares for
President Clinton's visit on Thursday, they're also mourning the death of one of
their colleagues, found murdered there earlier this week.
<P>
	   Who killed Jorge Cordova remained a mystery Wednesday. According to initial
police reports, investigators thought the 46-year-old had fallen down the stairs
at Boricua College, and, in a freak accident, punctured his chest with the pens
in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
	   But on Wednesday, the medical examiner's office ruled Cordova's death a
homicide. That puncture wound came from a bullet.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton is slated to help launch a small business development center on
Thursday at the private, four-year bilingual institution. The more than 1,000
students are predominantly Latino.
</P>
<P>
	   The president's visit will continue as planned, said White House spokesman
Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is obviously a tragedy, but the president very much wants to visit the
college," Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cordova was found unconscious inside the school with a puncture wound and
blood on his chest after officers responded to a 911 call from Assistant Dean
John Guzman about a noise, police said. Cordova was taken to Woodhull Hospital
where he was pronounced dead shortly after 8 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   He had worked as a maintenance worker for about five years, said his boss,
Angel Reyes.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was a happy person - he never spoke about any enemies or anything like
that," Reyes said. "Everybody here loved him."
</P>
<P>
	   Cordova's family could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Neighbor Julissa Pena said Cordova, his wife, and their two daughters - ages
15 and 18 - were like family to her.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was a great father and also he was a good housewife, because he would
always be planting flowers. He would always cook," said Ms. Pena, 17.
</P>
<P>
	   She said her building's residents will miss Cordova's singing and guitar
playing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every Saturday he would play his music loud and he would sing because he's
a great singer," Ms. Pena said, adding that Cordova was originally from Puerto
Rico, and came to the city when he was a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was a very friendly, very nice person," she said. "He used to come to my
house to put up the curtains, help out with anything we needed, help put in the
air conditioner, anything like that."
</P>
<P>
	   -----
</P>
<P>
	   Cordova's address: 359 S. 2nd St., Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
	   School address: 9 Graham Ave., Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1800 </TRAILER>
