<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Leader Rejects U.S. Aid  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez declined an
American offer Wednesday to send two shiploads of troops and equipment to help
after devastating floods, saying his country can handle the work on its own.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement came a day after Pentagon officials said one Navy ship had
already left from Norfolk, Va. en route to Venezuela, and another was scheduled
to depart on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The USS Tortuga and the USS Nashville were to transport bulldozers, tractors
and engineering equipment along with about 450 Marine and Navy engineers who
were to lend a hand in clearing part of a key coastal road damaged in the floods
last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez told reporters that while Venezuela still needs more money, equipment
and other materials, additional relief workers aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to clarify before Venezuela and the world that North American
troops are not going to come to Venezuela,'' Chavez said. ``If they want to send
machines or other types of equipment we are open to that, and we are very
thankful for the intention to help.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was not clear if the ships would be sent home given Chavez's comments and
spokespeople at the U.S. Embassy in Caracas, the State Department in Washington
and the U.S. military headquarters for Latin America in Miami had no immediate
comment. The troops were to be stationed in Venezuela for two months.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue of U.S. troops in Venezuela is a sensitive one, given Chavez's
left-leaning politics. A former army paratrooper, Chavez last year refused to
allow U.S. planes to fly over Venezuelan territory in anti-narcotics
reconnaissance flights.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez has also bolstered relations between Venezuela and communist Cuba,
and he often speaks of the need to reduce the U.S. influence in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 15,000 and 30,000 people were killed after floods Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the United States has played a key role in international efforts to
assist Venezuela, providing airplanes, ships, soldiers, water purification
machines, medicine, money and other aid. Chavez accepted the initial U.S. aid
with open arms.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez said Wednesday that the disaster relief effort had moved into a
second phase following the rescue and evacuation of tens of thousands of flood
survivors. The new phase involves repairing and constructing roads, schools,
hospitals, houses and other buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
