<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet May Face Charges in Chile  </HEADLINE>
   By KRISTIN GAZLAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Pressure mounted on Britain's top law enforcement official
Wednesday to release medical records that may spell freedom for ailing former
Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet, detained for 15 months on charges of
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
	   The human rights group Amnesty International demanded that Home Secretary
Jack Straw release the records, at least to Spain -- as well as to France,
Switzerland and Belgium, which also requested Pinochet's extradition claiming
their citizens suffered abuses during his 1973-90 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Many victims of Pinochet's crimes and the families of those who have been
murdered will feel betrayed if Pinochet is released on the basis of medical
evidence which is not going to be disclosed,'' said Geoffrey Bindman, an Amnesty
attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   Straw announced Tuesday that an independent medical exam on Jan. 5 by four
physicians was ``unequivocal and unanimous'' in finding the 84-year-old general
too ill to stand trial, opening the door for him to return to Chile within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel's findings were not disclosed, although Straw told the House of
Commons that criteria considered included whether Pinochet would be able to
follow the proceedings, assist in his own defense and give coherent testimony.
Pinochet suffered two minor strokes in September. He also has diabetes and
arthritis and wears a pacemaker.
</P>
<P>
	   Straw gave the parties involved seven days to submit arguments before he
issues a final ruling on extradition to Spain, but gave no timetable for his
decision.
</P>
<P>
	   He noted that Pinochet had been asked to allow Spain and the other countries
involved to read copies of the medical report, but that the general ``declined
to do so.''
</P>
<P>
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair's Downing Street office issued a statement
Wednesday saying Pinochet was entitled to his privacy. In Washington, White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, ``This is a legal matter between Chile and
Spain.''
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet was said by friends to be ``delighted'' by the latest twist in his
case. But his son said the family would put off celebrations until the general
boards a plane home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A possibility indeed has opened for his return, but there is nothing firm
yet,'' Marco Antonio Pinochet said at a news conference in Santiago.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he talked Wednesday with his mother, Lucia, who told him Pinochet
received the news ``with a lot of calm, but little optimism. He remains
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
	   If Straw rules against extradition, Pinochet's opponents have a few
alternatives, all viewed as long shots -- appealing to the High Court;
attempting to launch a private prosecution; or convincing Britain's director of
public prosecutions to bring action.
</P>
<P>
	   But even if Pinochet returns to Chile, he faces the prospect of prosecution.
</P>
<P>
	   Pablo Cabrera, Chile's ambassador in London, said Chilean law has been
amended since the closing days of the Pinochet regime, when the dictator passed
a wide-ranging law granting himself immunity from prosecution. Pinochet
relinquished power in 1990, and became a senator for life.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The law in Chile allows the people and the tribunal to strip off immunity,
as has been done already with another senator for other reasons,'' Cabrera told
BBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet has been detained in Britain since his Oct. 16, 1998, arrest in a
London hospital on the Spanish warrant. He is accused of using torture to
intimidate and silence political opponents throughout his dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   An official Chilean government report says 3,197 people -- including
citizens of Spain and other countries -- died or disappeared after the general
led a coup to topple the elected Marxist president, Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the Spanish government said it would not challenge Britain's
decision, legal and human rights activists in Spain said the 15-month legal
battle against Pinochet proved that no one is above the law.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What's been important in all of this case has been to fight impunity,''
said Joan Garces, a lawyer for families of Pinochet victims who also worked with
Judge Baltasar Garzon, the Spanish investigative magistrate who filed the
extradition request that led to Pinochet's detention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whether the case takes place in Spain or in another country is beside the
point,'' Garces said. ``We have already won this case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
