<HEADLINE> MCI Head Defends Sprint Merger  </HEADLINE>
    By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- MCI WorldCom's proposed marriage with long-distance
carrier Sprint is a "pro-consumer act," MCI WorldCom chief Bernard Ebbers said
Wednesday as he outlined steps the company will take to promote competition.
</P>
<P>
	   Ebbers sought to counter criticism that the deal between the No. 2 MCI
WorldCom and No. 3 Sprint, announced in October and originally valued at $115
billion, would hurt consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   "These concerns rest on a perception that's way out of date," Ebbers said at
the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
	   Ebbers, the company's president and chief executive officer, also used the
event to announce some new offerings forthcoming from MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
	   Soon after Bell Atlantic's rollout of combined local-long-distance calling
packages in New York, MCI WorldCom plans to offer its own all-distance service
in New York in about a month, Ebbers said. The package will include a large
variety of minutes, covering both local and long-distance calls, for a fixed
monthly fee, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ebbers said the company is developing a plan in New York for people who do
not make a large volume calls, without a monthly fee or minimum usage charge.
Consumer groups long have protested such fixed charges, saying that they are
keeping the cost of long-distance high for those that are infrequent callers.
</P>
<P>
	   That package eventually will be available nationwide, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ebbers also pledged that the merged company, within a year of closing the
deal, would accelerate its introduction of high-speed Internet connections --
delivered over Sprint's wireless network -- in rural and under-served areas.
</P>
<P>
	   But he added: "This deployment would not be possible and will not be
possible without our merger."
</P>
<P>
	   Addressing concerns that the marriage could raise prices, Ebbers asserted
that a combined MCI WorldCom/Sprint would not lead consumers to see even a 5
percent price increase in the markets the companies touch.
</P>
<P>
	   He attributed that to the level of competition already in the industry, with
some 600 long-distance carriers nationwide. Local Bell companies entering the
long-distance business will only add fuel to that fire, Ebbers said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bell Atlantic received permission last month to offer long-distance market
to its New York customers, and SBC Communications asked regulators this week for
approval to do the same in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is too much competition and too much capacity," Ebbers said.
</P>
<P>
	   When the deal was announced, Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill
Kennard said the companies would "bear a heavy burden to show how consumers
would be better off." Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in charge of
the Justice Department's antitrust division, also promised at the time that the
deal would get "a very serious and thorough review."
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, Ebbers told reporters the company is confident with "minor
modifications" it will be able to make its case to regulators. The companies
hope to close their deal by the middle or third quarter of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
