<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Concept Car Creates Buzz  </HEADLINE>
    By JIM SUHR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- For years, auto shows have been used to debut
not-ready-for-prime-time cars, new ideas dressed up with gadgets and gizmos.
</P>
<P>
	   Automakers hope these concept cars create a buzz, much like Ford Motor's
"021C" -- a model one observer called deliberately controversial in blurring the
line between prototype and stunt.
</P>
<P>
	   Named by Ford Chief Executive Jac Nasser after the specific color of its
deep orange paint, the "retro-futuristic" machine looks like a first-grader's
sketch.
</P>
<P>
	   It has four doors, a single oval headlight and one tail light, swiveling
seats, and a trunk that slides open like a drawer.
</P>
<P>
	   The 021C is the brainchild of Australian-born designer Marc Newson, whom
Ford hired for one reason: he'd never created a car before. Newson has said he
wanted the car to be simple and naive, "like an egg in an egg cup."
</P>
<P>
	   But some people just don't get it.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought kind of like, 'Is Ford developing a Jetsons division?,"' said
AutoPacific Inc. analyst George Peterson, who first saw the 021C when it was
unveiled last October at the Tokyo auto show. The 021C reappeared here this week
at the North American International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
	   Peterson said the car was rolled out simply to get attention. But, he added,
that's what car shows are for: "If nothing else, it got people to come into the
exhibit."
</P>
<P>
	   Mission accomplished for J Mays, Ford's design chief. Despite lukewarm
reviews for the 021C in media circles, Mays still beams about the attention
awarded to a machine he calls simple, honest and engaging.
</P>
<P>
	   "As expected, there have been some in the automotive press that didn't
understand it," Mays said, asserting that the industry -- Ford included -- has
been stuck in a design rut. "The point behind it is to reach a new generation of
customers not absolutely driven by a love for the auto, but who have an interest
in pop culture. Autos are supposed to be different."
</P>
<P>
	   Mays wouldn't say whether the 021C has any production potential beyond the
concept stage, which automakers traditionally use to gauge public reaction
before making the big investment needed to put their prototypes on the market.
</P>
<P>
	   While some elements of the 021C could show up in future cars -- including
its underseat storage and pillarless door frames -- some analysts say the whole
package will never make it to the showroom.
</P>
<P>
	   "You could build it, but where does it fit in the product lineup?" asked Jim
Hall, AutoPacific's vice president of industry analysis. "It could be the
next-generation Ford car, but I don't think that's what they want the car to be.
It's Ford's way of saying there are better ways to automotive designs. I won't
say it's a wakeup call, but an announcement."
</P>
<P>
	   The 021C has its fans. Jack Keebler, the Detroit editor of Motor Trend
magazine, said the car had a "studied naivete."
</P>
<P>
	   "This is an incredibly sophisticated car," Keebler said. "It looks simple,
but no one would look at an egg and say that's a simple design. ... Paint it
black and I want one."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1835 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
