<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Right To Sue Polluters Upheld  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Private citizens won assurances from the Supreme Court on
Wednesday that they can seek enforcement of environmental laws against
polluters.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices, in a 7-2 decision, upheld citizen groups' right to sue an
alleged polluter even if the group were not directly harmed by the pollution or
could prove financial damages.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling also said polluters sued by private citizens cannot necessarily
avoid paying damages by stopping their misconduct during litigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision involved the dumping of toxic chemicals into a stream from a
South Carolina hazardous waste incinerator. Friends of the Earth and several
other environmental groups sued incinerator's operator in 1992, although these
groups were not directly harmed by the pollution.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling ``assures that citizens ... have the right to go to court to
enforce environmental laws,'' said Lois Schiffer, assistant attorney general for
environment and natural resources, applauding the court's finding.
</P>
<P>
	   The case against Laidlaw Environmental Services, operator of the
incinerator, was a test of the Clean Water Act's provision that allows private
citizens to file lawsuits to help enforce the law. Under the law, citizens can
seek an end to misconduct, plus financial penalties to be paid to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This case had the potential to severely limit a citizen's ability to
enforce the Clean Water Act.,'' said Brian Dunkiel of Friends of the Earth. ``We
... are pleased that the court has maintained the status quo'' on citizen
participation.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit dealt with Laidlaw's operation of its waste incinerator in Roebuck,
S.C., that discharged wastewater into the North Tyger River.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time a federal judge ruled on the lawsuit in 1997, Laidlaw had come
into compliance of the Clean Water Act. While the judge found that the
environmental groups were not entitled to an order to deter future violations,
he imposed $405,800 in civil penalties for past violations.
</P>
<P>
	   A year later, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the penalty.
It said that once the judge decided not to ban future violations, the only
remaining remedy -- a civil penalty -- was not appropriate because it would not
benefit the groups who filed suit. Under the law, the money had to be paid to
the government.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Supreme Court said the civil penalty was intended to deter future
misconduct, and therefore it would, in fact, benefit the environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices ordered the case returned to a lower court to determine whether
Laidlaw could show that the case was moot because future violations could not be
expected to occur.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Congress has found that civil penalties in the Clean Water Act cases do
more than promote immediate compliance ... they also deter future violations,''
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A defendant's voluntary cessation of allegedly unlawful conduct ordinarily
does not suffice to moot a case,'' Ginsburg added. A case might be declared moot
if it were clear that the unlawful conduct could not reasonably be expected to
reoccur, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ginsburg's opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H.
Souter and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
	   Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas dissented. Writing for the two,
Scalia said the ruling permited ``law enforcement to be placed in the hands of
private individuals.''
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Friends of the Earth vs. Laidlaw Environmental Services, 98-822.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Logo Switch Raises Questions  </HEADLINE>
    By HANNAH WOLFSON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS News may have sacrificed journalistic ethics for the
sake of business by superimposing digital images of its logo over that of a
competitor during its newscast, media observers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS officials said they did nothing wrong when they used digital technology
to layer their name over a large NBC screen and a Budweiser advertisement during
live broadcasts of "CBS Evening News" from Times Square on Dec. 30 and Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Although digital imaging has been used before to insert advertising on TV
screens during sports and entertainment programs, the leap into news has raised
questions about how it should be used.
</P>
<P>
	   "When there's new technology, the ethical rules have to be restated or
firmed up," said Richard T. Kaplar, vice president of The Media Institute, a
nonprofit think tank in Washington. "This may seem like an innocent little
corporate coup, but there are bigger implications in terms of eroding people's
confidence in what they see on the screen."
</P>
<P>
	   CBS' morning show, "The Early Show," has used the technology routinely since
its Nov. 1 debut to make it seem that a large CBS advertisement is attached to
the General Motors building in New York, where the show originates.
</P>
<P>
	   But CBS News President Andrew Heyward said the decision to use the
technology during the ultra-competitive millennium broadcast did trigger
internal debate, though there was no talk of notifying viewers.
</P>
<P>
	   "Reasonable people could disagree whether it is an appropriate use of
digital technology," Heyward said, "and like any new technology it poses new
issues we have to address on a case-by-case basis."
</P>
<P>
	   Heyward also said CBS has a "core principle" of not deceiving the audience,
and he doesn't believe the imaging violated that principle any more than the
standard use of printed graphics on the television screen.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS spokeswoman Kim Akhtar said Dan Rather knew during the newscast that
digital technology was being used to project the logo behind him, but was not
notified in advance.
</P>
<P>
	   ABC sparked controversy in 1994, when Washington correspondent Cokie Roberts
was introduced as reporting from the Capitol when she was actually standing in
the studio in front of an image of Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a mistake," said Eileen Murphy, spokeswoman for ABC News. "It should
never have happened and you won't see that happening again."
</P>
<P>
	   Although ABC uses digital imaging to create graphics for Monday Night
Football, including the first down markers only TV spectators can see, Murphy
said viewer credibility is too important to try it with the news. In a 1998
Gallup poll, 66 percent of respondents said they trust nightly network news and
CNN, a number topped only by local TV news.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have an obligation to your viewers in news programming to be truthful,
and we just see it as being a bit manipulative," Murphy said. "It could have the
potential to raise questions in viewer's minds."
</P>
<P>
	   Aly Colon of The Poynter Institute for Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla.
agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   "If what's behind (Dan Rather) is not accurate or real, then is what he is
saying or where he is or what he's trying to convey any more authentic than the
environment he's in?" Colon asked.
</P>
<P>
	   NBC said it has never used digital imaging during its nightly newscasts and
has no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Digital manipulation is not limited to television. Time magazine apologized
to readers in 1994 for featuring a darkened version of O.J. Simpson's mug shot
on its cover. And many newspapers have policies against the use of
digitally-enhanced photos.
</P>
<P>
	   But with technology accelerating, Colon said, the famous wall between the
journalistic and the business sides of the news may need shoring up.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have to think about why those walls are there and if you're going to
vault over them, what that implies," Colon said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that it's going to be a very challenging element that the news
industry will have to address in terms of who's going to be responsible for the
news."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1837 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
