<HEADLINE> Teen Buddhist Leader Meets Devotees  </HEADLINE>
   By DEEPAK SHARMA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- The teen-age Buddhist leader who recently fled
Chinese-controlled Tibet met with devotees Wednesday while he rested at a
secluded monastery under tight security.
</P>
<P>
	   The 17th Karmapa gave red ribbons and grapes to his barefooted visitors, who
entered the Gyuto monastery in groups of 10 to 20 people and presented the
14-year-old lama with white scarves, said one of the devotees, who uses only the
name Dawa.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa, leader of one of the four main streams of Tibetan Buddhism,
fled Tibet and arrived in Dharmsala a week ago after an eight-day trek over the
Himalayas. He moved on Sunday to the Gyuto monastery in Sidvari, 10 miles
southeast of Dharmsala, the Dalai Lama's home in exile.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, the Karmapa expressed his happiness that the Tibetan community
and others are making efforts to help him, Dawa said.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 50 Indian security men ringed the monastery. Some carried AK-47
assault rifles. All visitors were frisked twice, by Indian police and the Dalai
Lama's guards.
</P>
<P>
	   A man who claimed to be the Karmapa's uncle was questioned by Indian police
Wednesday after he protested outside the monastery and demanded to be allowed to
meet the lama.
</P>
<P>
	   Mamgiyal, who gave only one name, said the Karmapa's mother was in serious
condition and thousands of his supporters were thronging his home in Tibet,
anxious for information on the whereabouts and condition of the leader.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa was recuperating at Gyuto with his principal teacher and
devotee, the Tai Situ Rinpoche.
</P>
<P>
	   About 130,000 Tibetans have fled to India since the Dalai Lama, Tibetan
Buddhism's supreme leader, escaped during a foiled uprising against Chinese rule
in 1959. Most of them are registered as refugees, a status they must renew every
year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Indian Foreign Ministry said it has not received a formal request for
the Karmapa's political asylum. On Tuesday, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman
Zhu Bangzao advised India to keep relations between the two neighbors in mind
when dealing with the Karmapa, but stopped short of saying India should deny him
asylum.
</P>
<P>
	   Bangzao reminded India of its recognition of Chinese sovereignty over Tibet
and a commitment to prevent the Dalai Lama from engaging in political activity
from Indian territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
