<HEADLINE> Doctors Warned on Flu Drugs  </HEADLINE>
    By LAURAN NEERGAARD AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government warned doctors Wednesday to make sure they
appropriately prescribe those heavily advertised -- but only somewhat helpful --
new flu drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   The Food and Drug Administration is looking into a handful of reports of
patients possibly treated inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
	   The warning also comes because the nation is in what health officials say
appears to be a normal influenza epidemic -- lots of misery but so far no worse
than each year's epidemic -- yet influenza is getting tremendous media
attention. Also, new flu drugs Relenza and Tamiflu are being promoted heavily.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want to make certain that physicians aren't thinking of these drugs
before they would think to use antibiotics" or other medicines, said FDA
antiviral chief Dr. Heidi Jolson.
</P>
<P>
	   FDA's first warning: Flu drugs do not prevent people from catching
influenza. Vaccination is the best way to do that.
</P>
<P>
	   It is not too late to be vaccinated, although some regions may start running
low on vaccine, said Dr. Keiji Fukuda of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. He advised people at highest risk -- the elderly and people with
chronic heart or lung conditions such as asthma -- to ask their doctor about
vaccination.
</P>
<P>
	   When doctors do prescribe the new flu drugs, the FDA warned:
</P>
<P>
	   --Patients with severe flu-like symptoms, especially those with chronic
medical conditions, may have serious bacterial infections like pneumonia instead
of influenza. Neither the new Relenza and Tamiflu, nor two older flu medicines,
can help bacterial pneumonia. Those patients need antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
	   The FDA has received reports of three people who died from bacterial
infections who at least initially may have been given flu drugs instead of
antibiotics, Jolson said.
</P>
<P>
	   --The flu drugs only work if taken within the first 48 hours of flu symptoms
-- and they then reduce flu symptoms only by about a day.
</P>
<P>
	   "If they are used, it should be with a realistic expectation of the likely
benefit from the drugs, which I would characterize as modest," Jolson said.
</P>
<P>
	   --Use special caution in prescribing Relenza, which is an inhaled drug, to
patients with underlying asthma or other lung disease because it might trigger
asthma attacks or wheezing. Although Relenza comes with a warning about that
side effect, the FDA has received four reports of asthma attacks in such
patients, a small number but one that signaled doctors needed a reminder, Jolson
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Wednesday, the FDA revealed that in November it had ordered Relenza
manufacturer Glaxo Wellcome to stop airing misleading television ads implying
the drug is more effective than it really is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arguments on Grandparent Rights  </HEADLINE>
   By REBECCA SINDERBRAND Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As arguments over grandparent visitation rights were
ending Wednesday inside the Supreme Court, the squabbles outside were just
getting started.
</P>
<P>
	   Small knots of protesters spilled onto the sidewalk outside the court
building and confronted each other verbally, as lawyers and outside
organizations on both sides of the issue took turns repeating the day's court
arguments for waiting reporters and television cameras.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The grandparents and children have needs that have to be considered as
well'' as the parents' wishes, said Mark Olson, attorney for Tommie Granville
Wynn, mother of Natalie, 10, and Isabelle, 8.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't think any of us are in a position to know what's in the best
interest of children. Parents are the ones in that position,'' said attorney
Catherine Smith, who represented Gary and Jennifer Troxel, the children's
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
	   Brad Troxel, the couple's son and the girls' father, committed suicide in
1993.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Children have a right to have contact with their grandparents,'' said
Davis Levy, president of the Children's Rights Council, an organization whose
stated goal is to ``demilitarize the divorce process to ensure children remain
in contact with parents and extended family.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the Family Research Council handed out a statement which read, in
part, ``In the age of splintered families, the government needs to uphold the
family unit, not break it down by granting unrelated third parties equal access
to children.''
</P>
<P>
	   At least one grandfather standing outside the court agreed with the FRC. ``I
think parents have the right to raise children the way they see fit. As long as
they're fit parents, this is a decision the parents have to make,'' said Carl
Argiroff of Livonia, Mich.
</P>
<P>
	   But there was a large group of very vocal senior citizens on hand who
supported the Troxels. ``If it wasn't for grandparents, the grandkids wouldn't
even be here!'' yelled a man on the edge of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
	   Jennifer Troxel sounded tired as she remarked, ``It's been good to have a
day in court, but I'm glad it's finally over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
