<HEADLINE> Ivorian Opposition Joins Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- A leading opposition party on Wednesday joined
Ivory Coast's interim government, ending the West African country's first major
political deadlock since junta soldiers took power in a Christmas Eve coup.
</P>
<P>
	   Four members of the Ivorian Popular Front (FPI) took part in their first
Cabinet meeting Wednesday along with 17 other ministers drawn from the army and
other parties, said Emile Doudou Boga, a senior FPI official.
</P>
<P>
	   The FPI originally had refused to join the Cabinet, complaining that Gen.
Robert Guei had offered them only four ministerial positions.
</P>
<P>
	   The party eventually changed its position after Guei offered another two
Cabinet posts, Boga said. The new ministers are expected to be announced later
this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Guei emerged as Ivory Coast's first junta leader during the coup, which
toppled President Henri Konan Bedie. It was the first-ever military takeover in
Ivory Coast -- one of Africa's most prosperous and stable nations -- since its
independence from France in 1960.
</P>
<P>
	   The interim government is led by Guei, who declared himself president and
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
	   The FPI's rivals, the Rally of the Republicans (RDR), was officially given
three Cabinet posts. However, the FPI earlier complained that as many as 10
ministers were RDR supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   RDR leader Alassane Dramane Ouattara on Wednesday welcomed the opposition
party's decision.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am happy to note today that the FPI is entering the transition
government. Now we have to see how the government will function,'' Ouattara
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Guei has said the interim government will rule Ivory Coast until elections
can be held, but he has not given a timetable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
