<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal judge appoints monitor to oversee troubled boxing group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A federal judge on Wednesday appointed a New Jersey
lawyer as monitor for the scandal-ridden IBF, the first time a U.S. sports
organization has come under a stewardship generally reserved for mob-riddled
labor unions.
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge John W. Bissell appointed Joseph A. Hayden Jr. to
oversee the operations of the East Orange-based International Boxing Federation,
one of the sport's three major governing organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a major step forward to free the IBF from the shackles of
corruption that have bound it virtually since its inception," U.S. Attorney
Robert J. Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cleary's prosecutors asked for a monitor in November after indicting and
suing IBF founder Robert W. Lee Sr. on charges he took bribes to rig its
rankings of boxers.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee took a leave as IBF president last month as lawyers for himself and the
IBF argued that a monitor was not needed.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bissell found "ample evidence presented to demonstrate a pattern of
illegal activity through the solicitation and receipt of payoffs allegedly for
the purpose of fixing rankings or scheduling boxing matches."
</P>
<P>
	   Although Lee and his codefendants took voluntary leaves, Bissell removed
them from their positions and asked the monitor to determine if the IBF should
still be paying them reduced salaries and legal fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee, who founded the IBF in 1983, and the others are accused of taking a
total of $338,000 in bribes to change the rankings of the IBF. Rankings play a
big role in determining fight opponents and purses for boxers.
</P>
<P>
	   IBF lawyer Linda P. Torres said Hayden was a good choice, and that Bissell
correctly declined to give him the sweeping authority sought by prosecutors,
which Torres said would have amounted to a takeover.
</P>
<P>
	   "What we want to do is ensure the integrity of both the way the organization
operates, and particularly the rankings," Torres said. The IBF's five employees
are "ready, willing and able to cooperate with anything the monitor wants to
do."
</P>
<P>
	   Lee's lawyer did not immediately return a call Wednesday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Hayden, who practices in Weehawkin, was the founder and first president of
the New Jersey Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. He did not return a call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   He is married to U.S. District Judge Katharine S. Hayden, who sits in the
same courthouse as Bissell.
</P>
<P>
	   Bissell's order, which took effect immediately, granted Hayden broad powers,
but did not give him the authority to issue subpoenas, which had been sought by
the U.S. attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
	   Hayden got the authority to attend all executive committee meetings, examine
all records and guarantee that the IBF's boxing decisions are made fairly.
</P>
<P>
	   The monitor can take steps to remove IBF personnel he suspects are involved
in misconduct, and can get expert help to conduct IBF business. It was not
immediately known what Hayden knows about the sport.
</P>
<P>
	   Monitors have been installed a dozen times in the 20-year history of the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act, generally to cleanse
mob-riddled labor unions.
</P>
<P>
	   Zachary Carter, the former U.S. attorney for Brooklyn, Queens and Long
Island, was the initial choice of prosecutors to become the IBF monitor. Bissell
selected Hayden from lists of possible monitors that he asked prosecutors and
defense attorneys to submit to him.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge ordered the lists kept secret, so Cleary declined to say whether
Hayden was on his list.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge in November imposed spending limits on the IBF. The organization
replaced Lee in December with longtime IBF vice president Hiawatha Knight of
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors have disclosed that videotaped evidence shows Lee taking bribes
and improperly manipulating the ratings committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Lee, 65, of Fanwood, faces racketeering, conspiracy, money laundering and
tax evasion charges. He has pleaded innocent to all charges, and a trial could
begin this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   The IBF board granted him a leave of absence Dec. 7 at his full $165,000
salary, which was recently reduced to $25,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The IBF board also has agreed to pay $250,000 of Lee's legal fees, and
$50,000 for each of his three codefendants. If any are found guilty, they must
repay the money.
</P>
<P>
	   The indictment said seven promoters and managers were involved in payoffs to
the IBF to alter rankings or give favorable treatment to 23 boxers. They have
not been charged, and the indictment refers to them only by number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 1849 </TRAILER>
