<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Hughes Stock Climb on Rumor  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL WHITE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Boeing is in talks to acquire the satellite-making
business of Hughes Electronics Corp., according to an unconfirmed report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing would pay $4 billion for the operations, according to Dow Jones
Newswires, citing unidentified sources familiar with the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesmen for Boeing and Hughes declined to comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal would make Boeing a dominant player in the commercial satellite
industry, which is now led by Hughes with about 40 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
	   The report boosted Hughes shares by 4 percent, to close up $4.43 3/4 at
$108.12 1/2 at 5 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange. Boeing shares rose 18 1/4
cents to $43.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes is owned by General Motors Corp., but its shares trade separately
from regular GM shares.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing wants to position itself broadly in the aerospace market, said Jon
Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, an investment bank
specializing in aerospace acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
	   The move would reduce its dependency on jet airliner sales, and put the
company in position to capitalize on potential growth in the commercial
satellite industry. The purchase also would reflect some uncertainty on Boeing's
part as to which areas of aerospace will become the most lucrative in the next
century, Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
	   "For Boeing, it's hard to sit here and decide which way things are going to
go, and they want to be represented across the board," Kutler said. "They're
trying to have their arms in most of the major areas of the space market in
order to be well-positioned regardless of how the market goes."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal would complete the transformation of Hughes from a major military
aerospace contractor to what would become primarily a commercial
telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes was founded as Hughes Aircraft by wealthy eccentric Howard Hughes in
1932 and branched out into defense electronics after World War II. The company
began to move into commercial ventures, such as DirecTV, after the end of the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shares have more than doubled during the past year, driven by the
growth of DirecTV. The service, with more than 8 million subscribers, had
revenue of $1.05 billion in the third quarter, up from $408 million in the third
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes, however, has spent heavily developing the subscriber base. The
company lost $29.6 million in the third quarter, mainly because of expenses from
its acquisition of two satellite-TV rivals, as well as higher satellite costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale of its satellite manufacturing business would provide cash Hughes
needs to continue developing DirecTV and other communications businesses, said
Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shed its aircraft operations in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a company that had a lot of money after selling off Hughes Aircraft to
Raytheon, but they've gone through that and now they're substantially in debt,"
said Nisbet. "This would be a source of funds to keep their growth going in
these new fields."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
