<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Studio Chief Resigns  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Joe Roth, the Disney movie chief who marshaled the
studio to box-office dominance for half a decade, said Wednesday he was quitting
to form an independent film company.
</P>
<P>
	   He will be replaced as Disney studio chairman by Peter Schneider, who has
worked for the company since 1985 and served as studio president under Roth for
the last year. The change is effective Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth said he wanted to be his own boss after nearly six years overseeing
Disney's film business and a previous stint as head of 20th Century Fox studios.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney Chairman Michael Eisner and Roth denied reports that there had been
friction between them, particularly over statements Eisner made a year ago about
the company's movie performance. In a letter to shareholders, Eisner had said
that despite good revenues, Disney films were not as profitable as he wanted due
to costly talent deals.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth said he may have felt the comments were a personal criticism, but that
the remarks had nothing to do with his leaving.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's just human for me to be reactive," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
	   But, he added, "That does not have one iota to do with this. It's 100
percent about me wanting, after spending 10 years working for Rupert Murdoch at
Fox and Michael Eisner, to strike out on my own."
</P>
<P>
	   Eisner said Wednesday his comments had not been intended as criticism of
Roth.
</P>
<P>
	   "Joe is not to blame for this. The industry is to blame for this," Eisner
said, adding that Roth has been instrumental in getting Disney's film costs
under control during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have not had one inkling from Joe, ever, of discontent with the way we
operate," Eisner said. "He and I operate very well together. We were totally on
board as far as strategy."
</P>
<P>
	   Disney's profits fell 28 percent to $1.3 billion in the company's last
fiscal year as revenue growth slowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Even so, Roth's departure follows a record year at the box office for
Disney, which was the top film distributor worldwide with $2.6 billion in ticket
sales and No. 1 domestically with $1.24 billion. Actually, Disney has led the
global box office for five of the last six years.
</P>
<P>
	   The studio's 1999 releases included "The Sixth Sense," which has taken in
$276 million domestically, and "Toy Story 2," which has grossed $220 million --
the first time two films from the same distributor topped the $200 million mark
in one year.
</P>
<P>
	   The resignation is the latest in a string of high-profile departures among
top Disney brass in the last few years, including chief financial officers Steve
Bollenbach and Richard Nanula, ABC TV and radio station chief Steve Burke, and
cable programming boss Geraldine Laybourne.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney also has suffered through costly severance settlements with former
top executives Jeffrey Katzenberg and Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly, there's people in the speculation camp who will continue to say
it's not a good thing, the revolving door continues," said Katherine Styponias,
an analyst for Prudential Securities. "But the company has weathered these sort
of departures before. They'll probably weather this one."
</P>
<P>
	   Roth joined Disney as motion picture chief in 1994 and became studio boss
two years later, overseeing film, TV, video and animation production. Other
Disney hits on his watch have included "Tarzan," "The Waterboy" and
"Armageddon."
</P>
<P>
	   He was chairman of 20th Century Fox from 1989 to 1992, when he left to form
Caravan Productions, a company that produced films financed by Disney. Roth also
was co-founder of Morgan Creek productions before he went to Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth said he has not lined up financing yet for his new company. He and
Eisner said Disney could possibly distribute some of Roth's films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1855 </TRAILER>
