<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA: Meat Labeling Could Cost  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Requiring meat to be labeled with the country of origin
could raise costs for consumers and there's no proof it would help U.S.
livestock producers, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In a study requested by Congress, USDA said that mandatory labeling also
could hurt U.S. meat exports if foreign countries impose a similar requirement.
</P>
<P>
	   Some American producers have been pushing for such labeling as a way to curb
imports of Canadian cattle.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA did not put a price tag on a labeling law. The labels themselves could
cost anywhere from $500,000 to $8 million, depending on what cuts of meat the
law applied to. But processors also would have to segregate meat that enters the
country to make sure it's labeled properly, and the cost of doing that ``is
unknown, but could be significant,'' the report said. There would be additional
costs to USDA to enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
	   The department also concluded there is evidence that consumers are willing
to pay higher prices to know where the meat they are buying comes from.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To the contrary, if consumers do distinguish goods depending on their
country of origin, strong incentive exists for industries to act without
government intervention,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meatpackers claim that labeling meat could cost the industry $1 billion a
year. About 10 percent of the beef that Americans eat is imported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
