<HEADLINE> Mexico Expels U.S. Zapatista Backer  </HEADLINE>
   By ALEJANDRO RUIZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- A Denver man who was ordered to
leave Mexico by Jan. 6 has remained in the country, battling an immigration
policy critics say is aimed at foreign supporters of leftist rebels in the
southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
	   A court on Tuesday issued an order suspending the government's effort to
expel Kerry Appel until federal immigration officials provide more evidence of
why he is being expelled.
</P>
<P>
	   Appel is one of hundreds of foreign supporters of the region's Zapatista
rebels who have been ordered out of Mexico over the past four years. He was
summoned Jan. 3 to immigration offices along with several other foreigners
suspected of violating their visas.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the government denies targeting Zapatista supporters, most of those
expelled were members of Zapatista support networks or human rights
organizations abroad. The government has also set up immigration checkpoints on
obscure country roads where the rebels have influence.
</P>
<P>
	   Appel advertises support for the Zapatistas on his Denver company's Web site
and has made documentary films supporting their cause. His small coffee company
says it sells beans purchased from pro-Zapatista peasants.
</P>
<P>
	   The government accuses expelled foreigners of violating terms of their visas
by meddling in politics. Some had worked directly with the Zapatistas -- though
none are known to have been involved in military activities -- and some were
simply caught in pro-Zapatista areas.
</P>
<P>
	   Appel says he was attending a Zapatista-sponsored New Year's celebration in
San Andres Larrainzar, a town north of San Cristobal de las Casas where the
Zapatistas have a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, the country's top immigration official told a news
conference that ``foreigners are not prohibited from attending local
celebrations, but if the celebrations have a political connection, that's
interference'' in domestic politics and grounds for expulsion.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Mexican officials are never known to have expelled foreigners for
watching political rallies anywhere else in Mexico, or in other parts of
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
	   The Zapatistas fought the government directly for two weeks at the start of
1994 before a cease-fire. Claiming to fight for democracy and Indian rights,
they have attracted widespread international support, thus irritating the
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
