<HEADLINE> Japan Pushed To Cut TeleCom Costs  </HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Japanese proposals to reduce charges imposed on U.S. and
other foreign telecommunication companies do not go far enough in meeting
commitments Japan made in 1998, the Clinton administration said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher said so far Japan has
proposed little in the way of reductions in steep connection charges imposed on
U.S. companies and other foreign telecommunications firms seeking to compete
against Japan's Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are seeking assurances that they will implement what we agreed upon in
1998,'' Fisher told reporters. ``The benefits of what we are advocating are very
important to Japanese consumers and businesses.''
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese officials are scheduled to meet with Fisher next Tuesday in
Washington for a review of the 1998 telecommunications agreement, announced by
President Clinton and then-Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
	   The major dispute concerns how Japan will implement pledges to cut hookup
charges that NTT imposes for rival telecommunication companies seeking to crack
Japan's vast telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
	   Fisher said the proposals currently being discussed in Japan currently
represent ``little or no change'' in the current high charges.
</P>
<P>
	   ``NTT is a monopoly. It is trying to do everything it can to delay a
significant reduction in rates,'' Fisher said. He said the U.S. side will be
seeking specific details of what the government of Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi will propose to the Japanese Diet next month.
</P>
<P>
	   The telecommunications dispute is just one of a number of trade tensions
between the two nations currently as America's deficit with Japan has widened
considerably over the past two years in the wake of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   Other issues in dispute include promises Japan has made to reduce
regulations in its construction industry to make it easier for American
companies to compete for business in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Fisher said the two countries would meet next month for an overall review of
the deregulation effort launched in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Those talks, known as the Enhanced Initiative on Deregulation and
Competition Policy, seek to cut Japanese regulations and increase foreign
competition in such areas as housing, retailing, energy and construction
standards as a way of boosting U.S. exports and narrowing the trade deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
