<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Skewered on Digital Insertion  </HEADLINE>
    By HANNAH WOLFSON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS News is facing criticism for something that wasn't
really there.
</P>
<P>
	   Network executives said they did nothing wrong when they used digital
technology to paste a CBS logo over an NBC screen and another advertisement in
Times Square during live broadcasts of "CBS Evening News" on Dec. 30 and Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
	   But some media observers say the network may have sacrificed journalistic
ethics for the sake of business.
</P>
<P>
	   Although digital imaging is often used to insert virtual billboards during
sports broadcasts and other images is entertainment programs, its use in a news
program has come under fire.
</P>
<P>
	   "This may seem like an innocent little corporate coup, but there are bigger
implications in terms of eroding people's confidence in what they see on the
screen," said Richard T. Kaplar, vice president of The Media Institute, a
nonprofit think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS News President Andrew Heyward said the decision to use the digital
imaging during the competitive millennium news broadcast triggered internal
debate.
</P>
<P>
	   "Reasonable people could disagree whether it is an appropriate use of
digital technology," Heyward said, "and like any new technology it poses new
issues we have to address on a case-by-case basis."
</P>
<P>
	   CBS's morning program, "The Early Show," routinely uses the technology to
digitally paste a CBS advertisement on the General Motors building in New York,
where it is taped. But like the other network morning programs, it is generally
considered entertainment.
</P>
<P>
	   Heyward said CBS has a "core principle" of not deceiving the audience, and
he doesn't believe the imaging violated that principle any more than the
standard use of printed graphics on the television screen.
</P>
<P>
	   Aly Colon of The Poynter Institute for Media Studies in St. Petersburg,
Fla., said such practices can hurt news broadcasters' credibility.
</P>
<P>
	   "If what's behind (the anchor) is not accurate or real, then is what he is
saying or where he is or what he's trying to convey any more authentic than the
environment he's in?" Colon asked.
</P>
<P>
	   ABC provoked a similar controversy in 1994 when Washington correspondent
Cokie Roberts was introduced as reporting from the Capitol when she was actually
standing in the studio in front of an image of Capitol Hill. She even wore her
coat for authenticity.
</P>
<P>
	   "It should never have happened, and you won't see that happening again," ABC
News spokeswoman Eileen Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
	   While ABC uses digital imaging to create graphics for Monday Night Football
and other sports programs, Murphy said credibility in the eyes of viewers is too
important to do the same with the news, Such a practice would be manipulative,
she said.
</P>
<P>
	   NBC said it has never used digital imaging during its nightly newscasts and
has no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   Digital manipulation is not limited to television. Time magazine apologized
to readers in 1994 for featuring a darkened version of O.J. Simpson's mug shot
on its cover. And many newspapers have policies against the use of
digitally-enhanced photos.
</P>
<P>
	   But with such technology evolving quickly, Colon said, most news
organizations' walls between journalism and business may need some updating.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have to think about why those walls are there and if you're going to
vault over them, what that implies," Colon said. "I think that it's going to be
a very challenging element that the news industry will have to address in terms
of who's going to be responsible for the news."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1911 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
