<HEADLINE> Iraq: U.N. Resolution 'Difficult'  </HEADLINE>
   By AHMAD SAMI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq would find it hard to accept or implement a new
U.N. Security Council plan to restart disarmament activities in the country, a
senior Iraqi official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But Deputy Foreign Minister Nizar Hamdoon did not rule out cooperation with
the United Nations in carrying out the plan if ``the situation changes and there
are new elements.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Iraq finds it very difficult to deal with this resolution ... as it exists
right now,'' Hamdoon, Iraq's former U.N. ambassador, told Associated Press
Television News. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dec. 17 resolution calls for the creation of a new international
inspection agency, which would resume the disarmament of all Iraq's remaining
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
	   Until Iraq is certified to be free of illegal weapons, the U.N. Security
Council will not lift the economic sanctions imposed in 1990 after Iraq invaded
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
	   The resolution promises to consider suspending sanctions for renewable
four-month periods if Iraq cooperates with the new inspectors and makes progress
toward answering questions about its disarmament.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. chief Kofi Annan asked the five permanent members of the Security
Council to consider Swedish diplomat Rolf Ekeus to head the new U.N. Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission, known as UNMOVIC, U.N. diplomats said
Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   UNMOVIC replaces the U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, which was
responsible since the end of the 1991 Persian Gulf War for eliminating Iraq's
programs for weapons of mass destruction. Ekeus was executive director of UNSCOM
before he left in 1997 to become Sweden's ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   UNSCOM pulled out of Iraq in December 1998 just before the United States and
Britain launched airstrikes to retaliate for Iraq's alleged obstruction of
UNSCOM inspectors.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, a state-run newspaper quoted Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf as saying Baghdad may eventually accept the UNMOVIC resolution if the
Security Council introduced some amendments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 1914 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
