<HEADLINE> Continental Warns on 1999 Earnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HOUSTON (AP) -- Continental Airlines announced Wednesday that its 1999
earnings, due out next week, will be reduced by $21 million because of
accounting changes made during the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Houston-based carrier said it has revamped the way it accounts for the
sale of mileage credits in its OnePass frequent-flyer program. Retroactive to
Jan. 1, 1999, revenue from the sale of mileage credits will be deferred and
recognized only when transportation is provided.
</P>
<P>
	   Continental, the nation's fifth-largest carrier, said other asset sales,
including a portion of its interest in Equant N.V., will cause a net gain of $6
million in the fourth quarter results, due out Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
	   The company had previously announced several non-recurring items in the
fourth quarter, including a $182 million after-tax gain from the sale of its
interest in Amadeus Global Travel Distribution S.A. and a $50 million after-tax
charge for the early retirement of several DC-10-30 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
	   Continental reported earnings of $358 million for the first nine months of
last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The earnings warning was issued after close of financial markets. In trading
Wednesday, Continental shares fell 12 1/2 cents to $44 at 5 p.m. EST on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
