<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Killer of Humorist Captured  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Police have captured a man accused of participating
in the drive-by killing last August of a beloved radio and television humorist,
authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The suspect, identified as 22-year-old Juan Pablo Ortiz, was arrested last
weekend in Medellin, Colombia's second-largest city. He is being kept under
tight security.
</P>
<P>
	   Ortiz has been identified by witnesses but has not confessed, chief
prosecutor Alfonso Gomez said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Gomez gave no indication that authorities were closer to knowing the motive
for the killing or if Ortiz -- a reputed professional hit man -- had been hired
to kill him.
</P>
<P>
	   Jaime Garzon made a career of lampooning leading figures in Colombian
politics, sports and entertainment on television and radio. He was widely
admired for helping Colombians laugh despite their country's seemingly endless
violence. The assassination caused a national outpouring of grief.
</P>
<P>
	   The 39-year-old satirist died Aug. 13, when men on passing motorcycles
sprayed his jeep with bullets as Garzon drove to his morning job at a Bogota
radio station.
</P>
<P>
	   Speculation about who ordered the killing abounds in Colombia's media, with
possible suspects ranging from leftist rebels to rightist paramilitary gunmen to
an ultraright faction in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   Garzon had discreetly helped mediate the release of hostages by the
guerrillas and was periodically accused of having leftist sympathies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
