<HEADLINE> U.S. Cancels Communications Licenses  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Valuable communications licenses held by a bankrupt
company have been canceled and will be reauctioned, the government told a
bankruptcy court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Communications Commission, in a filing with the U.S. Bankruptcy
Court for the Southern District of New York, objected to plans by NextWave
Telecom to reorganize itself in bankruptcy court in the hopes of using its
licenses to build a wireless network.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, the commission said the licenses had automatically been canceled,
per FCC rules, and that it would seek new bidders for those slices of the
airwaves -- potentially worth billions of dollars -- in July.
</P>
<P>
	   FCC Chairman Bill Kennard, citing a decision from the appeals court that
confirmed the commission's authority over the licenses, said the agency's rules
dictate that such licenses cancel when their holder fails to pay for them on
time.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Allowing a company to keep its licenses despite its failure to pay on time
would be unfair to others who have played by the rules and would undermine the
integrity of our auctions process,'' Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that the commission is anxious to put that portion of the airwaves
to use for consumers by auctioning it to another owner.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This spectrum has laid fallow for too long,'' Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
	   The problem of communication companies holding licenses and going bankrupt
has proved a major headache for regulators, who have unsuccessfully sought
legislation to ensure that licenses won at auction are not tied up in bankruptcy
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   NextWave, based in Hawthorne, N.Y., won its wireless licenses in a federal
auction several years ago, to use for the next generation of wireless
communications, known as PCS.
</P>
<P>
	   But then the company couldn't raise enough money to pay the $4.7 billion it
had bid for the licenses. The other two top bidders in that auction were also
unable to pay the FCC and filed for Chapter 11, tying up the licenses in
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
	   A bankruptcy court in New York ruled last year that the company could hold
on to the licenses after paying just a portion of the amount they bid. But the
Second Circuit court in late fall reversed that decision and reaffirmed the
FCC's jurisdiction over the licenses.
</P>
<P>
	   In light of the ruling, the commission filed its petition with the appeals
court stating that the licenses had automatically been canceled and therefore,
any attempts by the company to reorganize itself should not be approved.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, a group of investors including Global Crossing and Liberty
Media, an affiliate of AT&AMP;T, agreed to provide $1.6 billion in cash to help
NextWave emerge from bankruptcy court and build a wireless network.
</P>
<P>
	   That process, however, could take much longer than re-auctioning the
licenses to an existing wireless operator. One potential bidder for the new
licenses is mobile phone company Nextel Communications.
</P>
<P>
	   The licenses include some major metropolitan markets such as New York,
Seattle, Philadelphia and San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
