<HEADLINE> Blaze Disrupts Caribbean Cruise  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica (AP) -- Their vacations cut short by a cruise ship
fire, hundreds of disappointed passengers crowded a Jamaican airport for charter
flights home Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Carnival Cruise Lines' Celebration was about 100 miles from Jamaica when the
fire broke out, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Janna Vic.
</P>
<P>
	   The blaze in an auxiliary generator started around midnight and was put out
within minutes by automated firefighting equipment, said Carnival spokesman Andy
Newman. There are three auxiliary generators, all located in the middle of the
733-foot ship, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   None of the ship's 1,586 passengers and 667 crew members was injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Celebration pulled into port at Montego Bay on Wednesday afternoon. The ship
left New Orleans on Sunday for a seven-day cruise with planned stops in Montego
Bay, Grand Cayman Island and Cozumel, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of the fire, the passengers will be flown back to New Orleans or to
their hometowns, Newman said. Passengers will get full refunds and a free
seven-day cruise.
</P>
<P>
	   Many people waiting for flights at the Montego Bay airport said they were
frustrated at losing their vacations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've taken nine cruises -- this is our first with Carnival and we won't
be taking another one,'' said Peter Bogner of Eureka Springs, Ark.
</P>
<P>
	   After the fire, the ship drifted for about six hours and was temporarily
without running water, toilets or air conditioning, Newman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Carnival canceled Celebration's Saturday voyage from New Orleans. Passengers
scheduled for that trip will receive a full refund and a 50 percent discount on
a future Carnival cruise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
