<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ gets A for funding, D-plus for teacher development in survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - An annual survey by a national education magazine
this year gives New Jersey near failing grades on improving teacher quality.
<P>
	   But a state education spokesman said the information Education Week used to
craft a "D-plus" on teacher development is outdated and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey fared better in the annual Quality Counts survey on education
funding and curriculum standards, receiving "A" and "B-minus" grades
respectively.
</P>
<P>
	   But it garnered incomplete grades for student achievement and "school
climate." Too few students took a voluntary national test to provide a large
enough sample for the report card, which uses the test results to measure both
students' scholastic performance and their attitudes toward school.
</P>
<P>
	   This year's fourth annual survey, dubbed Quality Counts 2000, highlighted
national efforts to improve the quality of the teaching profession. Overall, the
50 states deserve a "C," magazine editors said.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, the survey found that while 39 states require prospective
teachers to pass basic literacy and mathematics tests, 36 of those states let
some who fail slip through loopholes.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's recent push toward professional development is too little, too
late, according the magazine.
</P>
<P>
	   But state spokesman Peter Peretzman disputed Education Week's findings.
</P>
<P>
	   "They used a flawed and subjective grading system that failed to take into
account numerous teacher quality programs put in place by the administration,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Those include continuing education programs that require teachers to take
100 hours of professional development courses every five years, a new teacher
recruitment program and higher college grade point averages for starting
teachers. In addition, Gov. Christie Whitman unveiled a new teacher mentoring
program in her State of the State address earlier this week, he noted.
</P>
<P>
	   Karen Joseph, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Education Association, agreed
that New Jersey is answering critics.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would anticipate that when Education Week revisits this subject and they
acknowledge the existence of our professional development program, coupled with
the mentoring program, next year New Jersey should get an 'A'," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Allen, a policy analyst for the Denver-based Education Commission of
the States, a bipartisan education think tank not associated with the magazine,
said states often complain about low survey grades. But the report card is meant
to hold states up to higher standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said New Jersey ought to do a better job certifying teachers' performance
throughout their careers. The state should also put teeth in its professional
development plan instead of leaving enforcement up to local districts, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Peretzman said the state is proud of its No. 1 ranking in the total amount
of money spent per pupil, $8,801 in dollars adjusted for regional cost
differences, according to the magazine. The state was previously ranked near the
bottom of the 50 states in terms of dollars spent in the classroom, but has
finally pulled itself up into the middle of the pack, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But a spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards Association said he is
troubled by the state's lower grade in resource allocation. In that category,
the state earned only a "C-minus."
</P>
<P>
	   "That signals that there are still too many districts that have to overtax
themselves," said spokesman Frank Belluscio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
