<HEADLINE> Coalition Leader To Be Croat Premier  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- The senior leader of a center-left coalition that won
Croatia's parliamentary elections will be appointed prime minister, the
country's acting president said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Vlatko Pavletic, the parliament speaker who is temporarily replacing the
late President Franjo Tudjman, told state-run radio that he will charge Ivica
Racan, the leader of the Social Democratic Party, with forming a new government
on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
	   Racan's party defeated the ruling Croatian Democratic Union in alliance with
their junior partners, the Social Liberal Party, in parliamentary elections on
Jan. 3, ending the ruling party's almost decade-long grip on power.
</P>
<P>
	   Racan's appointment would have been made earlier had election officials not
determined minor irregularities in about a dozen of the 6,000 polling stations.
</P>
<P>
	   Although a repeat of the vote in those areas on Sunday cannot significantly
alter the election outcome, the Constitution forbids the appointment of a
premier until official final results are declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
