<HEADLINE> Former State Sen. Associate Pleads  </HEADLINE>
   By KELLY P. KISSEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- A politically connected lawyer pleaded guilty to
conspiracy Wednesday, detailing cronyism in a federally backed welfare program
that prosecutors say netted a former state senator nearly $1 million for no
work.
</P>
<P>
	   By pleading guilty and agreeing to testify against his colleagues, Murrey L.
Grider escaped 35 other counts and won a promise from the federal government
that it would not prosecute his son on 12 related charges. His son, accused of
netting $73,000 in the scheme, could have faced 75 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Sentencing for Grider was postponed to a later date.
</P>
<P>
	   His agreement to testify boosts the government's case against former state
Sen. Nick Wilson, a former law partner accused of being the kingpin of a
wide-ranging public corruption ring. Wilson and seven others face trial on a
133-count indictment Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
	   Grider, 56, said Wilson hand-picked lawyers for a scheme to defraud federal
welfare officials through state-run programs. Grider said he knew about
kickbacks but did nothing to stop them.
</P>
<P>
	   In a five-minute summary before U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr.,
Grider incriminated Wilson, saying the once-powerful state senator hired the
lawyers and arranged the kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Johnson said Grider kicked back $618,610 to
Wilson. With kickbacks from other lawyers, ``Wilson received $984,844 for
performing no service,'' Johnson said. The figure is 67 percent of the amount
that Arkansas received for the child support program from 1993 to 1997, when the
alleged crimes occurred, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson, 57, who resigned from the Legislature on Dec. 31, could not be
reached for comment. Home and office numbers listed for him have been
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson was convicted in November of conspiracy and tax evasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
