<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Wife Criticizes Peruvian Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori's former wife is pulling no
punches as an opposition candidate for Congress, taking direct aim at her
ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
	   Susana Higuchi said in comments published Wednesday in the opposition
newspaper La Republica that if her husband returns to power for another
five-year term, it ``would bring more corruption, recession, more poverty, and
unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
	   The former first lady announced Monday that she would run for Congress,
ending supporters' hopes that she would challenge Fujimori for the presidency in
general elections in April.
</P>
<P>
	   She said her party, the Independent Moralizing Front, decided against
selecting a presidential candidate as an act of protest against Fujimori's
decision to seek a third consecutive term. Opinion polls indicate Fujimori has a
wide lead over his rival candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Posing with a broom on the front page of Wednesday's La Republica, Higuchi
was pictured sweeping scraps of paper with ``recession,'' ``injustice,'' and
``dictator'' written in red block letters.
</P>
<P>
	   The couple's marital problems became public in 1994, after Fujimori's
supporters in Congress passed a law prohibiting the president's immediate family
members from running for national office. Many Peruvians believed the
legislation was tailored to thwart Higuchi's bid to challenge her husband in the
1995 presidential race, which Fujimori won.
</P>
<P>
	   When Higuchi accused Fujimori of tolerating widespread corruption in his
government and ignoring the needs of Peru's poor, he stripped her of her
ceremonial title of first lady, locked her out of the palace and soon after
filed for divorce. The divorce was completed in 1996, removing the prohibition
against a Higuchi candidacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
