<HEADLINE> GOP Showcases Its Web Presence  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- National Republicans showcased new technology
Wednesday that will boost its presence on the Internet and possibly energize its
activists.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, the Republican National Committee becomes an Internet service
provider, offering direct access to the Net. The service will come with
customized Web pages providing updates on GOP developments, e-mail, chat rooms,
an ``anti-smut filter'' and ``unbiased reporting.''
</P>
<P>
	   An advertisement says the service targets ``people who want freedom FROM the
press.''
</P>
<P>
	   The RNC also began a separate service Wednesday that will let Web users
track Republican events nationally and in their neighborhoods. The service,
GOPlanit, is a calendar that also will alert users to nonpolitical events of
interest to them, and allows them to log personal events.
</P>
<P>
	   The Internet initiatives are part of an effort begun several months ago by
RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson to more aggressively use the Internet to promote the
party.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have recognized over the last 120 days that it's a new world where you
are digital or die,'' Nicholson said in opening the RNC's winter meeting here.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are trying to enhance participation in the political process,'' he
said. ``This gives us a wonderful capability ... to really stimulate people, and
to communicate with them without going through the filter of the news media.''
</P>
<P>
	   The party also announced that its national convention in Philadelphia in
August will be the first such political gathering broadcast in high-definition
television, which delivers substantially crisper images than traditional TV.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats also are using technology to spread their message.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic National Committee recently created a ``George W. Bush Stump
Speech Search Engine'' to underscore its contention that Bush falls back on his
standard address when pressed on almost any subject. By entering phrases from a
Bush appearance, users can count how many times he has used the statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The party will broadcast its national convention on the Web, as it did in
1996, and is considering an HDTV transmission, said Jenny Backus, a party
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen praised Vice President Al Gore's health care
plan Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The pair toured Child Health Services, which provides health care and other
help to low-income families, before describing why they believe Gore's plan to
expand insurance coverage to all children is good for New Hampshire and the
country.
</P>
<P>
	   Shaheen said the plan fits with New Hampshire's history of building on
successful programs instead of making radical changes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think Al Gore's approach to health care is reasoned, it builds on what
we know already works and provides changes where needed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Shalala criticized Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, for proposing to eliminate Medicaid and to give people
subsidies to buy health insurance or opt into the system that covers federal
employees.
</P>
<P>
	   She said that approach would hurt the disabled and others who depend on
Medicaid programs tailored to their needs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is a fundamental difference between giving people money to go out
and buy health insurance and making sure quality health care plans are
available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Former first lady Barbara Bush on Wednesday submitted the
forms that her son, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, needs to run in the Arizona
Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can imagine the pleasure a mother feels when she files papers for her
son to run for president of the United States,'' Mrs. Bush said after turning in
the forms at the Secretary of State's Office.
</P>
<P>
	   She was joined by Gov. Jane Hull, who chairs Bush's campaign in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Bush said she was amazed at the number of people who have contributed
more than $67 million to his campaign. His fund raising is unmatched by any
previous campaign, including those of his father, former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We would have died for that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press writers Scott Lindlaw and Holly Ramer contributed to this
report.
</P>
