<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. May Expand Sierra Leone Force  </HEADLINE>
   By JOSEF FEDERMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council on Wednesday began
considering a proposal to nearly double the size of a U.N. peacekeeping force in
Sierra Leone and to give it broader authority to maintain security in the West
African country.
</P>
<P>
	   The British draft resolution followed a call by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan to expand the multinational peacekeeping force to make up for the
departure of Nigerian troops who led a separate West African intervention force.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan first proposed expanding the U.N. mission last month after Nigeria
said it was pulling out of Sierra Leone. Annan outlined his proposal in a report
Wednesday, presenting a plan to beef up the force from 6,000 to 11,100 members
and to give it broader authority in maintaining security.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The rapid expansion ... will be indispensable in maintaining the necessary
security conditions for the implementation of the Lome Agreement,'' Annan wrote,
referring to the July 7 cease-fire that ended the country's eight-year civil
war.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's draft resolution closely resembles Annan's proposal. It says a
force numbering up to 11,100 military personnel is needed to provide security at
government buildings, airports, important intersections and other key locations.
</P>
<P>
	   The peacekeepers also would assist the government in disarming former
fighters and integrating them back into civilian life.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We must keep this process going and make sure that the Lome Accord, the
agreement on Sierra Leone, is brought to a final conclusion,'' British
Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock said.
</P>
<P>
	   The peacekeepers now have a mandate to merely monitor the cease-fire and
disarm fighters. The West African force, known as ECOMOG, was in charge of
overall security in the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Rebels still control parts of the countryside, banditry and lawlessness are
growing, attacks on civilians persist and the process of disarming fighters and
moving them back into civilian life has been slow, Annan's report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Annan said the situation has improved in areas where U.N. troops have
arrived.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States, which is billed 25 percent of the U.N. peacekeeping
budget, indicated reservations last month about whether Congress would approve
such a tremendous increase for the Sierra Leone mission.
</P>
<P>
	   But U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said Wednesday an increase of some
sort was necessary.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior U.N. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Annan's
proposal had been well received in the council. The official said he expected to
see an agreement in the coming weeks. He said that cost -- the current mission
is estimated to cost about $200 million through June -- could be an issue.
</P>
<P>
	   In the meantime, the official said, Nigeria was coordinating the departure
of the remaining 4,000 or so ECOMOG soldiers with the arrival of U.N. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
	   Tens of thousands of people were killed during Sierra Leone's civil war, and
many more were maimed in a systematic campaign of rebel terror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2018 </TRAILER>
