<HEADLINE> Tuvalu Wants U.N. Membership  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Tuvalu, the South Pacific nation of nine coral atolls,
has applied to be the 189th member of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   A letter containing Tuvalu's application was circulated Wednesday to members
of the Security Council and General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have the honor, on behalf of Tuvalu and in my capacity as prime minister
and minister responsible for foreign affairs, to declare that Tuvalu accepts the
obligations contained in the Charter of the United Nations and solemnly
undertakes to fulfill them,'' Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuvalu is a country of 9,000 people inhabiting nine small atolls, with a
total land area of 10 square miles. It is located 620 miles north of Fiji.
</P>
<P>
	   It subsists on fishing, fishing license fees, income from a national
investment trust fund, earnings by seamen who work on foreign ships and foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, the United Nations accepted three new members, all small South
Pacific island nations: Kiribati, Nauru and the Kingdom of Tonga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
