<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Defends Letter for Company  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ARNOLD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley on Wednesday dismissed as ``not a big deal''
a letter he wrote in 1994 on behalf of a New Jersey company whose officers had
donated money to his Senate campaign account.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who represented New Jersey, said he didn't think it was ``wrong at
all'' to urge the Commerce Department to give ``fair treatment'' to Sigma Corp.
of Cream Ridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's president, Victor Pais, said Bradley ``did nothing other than
just write a routine letter'' that was unrelated to political donations made 15
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   But the existence of the letter, first reported in Wednesday's Boston Globe,
put Bradley on the defensive hours before was to detail his criticisms of the
campaign finance system in general.
</P>
<P>
	   Although all candidates were invited, Bradley was the only presidential
candidate who attended an evening campaign finance forum in Manchester, N.H.,
co-sponsored by Common Cause, which supports overhauling federal campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
	   At the forum, Bradley repeated his call for campaign finance changes and
promised to be a president ``who is prepared to put his clout on the line in
order to liberate our democracy from the tentacles of money.'' He said he has
been more committed to the issue than Vice President Al Gore, his rival for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   In questioning Bradley, an audience member confused Gore and GOP
front-runner George W. Bush. ``You can get those two mixed up, I know,'' Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley had invited scrutiny of his Senate letter-writing record days
earlier, after questions were raised about letters written by Republican
presidential candidate Sen. John McCain on behalf of a major contributor.
Bradley said at the time that his policy during his 18 years in the Senate was
not to ``intervene in regulatory matters.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about the Sigma letter in Iowa on Wednesday, Bradley maintained that
writing letters to regulators ``wasn't a practice'' and that the discovery of
one or two such letters does not undermine his general policy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't think it's wrong at all,'' he said about the 1994 letter. ``What
am I going to say to a New Jersey company -- 'No, I'm not going to write on your
behalf and ask for a decision to be made'?''
</P>
<P>
	   His spokeswoman, Kristen Ludecke added, ``This is communicating on behalf of
a constituent and helping them navigate the bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore declined to comment on the letter. Asked whether he
wrote similar ones as a senator from Tennessee, Gore said: ``I've never claimed
not to have helped my constituents and my state and my congressional district.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sigma, which manufactures industrial pipe fittings, appealed a 1992 decision
by the International Trade Commission to impose a 127 percent duty on exports to
the United States by China National Metal Products. Sigma, which imports and
distributes water pipe fittings made by the Chinese company, protested the duty.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Court of International Trade returned the case to the Commerce
Department in June 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   Days later, Bradley wrote to then-Commerce Secretary Ron Brown: ``Sigma has
now been denied access to its CDIW fittings, a critical part of its product
line, for over two years. It only seems right that your department do its best
to ensure that this case not drag out any longer than necessary.''
</P>
<P>
	   In 1993, company president Pais and vice president Mark Abrams each had
donated $500 to Bradley's Senate campaign account.
</P>
<P>
	   Pais said Wednesday that Abrams was interested in politics and that both men
made campaign contributions, ``from time to time, not anything extensive.'' He
said the donations had nothing to do with the company's decision to seek
Bradley's help.
</P>
<P>
	   Pais said Sigma sought a meeting with Bradley in 1994, but had to settle for
a letter after Bradley's staff said the senator was too busy.
</P>
<P>
	   Pais said Bradley's letter had no effect on the case, which the company
ultimately won in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2042 </TRAILER>
