<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Exploits McCain's Tax Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN WOODWARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential rivals George W. Bush and John
McCain are accusing each other of promoting tax plans that would subject
middle-income families to a complex and potentially costly tax regimen meant
only for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue is the alternative minimum tax, which normally kicks in to ensure
well-off Americans pay their share. The Bush and McCain campaigns each assert
the other's tax cuts would be blunted by leaving many more average income
earners exposed to the minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
	   Campaigning in South Carolina on Wednesday, Bush said McCain's proposals
contained a ``serious flaw'' that actually ``may be a tax increase for many
people.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain spokesman Dan Schnur denied that, saying the senator is committed to
ensuring average Americans get the full value of his tax savings. But he
acknowledged more work must be done on the plan to protect middle-income people
from the minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
	   Moreover, he said the Texas governor's plan suffers from the same
shortcoming that Bush's aides are trying to exploit in the McCain package. He
quoted from an article last month in the newsletter Tax Notes by Al Davis, an
economist for congressional Democrats, saying, ``Many households will not get
the tax cuts portrayed in the Bush documents, unless major revenue-losing
changes are also made in the alternative minimum tax.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain this week announced a five-year plan costing $237 billion that would
put more people in the bottom 15 percent tax bracket, end dozens of business tax
breaks to help pay for the package and leave money from projected budget
surpluses aside for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's $483 billion, five-year plan, to be paid for largely from expected
surpluses, would eventually lower all income tax rates, bringing the bottom
bracket down to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and McCain both propose doubling the child tax credit to $1,000. But
Larry Lindsey, Bush's chief economic adviser, told reporters Wednesday the
governor's plan exempts the child credit from the alternative minimum tax and
the senator's does not.
</P>
<P>
	   Changing McCain's plan to protect middle-income Americans would cost
billions and throw its cost calculations out of kilter, Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
	   Schnur said the senator won't let the minimum tax reduce the savings his
plan would make available to people in the 15 percent bracket.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We realize that fixing the (minimum tax provision) will cost additional
money,'' Schnur said. He said McCain will propose the closing of additional
corporate loopholes to cover the cost.
</P>
<P>
	   People subject to the minimum tax have to calculate their liability in two
different ways and pay the higher amount. That's designed to stop wealthier
people from using so many deductions and credits that they end up owing little
or nothing.
</P>
<P>
	   Lindsey contended that under McCain's plan as written, more than 10 million
middle-income families would be caught in that web and lose much of the value of
the child tax credit.
</P>
<P>
	   In his example, a single parent with two children who makes $45,000 would,
under the normal calculation, owe $4,425 on taxable income of $29,500. But then
she would have her liability reduced to $2,425 after taking the credit of $1,000
for each child.
</P>
<P>
	   With the McCain plan, he said, that parent would also have to figure out her
liability under the minimum tax. Without access to the child credit in this
calculation, she would end up with a tax bill of $3,250 -- $825 more than if she
were protected from the minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was up front about the loose strings in his plan, saying that as it
is now drafted, some taxpayers might be hurt by the minimum tax. He said
extensive research was needed to estimate the cost of sheltering people, and he
promised ``appropriate adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lindsey acknowledged that the Bush tax plan rolled out in early December
does not spell out its exemption of the child tax credit. Bush aides decided at
the time that it was too ``wonky'' to explain.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said the Bush plan takes the exemption into account in its cost
calculations, and devotes some $30 billion to making sure middle-income
Americans are not bumped into the minimum tax by the child credit.
</P>
<P>
	   Schnur disputed that Bush advisers ever provided for such a breakdown and
said their estimate of the cost of protecting people from the minimum tax -- $10
billion a year when tax plans are fully in effect -- was wildly overblown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2057 </TRAILER>
