<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sale of Radioactive Metals Canceled  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department retreated Wednesday from plans to
sell thousands of tons of radioactive metal from its weapons production
facilities as scrap, saying the potential health concerns need to be more
clearly examined.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson blocked plans to sell 6,000 tons of nickel
taken from a defunct uranium enrichment plant at Oak Ridge, Tenn., thus keeping
it out of civilian commerce.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the department also was developing a formal policy to prevent the
future sale of 10,000 additional tons of radioactive metals, mostly nickel, at
other Energy Department facilities.
</P>
<P>
	   The action applies to ``volumetrically contaminated'' scrap metals -- mostly
nickel -- that have radioactivity embedded throughout, and not just on the
surface. Some nuclear watchdog groups have argued that the more than 120,000
tons of scrap metals with surface contamination also should be kept out of the
civilian market.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers who have pressed the administration to abandon the recycling
program applauded Richardson's action.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale of the nickel at Oak Ridge ``could have put U.S. workers, consumers
and steel producers in a very precarious situation,'' said Rep. Ron Klink,
D-Pa..
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., said ``common sense is finally beginning to take
hold.''
</P>
<P>
	   British Nuclear Fuel Inc., which is under DOE contract to clean up the Oak
Ridge facility, planned to sell the nickel to private buyers for $41 million
later this year. The company contended the nickel could be cleaned to the point
that it no longer would pose a health risk.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale had been approved by the state of Tennessee and in 1997 by the
federal Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
	   But it prompted criticism from nuclear watchdog groups, members of Congress
and some leaders of the steel industry, who were concerned about having to
explain to consumers why their products contained radioactive metals, even in
low doses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This plan had all the makings of being penny-wise and pound-foolish,''
said Klink in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Richardson said he was modifying the government's contract with British
Nuclear Fuel to block the impending sale at Oak Ridge or any future release of
similarly contaminated metals -- primarily nickel -- into the open market.
</P>
<P>
	   The long-range policy will cover not only the nickel at Oak Ridge but also
10,000 tons of metals -- mostly nickel -- being kept primarily at the Portsmouth
Gaseous Diffusion plant in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This will give the Nuclear Regulatory Commission time to develop national
standards for volumetrically contaminated materials ... (and) it will allow DOE
to examine alternatives to free release,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear when the NRC planned to consider a proposed standard for such
scrap metals. The NRC regulates consumer products where radiation has been
intentionally added, but has said the state had jurisdiction over the planned
nickel recycling at Oak Ridge.
</P>
<P>
	   While materials with surface contamination often can be cleaned, it is
unclear whether radioactivity that permeates a metal can be sufficiently
removed.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, some critics said Richardson was taking only half measures
because he does not address the recycling of scrap metals and other materials --
some 120,000 tons at DOE weapons facilities -- that contain only surface
radiation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we're concerned about is this will be just window dressing,'' said
David Adelman, an attorney at the Natural Resources Defense Council, which sued
to try to stop the recycling.
</P>
<P>
	   Wenonah Hauter, director of the Public Citizen Critical Mass Energy Project,
a nuclear watchdog group, said: ``Even if you believe that metal contaminated on
the surface by radioactive isotopes can be adequately cleaned, and we believe it
can't, who would possibly believe DOE can competently carry out a radioactive
recycling program?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
