<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Demands Bosnian Cooperation  </HEADLINE>
   By NICOLE WINFIELD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council demanded Wednesday that Bosnia's
three presidents fully implement a new U.S.-brokered agreement on cooperation
and implementation of the Dayton peace process, saying claims that the agreement
was invalid were false.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am here today to express our considerable annoyance at the delays,''
said the council president, U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke brokered the accord last Nov. 15 in a meeting in New York with
Bosnia's three presidents, Ante Jelavic, a Croat; Alija Izetbegovic, a Muslim;
and Zivko Radisic, a Bosnian Serb.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York Declaration, as it is known, was intended to pick up the pace
of the Dayton peace process and get Bosnia's Serbs, Croats and Muslims working
better together to form a united, democratic and multiethnic society.
</P>
<P>
	   Mistrust among the groups, who fought a 3 1/2-year war, has kept over a
million refugees from returning to their prewar homes.
</P>
<P>
	   In the declaration, the three presidents agreed to establish a joint border
patrol, support a single national passport, create a permanent executive staff
for their joint presidency and make a commitment to fully fund state ministries.
Their priority, they said at the time, was the return of displaced people and
refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
	   But two weeks after the accord was presented to the Security Council,
Radisic told the Bosnian Serb parliament that he had agreed only to work on
elements of the accord, which he described as an ``expression of the will''
rather than a binding commitment.
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke disputed that Wednesday after the council was briefed on the
situation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That declaration submitted to the world body had standing,'' Holbrooke
said. ``The Security Council was unanimous in calling on the joint presidency to
implement the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said the council would ask the U.N. chief's special representative in
Bosnia to consult urgently with the joint presidency to move the agreement
forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2057 </TRAILER>
