<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cos. Accused of Space Shuttle Fraud  </HEADLINE>
    By LINDA DEUTSCH AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Three companies were sued by the government for
allegedly concealing fraud by a subcontractor that spent millions from space
shuttle program funds on homes, jewelry and exotic vacations, it was disclosed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Justice Department suit, filed Tuesday, named Rockwell
International Inc., Boeing North American Inc. and United Space Alliance, the
current space shuttle contractor. The suit said United Space Alliance was liable
as a successor company.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing issued a statement saying it had cooperated in the investigation and
believed it was not liable for the actions of its subcontractor. The head of the
subcontracting firm pleaded guilty to fraud five years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit contended that Rockwell officials knew about the improper costs and
submitted false claims to the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
which resulted in overbilling and unallowable expenses between 1986 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Calls made after business hours to Rockwell headquarters in Milwaukee and to
United Space Alliance in Houston were not answered.
</P>
<P>
	   Space shuttle builder Rockwell, then based in California, was chosen in the
1980s and early 1990s to manage and operate the shuttle and space station
programs with contracts awarded for more than $4.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreements provided for more than $325 million in award fees or bonuses
to Rockwell based upon its performance, including how well it managed costs and
monitored its subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
	   In late 1996, Rockwell sold its defense and aerospace businesses to Boeing,
which assumed the contracts under its Boeing North American division. The
acquisition included Rockwell's 50 percent share in United Space Alliance, a
joint venture with Lockheed Martin Corp., to take over shuttle operations from
NASA.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the lawsuit, Rockwell had hired a subcontractor, Omniplan
Corp., to handle cost controls and management.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit said Omniplan established phony companies in order to lease
buildings and equipment to itself at inflated values, and commingled millions of
dollars in personal expenses with corporate accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit cited such activities as operating a pizza delivery company out of
a building Rockwell was billing to NASA.
</P>
<P>
	   Omniplan also included as allowable expenses the purchases of personal
houses, a ski lodge, expensive jewelry and personal vacations to exotic locales
including Nepal, Singapore and Argentina, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1995 the owner of Omniplan, Ralph Montijo, pleaded guilty to about 180
felony fraud violations.
</P>
<P>
	   "We regret that the government has chosen to file this complaint which
involves a subcontractor that was ultimately convicted of fraud several years
ago," said the Boeing statement.
</P>
<P>
	   "We cooperated with the government investigation at that time," Boeing said.
"We deny we had any knowledge of the fraud and we do not believe we are liable
under the False Claims Act."
</P>
<P>
	   Under the act, the government could seek treble damages plus civil penalties
ranging from $5,000 to $10,000 per violation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2058 </TRAILER>
