<HEADLINE> Mass. Lieutenant Gov. Apologizes  </HEADLINE>
   By JEAN McMILLAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- Lt. Gov. Jane Swift apologized Wednesday for asking state
workers to baby-sit her child and catching a ride home in a state police
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Maybe I should have come to this conclusion earlier, but I'm willing to
accept responsibility for my action and to say when I've been wrong,'' Swift
said. ``I'm still learning quite a few things about being a mother and even more
about being a lieutenant governor.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said she would ask the state's Ethics Commission to review whether she
abused her office by using a state police helicopter to leave a conference for
her home. She said her daughter had pneumonia and she should have called in
sick.
</P>
<P>
	   She also said she would cooperate if the commission chose to review her use
of staff to watch her 14-month-old daughter, Elizabeth. Swift has defended it by
saying the workers were not on state time and were old friends of hers who
volunteered.
</P>
<P>
	   The Boston Herald reported Wednesday that two aides who helped baby-sit had
received promotions and pay raises. Swift said that was unrelated.
</P>
<P>
	   House Speaker Thomas Finneran said Wednesday he was not troubled by Swift's
use of the helicopter if it was related to official duties.
</P>
<P>
	   As to the personal use of staff, he said: ``I'm confident that the
lieutenant governor will find a way to address it in a timely fashion. I hope
it's an isolated incident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
