<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: With some setbacks, state stays with teacher education  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York education officials have backtracked on
some tougher teacher education, certification and continuing education standards
they adopted in 1998, a new evaluation says.
<P>
	   A report card on New York teachers by Education Week magazine out Wednesday
gave the state an "A" for standards and accountability, but a "C-plus" on
improving teacher quality and a "D-plus" on school climate.
</P>
<P>
	   School climate is measured by such things as class size and the level of
parental involvement, Education Week editors said. Teacher quality is measured
by the number of teachers working in their field of study and individual teacher
assessments.
</P>
<P>
	   While noting some backsliding over the past two years, Education Week
concluded that in many respects, New York "policymakers are largely sticking to
the game plan the Regents adopted in mid-1998 for reworking the state's approach
to teacher preparation, certification and continuing education."
</P>
<P>
	   State education officials say the discrepancies noted in the report largely
involve their narrowing the focus on a broad range of proposed revisions
intended to improve teacher training and education.
</P>
<P>
	   "Whenever you bring a policy to life there are all kinds of adjustments and
compromises that are made," state Education Commissioner Richard Mills said.
"Much of that has to do with the fact that the Regents never propose things
without listening to a number of different ideas or voices."
</P>
<P>
	   According to Education Week, there's been a major shift in the state's
thinking on tenure standards.
</P>
<P>
	   A recent state policy would have given beginning teachers only two years to
earn a master's degree in order to keep teaching.
</P>
<P>
	   But the latest proposal, which the state Board of Regents is expected to act
on this year, would effectively extend that period to three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state's decision is an acknowledgment that for many people it is
financially impossible to get a masters' degree as a beginning teacher," Philip
Ellis, manager of educational services with the New York State United Teachers
union, said. "It's particularly tough if those young teachers are working on a
full-time basis because at this time they should really be trying to get
acclimated to the job."
</P>
<P>
	   Mills said the Regents' ultimate goal is to employ teachers who are fluent
in the subjects they are instructing, plus those having a broad range of
experience and the ability to teach students with diverse needs.
</P>
<P>
	   Currently, the state gives beginning teachers five years to earn a master's
degree.
</P>
<P>
	   Other controversial proposals included those which effectively narrowed the
number of grades that an educator is licensed to teach in New York. Now, the
state has two basic types of certification for teachers in regular education:
pre-kindergarten through sixth grade and seventh grade through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the latest proposal before the Board of Regents, those would be
replaced by four certificates: Birth through second grade; first grade through
sixth grade; fifth grade through ninth grade; and seventh grade through 12th
grade.
</P>
<P>
	   "New teachers need to understand the subjects they teach but they also need
to understand how children grow and develop and the Regents are trying to
combine both perspectives in the standards for teachers," Mills said.
</P>
<P>
	   But according to Ellis, the new breakdown might be self defeating.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have concerns that the narrowing of certification areas could
potentially lead to shortages of teachers in some areas, especially the first
certification (birth to second grade)," Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
	   "If a student was going to become a teacher and was concerned about
long-term employment they might look for certification areas with the widest
grade spans, so people may not want to become kindergarten teachers and we may
potentially end up with a shortage of kindergarten teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 2107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
