<HEADLINE> Former Principal Admits Embezzling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) -- A former elementary school principal who was
sentenced Wednesday admitted stealing $20,000 in student funds she used to
support a gambling habit, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cynthia Mello, 61, was sentenced to two years probation and counseling for a
gambling addiction after pleading guilty Wednesday to charges of forgery and
larceny.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Mello also was ordered to repay the school. The money will be given to a
scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors said that while Mello was principal from 1986 to 1997 she
developed an aggressive fund-raising program, purportedly to raise money for
workbooks, science projects, school plays and field trips. Prosecutors said she
instead used the money to buy lottery tickets and play casino slot machines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
