<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study supports ethanol plant in New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A consulting firm hired by the New Jersey Farm
Bureau says it would make economic sense to build an $18 million facility in the
state to convert field corn into fuel.
<P>
	   AUS Consultants Inc., of Moorestown, was commissioned last summer to
determine whether it would be feasible to build an ethanol plant in New Jersey -
the first in the Northeast. The report was completed in December, and The
Associated Press obtained a copy last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The preliminary plan has intrigued farmers, gasoline marketers, government
officials and environmentalists who say ethanol is a cleaner gasoline additive
than widely-used MTBE. A follow-up study is expected to project operating costs
and potential profits.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's pretty critical" for the survival of corn farmers, said Steve
Jany, a West Windsor grain farmer. "An ethanol production plant would pay a
little more than the market."
</P>
<P>
	   Farmers earn between $2.45 and $2.55 on a bushel of field corn. An ethanol
plant would pay about 10 cents less per bushel, but farmers would save the
30-cents-per-bushel transportation cost they pay to bring corn to markets in
Lancaster County, Pa., Jany said.
</P>
<P>
	   Proponents say an ethanol production plant also makes environmental sense.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly ethanol is a better alternative to other gasoline additives on the
market today," said David Pringle of the New Jersey Environmental Federation.
MTBE, a methanol-based gasoline additive, dominates the market; however, a
federal panel has recommended that it be phased out over four years because it
contaminates groundwater.
</P>
<P>
	   The additives, called oxygenates, increase the oxygen mix in engine
combustion, reducing the emissions of poisonous carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
	   Pringle said he would not support an ethanol production plant if it replaced
the development of technologies such as natural gas and electric-powered
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this happens in addition to the other alternatives, that would be
progress," Pringle said.
</P>
<P>
	   John Elston, who directs air quality issues for the state Department of
Environmental Protection, said an ethanol plant would support the department's
clean air efforts. There are some environmental concerns with ethanol, such as
the release of organic pollutants during hot summer months. But the problem
could be overcome by vapor recovery systems in new cars or detected by the
state's new emissions test, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "MTBE use may likely drop because of public pressure, but the Clean Air Act
still requires the use of an oxygenate," although it doesn't specify which one
is to be used, said Elston.
</P>
<P>
	   "The substitute may become very important," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter Furey, the farm bureau's executive director, noted that 12.4 million
gallons of ethanol was sold in New Jersey in 1997, compared with 3.7 billion
gallons of gasoline containing MTBE. Those figures could be reversed if MTBE is
phased out, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why not make that additive (ethanol) here, instead of bringing it in from
somewhere else?" Furey said. The study noted that Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
the state's primary supplier of MTBE, spends 7 to 10 cents per gallon to
transport its product from the Midwest to the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Eric Vaughn, president of the Renewable Fuels Association in Washington,
D.C., a lobbying group for the ethanol industry, said it's just a matter of time
before the demand for ethanol in the Northeast requires a production plant in
the region.
</P>
<P>
	   There are currently 55 ethanol plants in the nation, primarily in the
Midwest, according to his group.
</P>
<P>
	   "If it's readily available and if it makes sense to use it, we would use
it," said Jerry Davis, a spokesman for Philadelphia-based Sunoco Inc. The
company uses MTBE-blended gasoline in the Northeast states and ethanol in the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government provides a tax reduction up to 5.4 cents per gallon
for gasoline marketers that use ethanol-blended gasoline.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not a handout to the farmers," said Jim Etsch, president of Grain and
Forage Producers of New Jersey, which represents about 2,300 farmers in New
Jersey. "It's a way for them to create a new market."
</P>
<P>
	   Industry experts say the proposed facility would produce 10 million gallons
of ethanol a year. That would require 3.8 million bushels of corn - about 40
percent of New Jersey's annual production of field corn. It would generate up to
35 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   The state grows enough corn to support a small-scale ethanol plant,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
	   "The biggest challenge is raising the equity to get the plant built," said
Kate A. Smith, an author of the study. "If they can raise that, it appears the
economics are favorable."
</P>
<P>
	   Smith said the facility should be run by a farmer-owned cooperative, and
possibly be built near the Burlington County Resource Recovery Complex in
Columbus. The plant could be fueled with methane gas from the landfill,
supporters say.
</P>
<P>
	   Ralph Shrom, a spokesman for the Burlington County freeholders, said county
officials have not seen the study, but would be interested in hearing more about
the plan.
</P>
<P>
	   The cooperative would require a $12,500 investment from 392 farmers, Smith
said. Many cash-strapped farmers, however, could not afford that. Several
supporters said a public-private partnership would be critical in raising money
for the project.
</P>
<P>
	   "From a policy perspective, certainly this looks good," said Rob Young of
the New Jersey Commerce and Economic Development Growth Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission has low-cost loans available for ventures that create
environmental businesses and those that provide new markets for agricultural
products. This venture would fall under both categories, Young said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 2117 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA: Meat Labeling Could Cost  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Requiring meat to be labeled with the country of origin
could raise costs for consumers and there's no proof it would help U.S.
livestock producers, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In a study requested by Congress, USDA said that mandatory labeling also
could hurt U.S. meat exports if foreign countries impose a similar requirement.
</P>
<P>
	   Some American producers have been pushing for such labeling as a way to curb
imports of Canadian cattle.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA did not put a price tag on a labeling law. The labels themselves could
cost anywhere from $500,000 to $8 million, depending on what cuts of meat the
law applied to. But processors also would have to segregate meat that enters the
country to make sure it's labeled properly, and the cost of doing that ``is
unknown, but could be significant,'' the report said. There would be additional
costs to USDA to enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
	   The department also found no evidence that consumers are willing to pay
higher prices to know where the meat they are buying comes from.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To the contrary, if consumers do distinguish goods depending on their
country of origin, strong incentive exists for industries to act without
government intervention,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meatpackers claim that labeling meat could cost the industry $1 billion a
year. About 10 percent of the beef that Americans eat is imported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2118 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000112.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
