<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Soft-Money Summit  </HEADLINE>
   By MARC HUMBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign manager Wednesday
invited his counterpart on Rudolph Giuliani's political team to negotiate a
mutual ban on the use of unlimited soft-money contributions in their expected
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
	   But Giuliani campaign chief Bruce Teitelbaum, in a letter to Clinton
campaign manager Bill de Blasio, said that before any such negotiations could
take place, the first lady would have to refund such money already spent on her
behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You should also determine how much soft money you have already raised and
publicly declare that none of that money will be used to benefit the Clinton
campaign in any way,'' wrote the aide to the Republican mayor of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading letters, de Blasio criticized Giuliani's fund-raising activities and
said ``we are disappointed that you are apparently rejecting our offer to
meet.''
</P>
<P>
	   Thus far, the national Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee has raised
several hundred thousand dollars in soft-money donations aimed at helping Mrs.
Clinton's campaign in New York. It also spent more than $200,000 to finance
television ads across upstate New York late last year promoting the first lady.
</P>
<P>
	   Under fire for her use of soft money, Mrs. Clinton began pressing Giuliani
last year to agree to a ban on the use of such funding and to disavow
third-party advocacy advertising in the race to succeed Democratic Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
	   While Giuliani has not been actively raising soft money for the Senate race,
he has not ruled out using such funds.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to demanding that Mrs. Clinton pay the cost of the DSCC-financed
ads from her campaign account, Teitelbaum said ``it would also be useful if we
could agree on an ironclad, verifiable method of accountability to ensure that
any agreement we reach will be honored throughout the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   Under federal rules, Senate candidates can accept no more than $2,000 from
individual contributors to spend on their races. But those same contributors can
give unlimited money to political committees such as the DSCC that can then use
it to promote a candidate, as long as they don't directly advocate voting for
that candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
