<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Opposition Founder Quits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A founder of the opposition Democratic Revolution Party
on Wednesday formally resigned from the party, which said he was fired for lack
of discipline.
</P>
<P>
	   The resignation of Porfirio Munoz Ledo, who is seeking the presidency with
another party, is widely seen as the result of his losing a power struggle with
the Democratic Revolution Party's most prominent figure, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
Cardenas is a three-time presidential candidate and was recently mayor of Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
	   The two men haven't spoken to each other since Munoz Ledo three months ago
registered as a candidate in July 2 presidential elections under the banner of
the tiny Party of the Authentic Revolution. That group broke away in the 1940s
from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, but has never posed a
serious threat to it.
</P>
<P>
	   Cardenas and Munoz Ledo themselves are former PRI leaders who quit in 1987.
Munoz Ledo backed Cardenas' 1988 presidential campaign and the two helped found
the Democratic Revolution Party out of the alliance of leftist parties that
formed around that campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing his resignation Wednesday, Munoz Ledo predicted his followers
will leave the party ``in droves'' in coming months because its leadership has
become ``frivolous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
