<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Still Detains U.S. Librarian  </HEADLINE>
   By RENEE SCHOOF Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- More than 100 scholars from around the world petitioned
Chinese leaders Wednesday to free a Pennsylvania librarian who has been detained
for five months and charged with supplying intelligence to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
	   Song Yongyi, a librarian at Dickinson College in Carlisle, Pa., and an
authority on the history and documents of the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, was
detained with his wife Aug. 7 while in China collecting old newspapers.
</P>
<P>
	   Scholars of the Cultural Revolution rely on such documents for their
research, according to the petition, which was to be sent to President Jiang
Zemin and other government leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Continued prosecution of this case will make it impossible for foreign
scholars or Chinese scholars associated with foreign universities to conduct
research in open sources in China with the confidence that they will be safe
from criminal prosecution,'' the petition said.
</P>
<P>
	   Song, who was born in China and spent five years in prison during the
Cultural Revolution, was charged Dec. 24 with ``purchasing or illegally
supplying intelligence for people outside the territory of China.''
</P>
<P>
	   Security officials accused Song of having secret documents, said his wife,
Helen Yao, who was detained for three months and then returned to their home in
Carlisle, about 100 miles west of Philadelphia. But she said that according to
her husband, all the documents had all been published in newspapers and other
open sources.
</P>
<P>
	   China officially says revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung created a ``great
disaster'' when he unleashed chaos to purge his enemies and stir up
revolutionary zeal during the Cultural Revolution, the 10-year political
movement in which millions were persecuted, jailed and killed. But officials
also say that Mao was a great revolutionary who made some mistakes only late in
life.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cultural Revolution remains extremely sensitive in China. Fearing
erosion of its authority, Beijing's communist government has never allowed a
public debate about Mao's and other leaders' errors.
</P>
<P>
	   The petition was signed by 101 historians, political scientists and other
scholars in the United States, Canada, Europe, Australia and even Chinese-ruled
Hong Kong. As more signatures are collected they also will be sent to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
	   Another petition has garnered more than 2,000 signatures from Dickinson
students and faculty members, shoppers in stores where merchants have posted it
and others who have signed an online version at the college's Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   Like millions of other Chinese, Song suffered in the Cultural Revolution. In
1971 he was labeled a ``counterrevolutionary'' for joining a book club with four
other people and spent five years in prison under harsh conditions. He was later
exonerated, but, the petition says, ``still bears the scars of beatings from
that terrible experience.''
</P>
<P>
	   Song is a permanent resident of the United States and had planned to become
a citizen in September. He has been a librarian at Dickinson College since 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Song is not accused of spying, a charge covered under a different section of
Chinese law, said Arlette Ladugui, a researcher with Amnesty International. The
``secrets'' or ``intelligence'' he is accused of gathering could be anything in
China from political gossip to harmless economic information to classified
official documents, many of which circulate widely in China, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The law is so vague that the authorities can do anything they want with
it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-12-00 2156 </TRAILER>
