<DOCNO> APW20000112.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman steered away from controversy in feel-good State of State  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - For most of her time in Trenton, Gov. Christie
Whitman has gone for bold strokes during her State of the State address.
<P>
	   In past years, there were tax cuts, headline-grabbing proposals, and
populist proposals that made lawmakers squirm. Last year, she offered a property
tax rebate.
</P>
<P>
	   But this year's address, Whitman's sixth, steered away from big controversy,
painting a positive picture of the Garden State and pushing apple pie issues
such as luring more high-tech businesses to New Jersey. Whitman may get some
steam from developers about her plan to toughen approval standards for sewer
plants, but not much else promises to raise hackles in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats say they were intrigued by what Whitman left out of the speech.
The state of the state, she said, was "brimming with promise," but there was not
one word about the biggest state government controversy in the year since her
last speech to the people: racial profiling and the State Police.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman made sure not to add more fuel to the furor over long wait times at
auto inspection stations. She gave a passing mention to school construction and
property taxes, but uttered not one word about how the state will pay for new
road construction.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the speech was designed to be not controversial," said Sen. Bernard
Kenny, D-Hudson. "There were certain things that were not stated, issues that
the governor left unaddressed."
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins said lawmakers know all about those issues. He
said leaving them out of the speech allowed Whitman the ability to shine the
spotlight on other areas.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's going to be school construction," Collins said. "Everyone knows
that. There's going to be a Transportation Trust Fund. There's going to be
continuing efforts to do something about health care. So all these things are
understood. What I think she was trying to do today was say, 'Hey, look at these
other things in there."'
</P>
<P>
	   What of those other things?
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman did call for a $96 million state effort to lure high-tech companies
to New Jersey. In total, there would be a $165 million commitment, when federal
aid and private dollars are included. There was a $69 million promise to
increase early childhood education aid. Tighter restrictions on the approval
process for sewer plants could stem development, and state workers would get the
bonus of two hours off a month to volunteer at their children's schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the plans Whitman outlined include a modest dollar commitment.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's a very modest agenda," said Cliff Zukin, a Rutgers University
political scientist. "It is very incremental, and there are small amounts of
money involved. It does not have the boldness of some of her other State of the
States."
</P>
<P>
	   Zukin said Whitman may be realizing that now, more than ever, she must share
the stage with Collins and Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, both of whom are
considering a run for governor next year.
</P>
<P>
	   Thus, while Whitman may be criticized for taking a more modest road, the
alternative is to watch bolder proposals routinely swatted down by Collins and
DiFrancesco. That occasionally happened in past years when Whitman attempted to
ram through items the two leaders didn't like. The days when Whitman could
simply push through much of her agenda are over.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Whitman seems to be reaching out to past critics rather than
making new ones. Environmentalists, for example, seemed cautiously pleased by
her green proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   Zukin said Whitman, as a moderate Republican, "is trying to steer the ship
of state safely" with neither the liberal's big push for government solutions
nor the conservative's zeal to slash government.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman's supporters contend she's slain many of the bigger policy beasts in
past years, saying voters no longer raise angry fists over the cost of auto
insurance and that bigger property tax rebates are already locked in.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, the governor herself talked a lot about preserving her policies,
something she said could have gone by the wayside had she run for the U.S.
Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've come too far to see these accomplishments slip away because we rested
on our laurels," Whitman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 2206 </TRAILER>
