<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Rejects Old Growth Protection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- California forestry officials rejected a demand
Wednesday for an immediate halt to old-growth logging made by dozens
environmentalists, including a protester who lived for two years in a redwood
tree.
</P>
<P>
	   The Board of Forestry, as expected, rejected the petition after a day-long
hearing but agreed to set up a committee of environmentalists, timber owners and
others to study the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Julia ``Butterfly'' Hill, who lived on a tarp-covered platform in a redwood
tree 250 miles north of San Francisco until the Pacific Lumber Co. agreed to
spare the tree last month, said current law allows the cutting of ancient trees,
including redwoods, under loopholes and exemptions abused by harvesters.
</P>
</TEXT>
