<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Joins Wife in N.Y. Home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) -- Bringing along his mother-in-law, President Clinton
hopped on an Air Force jet Wednesday and flew to New York to join his wife,
Hillary, at their new home in Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the president's second visit in a week, and this time he'll stay two
nights. Last week he squeezed in one night amid peace talks between Israel and
Syria. Clinton flew here on a two-engine military plane rather than the jumbo
jet he usually flies, although any plane he rides is designated Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
	   He was accompanied by the first lady's mother, Dorothy Rodham.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Clinton joined his wife in unpacking belongings at the house,
where she moved to establish residency for her Senate bid. This time, Clinton
was staying at the house more for convenience's sake, said White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, he is scheduled to attend a Wall Street conference convened by
Jesse Jackson and decided to take advantage of the house's proximity to New York
City, Lockhart said. Clinton planned to stay overnight in Chappaqua on Thursday
and return to the White House on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After a very full day in New York, he can actually go to his own home
instead of taking up two floors in some very expensive hotel,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
	   After their first night in the house, Mrs. Clinton said she and her husband
had a lot of unpacking and settling in to do. They have lived either in the
Arkansas governor's mansion or the White House since 1983, and must sort through
17 years' worth of stored possessions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a place where they will make a home,'' Lockhart said. ``I think
the first lady will spend a lot of time there, given what she is doing for the
year, but for the president, this is a place in the future.''
</P>
<P>
	   The spokesman added: ``No, the boxes aren't all unpacked yet.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president has said he plans to live in Chappaqua after he leaves office
in January 2001. He also has said he intends to maintain an apartment at his
presidential library in Little Rock, Ark., and plans to work there regularly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
