<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing Israeli Airman May Be Alive  </HEADLINE>
   By HUSSEIN DAKROUB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- The leader of the Hezbollah guerrilla group said
Wednesday that the 14-year-old case of a missing Israeli airman is ``a real
mystery'' and that the group hopes he can be found alive and exchanged for
Lebanese prisoners held by Israel and its allies.
</P>
<P>
	   Sheik Hassan Nasrallah repeated in a television interview previous Hezbollah
assertions that the group continues its efforts to uncover the fate of Ron Arad,
who disappeared in 1986 after his jet was shot down over south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasrallah's comments came hours before the expected release Thursday of
about 25 Lebanese held by Israeli-allied militiamen in south Lebanon and more
than two weeks after five Hezbollah guerrillas were released by Israel -- two
signs of serious efforts to tackle the issue of prisoners and the missing after
the resumption of Syrian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   In the interview with Al-Jazeera, a popular Gulf Arabic-language satellite
news channel, Nasrallah said Arad was not in the hands of the Iranians, the
Syrians or Hezbollah, which is waging a guerrilla war against Israeli forces in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The case has become a real mystery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   There has been speculation that Arad may have died in fighting in 1989,
killed by his captors or even escaped.
</P>
<P>
	   Responding to a question whether he thought Arad was still alive, Nasrallah
said: ``The possibility is still there.''
</P>
<P>
	   Arad's jet was shot down during a bombing raid and guerrillas captured him.
</P>
<P>
	   Hezbollah has repeatedly denied any knowledge of his whereabouts. Officials
have said it is in Hezbollah's interest to find him and trade him for Lebanese
guerrillas and other prisoners held in Israel and by Israeli-allied militiamen
in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   There are 16 Lebanese held in Israel as what human rights groups call
bargaining chips for future negotiations on Israeli MIAs. Another approximately
120 are held at a detention camp in an Israeli-occupied zone of southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Hezbollah's efforts continue to know the fate of this person. When we have
information, we will demand a high price (from the Israelis),'' Nasrallah said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
