<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow May Be Sued in Implant Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- Women opposed to a settlement over silicone breast implants
once made by Dow Corning Co. may sue the company's corporate parents, a judge
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Arthur Spector this week threw out a challenge to an
earlier ruling that opened the way for suits against Midland-based Dow Chemical
Co. and Corning Inc. of Corning, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
	   Spector approved the settlement Nov. 30 after 4 1/2 years of negotiations.
It calls on Dow Corning, a 50-50 joint venture between Dow Chemical and Corning,
to pay out $3.2 billion to settle claims by more than 170,000 women blaming Dow
Corning implants for a wide range of health problems.
</P>
<P>
	   About 94 percent of the 112,774 women who voted on the plan in 1999 approved
it.
</P>
<P>
	   Spector on Dec. 21 issued a ruling saying that women who voted against the
settlement could still sue Dow Chemical and Corning if they chose.
</P>
<P>
	   That ruling was challenged by Dow Chemical and Corning, but in an opinion
dated Monday, Spector said the challenge wrongly assumed that it changed the
terms of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers for Dow Chemical and Corning had filed a notice with Spector on Dec.
29. They argued that his Dec. 21 opinion violated the ban on future lawsuits
against those companies, and said they did not consider the settlement
confirmed, said Dow Corning spokesman T. Michael Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
