<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Stock Plummets After Delay  </HEADLINE>
    By HOPE YEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp.'s shares plummeted 26 percent
Wednesday, as investors reacted to speculation that the New York Stock Exchange
was poised to delist the stock due to the company's delay in releasing financial
reports.
</P>
<P>
	   The NYSE postponed trading for nearly two hours Wednesday morning after
Lehman Brothers analyst Meredith Adler said the exchange was expected to delist
the stock. The NYSE later said it would not delist "at this time," though it was
closely monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokeswoman for the exchange said it had halted activity after hearing
news of a possible delisting, but declined to comment further. Adler later
retracted her statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Rite Aid shares closed trading at $7.87 1/2 at 5 p.m., down 26 percent from
Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's third-largest pharmacy chain announced after the close of
markets Tuesday that it had reached agreement with its lenders on the delay and
planned to seek extensions on Securities and Exchange Commission filings for the
remaining quarterly and annual reports for fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Rite Aid's third quarter report for the period ending Nov. 27 was due
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't have any reason to believe we're delisted, and have no indication
that we would be," said senior vice president Karen Rugen. Exchange officials
"hadn't mentioned a word until they called to ask where the delisting headlines
came from."
</P>
<P>
	   The Camp Hill-based chain has been trying to recover after financial woes
sent the company's stock tumbling by more than 80 percent in a year. Former top
executive Martin L. Grass was ousted in October, and a new team led by CEO
Robert Miller has pledged to improve profitability with stricter financial
controls and strategic marketing.
</P>
<P>
	   Rite Aid also has switched auditing firms and a restatement of its earnings
for the past three years was expected to result in a $500 million reduction.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts have said the chain's delay in financial reports may be troubling
in light of December same-store sales figures showing a "poor" 5.9 percent
increase, compared to the double-digit growth of Walgreen's and CVS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
