<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton tells Letterman she couldn't resist following him  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Quipping that she finally agreed to take the hot seat
next to David Letterman because she lost a bet with Tipper Gore, a nervous
Hillary Rodham Clinton appeared a pretty good match for the late-night host on
Wednesday.
<P>
	   The first lady made her first visit to the Late Show, a stop that followed
weeks of the host taking pot shots at Mrs. Clinton over her plan to run for U.S.
Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman's trademark sarcastic wit was never turned on the first lady, and
he even took a moment to laud her for appearing after hearing him joke about her
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have to give this woman a tremendous amount of credit for just showing
up," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Confronted with the first lady in the flesh, Letterman started by lobbing
her a softball, asking her to "tell us a little bit about yourself."
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton smiled and told Letterman she grew up in the Midwest - as he
did - has a mother named Dorothy - as he does - and just couldn't resist the
temptation to follow him to New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton actually made a joke at Letterman's expense, when he was asking
her about her new home in Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every idiot in the universe is going to drive by honking now," Letterman
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Was that you?" Mrs. Clinton asked.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman has made a running gag of Mrs. Clinton, calling her a carpetbagger
from Arkansas seeking political opportunity in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton's likely opponent in the U.S. Senate race, Republican New York
City Mayor Rudy Giuliani, has been on the show 14 times, chatting up Letterman
about the Yankees, Mrs. Clinton and life in New York. He even got some laughs in
a few comedy skits.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton admitted to being "just a little" nervous, but told Letterman:
"I knew if I was going to run for Senate, I was going to have to come and sit in
this chair and talk to the big guy."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's name came up during the interview, as Letterman asked Mrs.
Clinton what she thought of the mayor and if he had the temperament to be a
senator.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's done a lot of stuff as mayor but I think being senator is a different
kind of job. A senator can't go arrest a homeless person," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   She aced Letterman's New York quiz, correctly identifying the state bird
(bluebird) and the state tree (sugar maple).
</P>
<P>
	   Her top 10 reasons for appearing on the show included "I lost a bet with
Tipper" and "If Dan Quayle did it, how hard could it be?"
</P>
<P>
	   The show was to air Wednesday night at 11:30 EST.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-12-00 2247 </TRAILER>
