<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Minister Hails Morocco King  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy hailed Morocco's
new king, Mohammed VI, as a ``man of peace'' Wednesday at the start of a
four-day visit aimed at building confidence between the two countries, media
reports said.
</P>
<P>
	   After a two-hour visit between the two at the royal palace in Rabat, Levy
said the king was ``ready to continue his father's work'' in the Mideast peace
process, the official MAP news agency said. Levy is the first Israeli official
to visit since King Mohammed came to the throne in July.
</P>
<P>
	   Morocco and Israel have low-level diplomatic relations and Levy's trip
suggests that Morocco is not about to forgo its discreet but important role in
the Middle East peace process despite the death of King Hassan II, who broke
Arab world taboos to hold secret talks with Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
	   MAP quoted Levy as saying Mohammed was ready to play the role of
intermediary in the peace process and had a good knowledge of the problems. He
said the meeting was frank and warm, and praised the ``young wise king whom we
respect and encourage.''
</P>
<P>
	   Levy met other Moroccan officials during the visit, which is meant to pave
the way for a trip to the kingdom by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel's Channel Two TV reported that Mohammed invited Barak to visit
Morocco during Wednesday's meeting. It said Levy also extended an invitation to
the king to visit Israel and Mohammed said he would like to.
</P>
<P>
	   The trip was also an emotional homecoming for 61-year-old Levy, who left
Morocco for Israel at age 20 and has only been back once, briefly, to attend the
funeral of Hassan in July.
</P>
<P>
	   As a young immigrant in Israel, Levy worked his way up from ditch digger and
union activist to political leader. Throughout his political career, first in
the hawkish Likud Party and then in Barak's moderate One Israel alignment, he
presented himself as a champion of Sephardi Jews with Mideastern roots, who have
long complained about discrimination by Israel's European-born elites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
