<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maine House Fire Kills Three Kids  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITY, Maine (AP) -- Seven-year-old triplets boys died when their house
caught fire Wednesday afternoon, authorities said. Their mother escaped with
another child and yelled to firefighters that her sons were still inside, but
firefighters couldn't reach them.
</P>
<P>
	   Firefighters were recovering the bodies of the three brothers from the
gutted home late Wednesday night, Stephen McCausland of the Maine Public Safety
Department said.
</P>
<P>
	   Unity Fire Chief Dennis A. Turner identified the triplets as Josh, Marcus
and Brydon Freyer.
</P>
<P>
	   The mother, Carmen Freyer, 28, was hospitalized in good condition, and the
other child was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
	   John Dean, the state fire marshal, said after the fire was extinguished that
the house ``still has walls and part of the roof, but it's destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said it was too early to tell the cause of the fire.
</P>
<P>
	   Waldo County Sheriff Robert M. Jones, 48, who responded to the call for
firefighters, collapsed near the home and later died at Maine General Medical
Center in Waterville, a hospital spokesman said. The cause of death was not
available, but McCausland said it was believed to be a heart attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
